{"title_page": "Douglas Melamed", "text_new": "[[File:Doug Melamed at Berkman Center 2.jpg|thumb|Doug Melamed at the [[Berkman Center for Internet & Society]] at [[Harvard University]].]]\n'''A. Douglas Melamed''' (born December 3, 1945) is an American legal scholar specializing in [[antitrust law]]. Since 2014, Melamed has been a professor at [[Stanford Law School]].<ref name=\":0\">\"[https://law.stanford.edu/directory/a-douglas-melamed/]\"</ref> He was previously Senior Vice President and General Counsel at [[Intel Corporation]] and the chair of the Antitrust and Competition Practice Group at the law firm of [[WilmerHale]].<ref name=\":1\">\"[http://www.intel.com/pressroom/kits/bios/melamed.htm Intel Executive Bio]\", Retrieved April 30, 2010</ref> <ref name=\":2\">https://law.stanford.edu/directory/a-douglas-melamed/</ref>\n\n== Early Life & Academics ==\nArthur Douglas Melamed was born on December 3, 1945, to Arthur C. Melamed and Helen Melamed in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Melamed graduated from [[Yale University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1967, then from [[Harvard Law School]] with a [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1970, where he was an editor on the ''[[Harvard Law Review]]''.\n\n== Career ==\nAfter law school, he clerked for one year with Judge [[Charles M. Merrill]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]. He became well-known in the field of [[law and economics]] for his views on the natural evolution of property rights as a co-author with [[Guido Calabresi]] a law review article on the different types of property rights accorded by tort rules and property rules in ''[[Property Rules, Liability Rules and Inalienability: One View of the Cathedral]]''.  He served in the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]]'s [[antitrust]] division under [[Joel Klein]] and was later Acting Assistant Attorney General during the Clinton Administration.<ref>http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/1996/Oct96/499at.htm</ref><ref>http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2001_April_26/ai_73670141</ref> He then began working as the chair of the Antitrust and Competition Practice Group at the law firm of [[WilmerHale]].<ref name=\":1\" /> From 2009 to 2014, Melamed was the Senior Vice\u00a0President and General Counsel of Intel Corporation; there, he oversaw Intel\u2019s legal, corporate affairs, and government affairs departments.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2014, he became, and still is, a professor at [[Stanford Law School]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Publicity ==\nThroughout his career, Melamed has been interviewed by the media, mainly about antitrust law. In 2015, [https://www.law.com/corpcounsel/?slreturn=20190518155047 Corporate Counsel] covered a story on Melamed titled <u>'The Michael Jordan' of Law now Focuses on Teaching.</u><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/print-edition/2015/03/13/a-douglas-melamed-called-the-michael-jordan-of-law.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> From May 2019 to June 2019, in particular, Melamed was interviewed by a variety of news outlets, including [[CNBC]], as some antirust academics, regulators, and members of the public became concerned by the threat to competition large tech platforms may pose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/video/t/facebooks-crypto-partners-signal-it-passes-security-test-analyst/vp-AAD4Dpp|title=Facebook's crypto partners signal it passes security test: Analyst|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melamed, Douglas}}\n[[Category:Law and economics scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Intel people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Scholars of competition law]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Attorneys General for the Antitrust Division]]\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Doug Melamed at Berkman Center 2.jpg|thumb|Doug Melamed at the [[Berkman Center for Internet & Society]] at [[Harvard University]].]]\n'''A. Douglas Melamed''' (born December 3, 1945) is an American legal scholar specializing in [[antitrust law]]. Since 2014, Melamed has been a professor at [[Stanford Law School]].<ref name=\":0\">\"[https://law.stanford.edu/directory/a-douglas-melamed/]\"</ref> He was previously Senior Vice President and General Counsel at [[Intel Corporation]] and the chair of the Antitrust and Competition Practice Group at the law firm of [[WilmerHale]].<ref name=\":1\">\"[http://www.intel.com/pressroom/kits/bios/melamed.htm Intel Executive Bio]\", Retrieved April 30, 2010</ref> <ref name=\":2\">https://law.stanford.edu/directory/a-douglas-melamed/</ref>\n\n== Early Life & Academics ==\nArthur Douglas Melamed was born on December 3, 1945, to Arthur C. Melamed and Helen Melamed in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Melamed graduated from [[Yale University]] with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in 1967, then from [[Harvard Law School]] with a [[Juris Doctor]] degree in 1970, where he was an editor on the ''[[Harvard Law Review]]''.\n\n== Career ==\nAfter law school, he clerked for one year with Judge [[Charles M. Merrill]] on the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]. He became well-known in the field of [[law and economics]] for his views on the natural evolution of property rights as a co-author with [[Guido Calabresi]] a law review article on the different types of property rights accorded by tort rules and property rules in ''[[Property Rules, Liability Rules and Inalienability: One View of the Cathedral]]''.  He served in the [[United States Department of Justice|Justice Department]]'s [[antitrust]] division under [[Joel Klein]] and was later Acting Assistant Attorney General during the Clinton Administration.<ref>http://www.usdoj.gov/opa/pr/1996/Oct96/499at.htm</ref><ref>http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2001_April_26/ai_73670141</ref> He then began working as the chair of the Antitrust and Competition Practice Group at the law firm of [[WilmerHale]].<ref name=\":1\" /> From 2009 to 2014 Douglas was the Senior Vice\u00a0President and General Counsel of Intel Corporation, there he oversaw Intel\u2019s legal, corporate affairs, and government affairs departments.<ref name=\":2\" /> Then in 2014, he became, and still is a professor at [[Stanford Law School]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Publicity ==\nDoug Melamed, throughout his career, was interviewed for articles and TV mainly about antitrust law. In 2015 [https://www.law.com/corpcounsel/?slreturn=20190518155047 Corporate Counsel] covered a story on Douglas titled <u>'The Michael Jordan' of Law now Focuses on Teaching.</u><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/print-edition/2015/03/13/a-douglas-melamed-called-the-michael-jordan-of-law.html|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref> Doug's expertise with antitrust law has become more relevant in May-June of 2019 with him going on and being interviewed for a variety of news outlets like [[CNBC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/video/t/facebooks-crypto-partners-signal-it-passes-security-test-analyst/vp-AAD4Dpp|title=Facebook's crypto partners signal it passes security test: Analyst|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Melamed, Douglas}}\n[[Category:Law and economics scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Intel people]]\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Scholars of competition law]]\n[[Category:United States Assistant Attorneys General for the Antitrust Division]]\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jammiejamie", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammatical clean-up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Douglas_Melamed"}
{"title_page": "Carolyn Rodgers", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Carolyn Rodgers\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = Carolyn Marie Rodgers\n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date|1940|12|14}} \n| birth_place      = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date       =  {{Death date and age|2010|04|02|1940|12|14}}\n| death_place      = Chicago, Illinois\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Writer\n| language         = \n| nationality      = American\n| education        = [[Roosevelt University]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''Paper Soul'' (1968); ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969)\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n\n}}\n{{African American topics sidebar}}\n'''Carolyn Marie Rodgers''' (December 14, 1940<ref>According to [http://authorities.loc.gov/webvoy.htm Library of Congress Authority Files] her birth year was 1940, although their source seems to be ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref> &ndash; April 2, 2010) was a [[Chicago]]-based writer.<ref name=ny>Weber, Bruce (April 19, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/19/books/19rodgers.html \"Carolyn Rodgers, Poet, Is Dead at 69\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> The youngest of four, Rodgers had two sisters and a brother, born to Clarence and Bazella Rodgers. Rodgers was also a founder of one of America's oldest and largest black presses, [[Third World Press]]. She got her start in the literary circuit as a young woman studying under [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning poet [[Gwendolyn Brooks]] in the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]] of Chicago.\n\nLater, Rodgers began writing her own works, which grappled with black identity and culture in the late 1960s. Rodgers was a leading voice of the [[Black Arts Movement]] (BAM) and the author of nine books, including ''How I got Ovah'' (1975). She was also an essayist and critic, and her work has been described as delivered in a language rooted in a black female perspective<ref>Shadduck, Lani, [http://www.huliq.com/9502/92676/funeral-held-chicago-poet-founding-black-press \"Funeral Held For Chicago Poet Founding Black Press\"], ''Huliq'', April 14, 2010.</ref> that wove strands of [[feminism]], [[black power]], [[spirituality]], and self-consciousness into a sometimes raging, sometimes ruminative search for identity. She also wrote deeply on the subject of mother/daughter relationships, particularly focusing on feminist, matriarchal issues.\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn in the [[Douglas, Chicago#Bronzeville|Bronzeville]] neighborhood in the South Side of [[Chicago, Illinois]], Rodgers was encouraged from a young age to pursue music, and learned to play guitar and composed music for much of her life. She kept a journal throughout adolescence in which she explored poetry, but did not take writing seriously until she began college. Rodgers first attended college at the [[University of Illinois]] in 1960, but transferred in 1961 to Chicago's [[Roosevelt University]], where she earned her BA degree in 1965. She later earned an MA in English from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1980. Rodgers is most well known for her writing contributions to the [[Black Arts Movement]] (BAM). Rodgers first became involved in writing during that period while attending Writers Workshops by the [[Organization of Black American Culture]] (OBAC), of which she was an active member from 1967 to 1971.<ref>[[Margaret Busby|Busby, Margaret]], \"Carolyn Rodgers\", ''[[Daughters of Africa]]'', 1992, pp. 544\u201346.</ref> The organization sought to promote city involvement and inclusion of the arts in the city of Chicago, which Rodgers was eager to participate in.\n\nShe became distinctive as a new black woman poet in the 1960s with the publication of her first two books, ''Paper Soul'' and ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (Chicago: Third World Press, 1969). Following the national success of ''Paper Soul'', Rodgers was awarded the first Conrad Kent Rivers Memorial Fund Award. Rodgers also won the Poet Laureate Award from the Society of Midland Authors in 1970. She then went on to receive an award from the [[National Endowment of the Arts]], following the publication of ''Songs of a Blackbird''. In 1980, Rodgers won the Carnegie Writer's Grant. She won the Television Gospel Tribute in 1982 and the PEN Grant in 1987.\n\nIn 2009, Rodgers was inducted into the International Literary Hall of Fame for Writers of African Descent at the Gwendolyn Brooks Center for Black Literature and Creative Writing.  In 2012, Rodgers was inducted into the Chicago Literary Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://chicagoliteraryhof.org/inductees/profile/carolyn-rodgers |title=Carolyn Rodgers |date=2012 |website=Chicago Literary Hall of Fame |language=en |access-date=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Poetry and poetics==\n;Early work\nRodgers's poetry is recognizable for its themes, which included identity, religion, and revolution, and her own use of [[free verse]] street slang and concern with feminine issues. In her early days, black revolutionary themes and \"cuss words\" wove through some poems.\n\nShe used slang and heartfelt language to write about love, lust, body image, family, religion, and the grace of human kindness. In her earliest writings such as ''Paper Soul'' (1968) and ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969), her revolutionary ideas about women's roles conflicted with the more traditional ideas of the African-American culture. She was criticized for her use of profanity, which male leaders of BAM found inappropriate for a woman.\n\n[[Haki R. Madhubuti]], chair, publisher and fellow founder of Third World Press, told the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' that: \"She would take no quarter from insults, or downgrading her writing as a woman ... Her writing could stand by itself.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article |title=\"CAROLYN M. RODGERS: 'Great poet' born of '60s\". |access-date=2010-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418194447/http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article |archive-date=2010-04-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSo while Rodgers's ''Songs of a Blackbird'' includes themes about survival, mother-daughter conflicts, and street life, it also criticizes those who dishonor her use of profanity. In her poem \"The Last M.F.\" she fights back:\n\n<blockquote>\nthey say,<br />\nthat I should not use the word<br />\nmothafucka anymo<br />\nin my poetry or in any speech I give.<br />\nthey say,<br />\nthat I must and can only say it to myself<br />\nas the new Black Womanhood suggests<br />\na softer self<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nIn \"The Last M.F.\" Rodgers says she will stop using profanity but continues using the \"menacing word\" at least 11 times throughout the poem, blatantly making jabs at men and their ideas of how a woman should speak and behave. Here too, Rodgers mocks the new Black Womanhood which she believes, paradoxically, promotes women to be silent.\n\n;Later work\n\nRodgers was a revolutionary influence during the Civil Rights Movement for the black community and oppressed women. She was not afraid to stand up and fight for herself and her people, and she welcomed controversy:\n\n<blockquote>\nlet uh revolution come<br />\nstate of peace is not known to me<br />\nanyway\n</blockquote>\n\nHer poetry centered on declaring what black people needed to do to overcome their low status in society. She also elocuted that women not stand for the poor treatment they received from men, black or white.\n\nOther volumes of work such as ''The Heart as Ever Green'' (1978) and ''How I Got Ovah'' (1975) also reflect on feminine issues such as female identity, women's roles in society, and the relationships between mothers and daughters. However, ''How I Got Ovah'' exhibits a more crafted tendency than previous books, along with being more autobiographical and transformative. Personal voice pervades the poems of ''How I Got Ovah''.<ref name=McElroy>{{cite web|last=McElroy|first=Hilda|title=About Carolyn Rodgers|url=//www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/about.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rodgers develops the individual tone so well that the reader experiences a kinship with the poet and her subject matter (McElroy). The poem \"how i got ovah\" (from which the book receives its title) serves as an example of this deep personal voice. Rodgers begins an intimate revealing of personal survival with the opening lines:\n\n<blockquote>\ni can tell you<br />\nabout them<br />\ni have shaken rivers<br />\nout of my eyes.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nRodgers carries the reader through experiences of crossing rivers while \"eyelash deep,\" picturing the engulfing of ideas and socially accepted expectations of her as a black woman. She encounters ancestors through nature with their \"rich dark root fingers,\" showing appreciation for her heritage. At the end of the poem, she has found secret strength through staying afloat:\n\n<blockquote>\nthough i shivered<br />\nwas wet with cold<br />\nand wanted to sink down<br />\nand float as water, yea--<br />\ni can tell you.<br />\ni have shaken rivers<br />\nout of my eyes.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nEstella M. Sales concludes that, in this poem, Rodgers \"comes to recognize ... her own inner voice, her ancestral rootedness, her Christian faith, and her parental support\".<ref name=Sales>{{cite web|last=Sales|first=Estella|title=About Carolyn Rodgers|url=//www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/about.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She finds a way to \"bridg[e] the separating waters\" and \"reconcile ... contradictions\" in the \"seemingly dichotomous entities of black life.\"\n\nBy the 1970s, Rodgers was distilling her language and militant persona into poetry that was deeply concerned with religion, God, and the quest for inner beauty. The change from militant views to more religious views can be seen in her 1975 poem \"and when the revolution came.\" The repetition in the first four verses show a constancy in the black church communities:\n\n<blockquote>\nand they just kept on going to church<br />\ngittin on they knees and praying<br />\nand tithing and building and buying<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nThe implied criticism here is that while the militants were busy telling other black people how they should live to improve their lives, the black church communities were busy making black communities better. In stanzas 1\u20135, Rodgers notes that the militants try to change the hair styles, the dress, any association with whites, the food eaten by blacks, and what the militants termed \"white man's religion\", According to Friedrike Kaufel, these changes \"are petty ones\".<ref name=Kaufel>{{cite web|last=Kaufel|first=Friederike|title=On \"when the revolution came\"|url=http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/revolution.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate= November 11, 2012}}</ref>  These changes were quietly and passively resisted by the church members, who continued \"going to church\" and \"tithing and building and praying\" Stanzas 6\u20138 show the militants wanting to build new institutions for black children, and realizing that while the militants were only using words, in the form of orders, to make changes, the churches were actually making needed changes in black neighborhoods. Rodgers shows further implicates the oppressive actions of the militants, and celebrates the communal sanctity of the black church in Stanza 8:\n\n<blockquote>\nand the church folks said, yeah.<br />\nwe been waiting fo you militants<br />\nto realize that the church is an eternal rock<br />\nnow why don't you militants jest come on in<br />\nwe been waitin for you<br />\nwe can show you how to build<br />\nanything that needs building<br />\nand while we're on our knees, at that.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nIn these actions, the church members have long before reached the state of solidarity among themselves that the militants finally call for in Stanza 6.<ref name=Kaufel />\n\nAnother example of Rodgers's turn to more personal and religious matters is her poem \"mama's God\":<ref>\"mama's God\", in Cary Nelson (ed.), ''Anthology of Modern American Poetry''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2000.</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n:mama's God never was no white man.\nher My Jesus, Sweet Jesus never was neither.<br />\n::the color they had was the color of\nher aches and trials, the tribulations of her heart<br />\n:mama never had no savior that would turn\n::his back on her because she was black\n:::when mama prayed, she knew who she\n::was praying to and who she was praying to\n:::didn't and ain't got\n::::no color.\n</blockquote>\n\t\t\nHere Rodgers points once again to the underlying foundation to which African Americans had been clinging even before the Black Arts Movement. By using her mother as the major reference point, the poet establishes these ideas as coming before the militants. Just as the church-goers had already been calling each other brother and sister according to a higher authority, Rodgers perceives an authority to which she can appeal who \"ain't got no color\". She renders powerless the restrictions placed on her by the color of her skin.\n\nIf this cannot be characterized as transformative, nonetheless her work seems to have shifted from a collective black perspective in her early work to an individual one<ref name=ny/> in her later writings. Consequently, by the time she publishes ''The Heart as Ever Green'' in 1978, Rodgers is incorporating earlier themes of feminism and human dignity in her poems, along with newer or more pronounced themes of love and Christianity. Some readers and cultural observers do not recognize a break or rupture from Rodgers's past in her later work. For them, Rodgers's spiritual progress in her poetry still brings a radical infusion. Even in her later poetry, we can still break open into a vision uniquely situated in a poetics that remains strident, militant and experimental.\n\n==Fiction and literary criticism==\nRodgers earned an appreciative and crucial audience through her fiction and literary criticism. Her short stories, which are often overlooked, ultimately suggest themes of survival and adaptability, and are directed to a predominately black audience. Rodgers was successful in providing contemporary black readers with solace and encouragement to persist through her use of well-crafted language. Marsha C. Vick points out some of the reasons why Rodger's fiction was so influential at the time of publication, particularly focusing on her aesthetic appeal:\n\n<blockquote>\nThe same insight and searching analysis that distinguish her poetry are integral to Rodgers's short fiction and her literary criticism. She portrays in her short fiction the ordinary and overlooked people in everyday African American life and emphasizes the theme of survival. Many consider her critical essay \"Black Poetry\u2014Where It's At\" (1969) to be the best essay on the work of the \"new black poets\". In it, she aesthetically evaluates contemporary African American poetry and sets up preliminary criteria of appraisal.<ref>[http://www.answers.com/topic/carolyn-m-rodgers Carolyn M. Rodgers: Information from Answers.com]</ref> </blockquote>\n\nAccording to poet [[Lorenzo Thomas (poet)|Lorenzo Thomas]], Carolyn Rodgers proposed new [[prosodic]] categories specific to black poetry. Thomas points out that this kind of essay (or [[manifesto]]) outlining a vision statement to spur militant and creative inquiry (but most particularly \"Black Poetry\u2014Where It's At\") was widely disseminated and discussed among poets of that time.<ref>Thomas, Lorenzo. ''Extraordinary Measures: Afrocentric Modernism and Twentieth-Century American Poetry.'' Tuscaloosa and London: The University of Alabama Press, 2000. p. 211.</ref> Thomas then goes on to point out that: \"Her [Rodgers's] ideas were based on what Jerry W. Ward, Jr., has called \"culturally anchored SPEECH ACTS and Reader/Hearer Response.\" Her position on not only African-Americans' rights, but women's rights, was clear in the content and language in her poems. \"She's demonstrably feminine because she's sexy,\"<ref name=Gender>From ''Gender and The Poetics of Excess: Moments of Brocade''. Copyright \u00a9 1997 by the University Press of Mississippi.</ref> and her lines in \"The Last M.F.\" show this:\n\n<blockquote>\ni say,<br />\nthat i am soft, and you can subpoena my man, put him<br /> \non trial, and he will testify that i am<br /> \nsoft in the right places at the right times<br />\nand often we are so reserved, i have nothing to say.<ref name=Gender />\n</blockquote>\n\nDespite recognition for her efforts in the Black Arts Movement, Rodgers' unconventional use of language, especially for a woman, was frowned upon by some of her readers, most notably men. Her consistent use of profanity wasn't seen as \"ladylike\". Also, she urged her fellow black women to be strong and state clearly what they wanted. She prompted them not to acquiesce to the demands and expectations of white people, but just as important, she made it clear that black women should not be submissive to men in general; \"she registers her scorn for black men who censor women.\"<ref name=Gender />\n\n==Sidelights==\n*In addition to writing poetry, Rodgers wrote numerous short stories. Her play ''Love'' was produced Off-Broadway by [[Woodie King Jr.]], a father of the Black Theatre movement.\n*Rodgers had a career as a teacher and educator, and taught at [[Columbia College Chicago]], [[University of Washington]], Malcolm X Community College, [[Albany State University|Albany State College]], and [[Indiana University]].\n*Rodgers was a member of the [[Organization of Black American Culture]] (OBAC), which promotes cultural activity of the arts.\n*Rodgers also owned her own publishing firm, Eden Press.\n*Rodgers was deeply influenced by [[Hoyt Fuller]], the founder of Chicago's OBAC, after meeting him while working as a social worker at the YMCA (1963\u201369).  \n*Rodgers worked as a book critic for the ''Chicago Daily News'' and as a columnist for the ''Milwaukee Courier'' \n*In December 1967, Carolyn Rodgers met with Haki R. Madhubuti and Johari Amini in the basement of a South Side apartment to found Third World Press, an outlet for [[African-American literature]]. By 2007, the company continues to thrive in a multimillion-dollar facility. Over the years, Rodgers would publish works for friend and Pulitzer Prize\u2013winning author Gwendolyn Brooks, as well as [[Sonia Sanchez]], [[Sterling Plumpp]] and [[Pearl Cleage]]. Rodgers' work has been quoted by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and performed by [[Ruby Dee]] and [[Ossie Davis]].<ref>[http://www.blackamericaweb.com/?q=articles/news/moving_america_news/18087 Little Known Black History Fact: Carolyn Rodgers]</ref>\n*Was at the forefront of the Civil Rights Movement and served as a great influence for Black Consciousness, sparking \"a new generation of African Americans [who questioned] the political relevance of Black Christian organizations, beliefs, and practices.\"<ref>Gilks, Cheryl T. \"Plenty Good Room: Adaption in a Changing Black Church.\" ''The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science,'' vol. 558, no. 1, Americans and Religions in the Twenty-First Century, Summer 1998, pp. 101\u2013121.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Morning Glory: Poems'' (1989)\n*''Finite Forms'' (1985)\n*''Eden and Other Poems'' (1983)\n*''The Heart as Ever Green'' (1978)\n*''How I Got Ovah: New and Selected Poems'' (1975)\n*''2 Love Raps'' (1969)\n*''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969)\n*''A Statistic, Trying to Make it Home'' (1969)\n*''Paper Soul (1968)\n*''Blackbird in a Cage'' (1967)\n\n===Further reading===\n*Bettye J. Parker-Smith, \"Running Wild in Her Soul: The Poetry of Carolyn Rodgers\", in Mari Evans (ed.), ''Black Women Writers (1950\u20131980): A Critical Evaluation'', 1984, pp. 393\u2013410.\n*Jean Davis, \"Carolyn M. Rodgers\", in Trudier Harris and Thadious M. Davis (eds), ''Dictionary of Literary Biography'', vol. 41, ''Afro-American Poets since 1955'', 1985, pp. 287\u201395.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n;Additional references\n*Nelson, Carrie. ''Anthology of Modern American Poetry''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2000, pp. 1095\u20131097.\n*Thomas, Lorenzo. ''Extraordinary Measures: Afrocentric Modernism and Twentieth-Century American Poetry''. Tuscaloosa and London: The University of Alabama Press, 2000.\n\n==External links==\n\n;Sites, exhibits, and artist pages\n*[http://voices.cla.umn.edu/artistpages/rodgers_carolyn.php Carolyn M. Rodgers: Voices from the Gaps]\n*[http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/rodgers.htm Modern American Poetry Site: Carolyn M. Rodgers]\n\n;Tributes and obituaries\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/04/13/carolyn-m-rodgers-dead-at_n_536569.html \"Carolyn M. Rodgers Dead at 69, Chicago Poet and Writer Helped Found Black Press\"], ''[[Huffington Post]]'', April 13, 2010.\n*[http://ronsilliman.blogspot.com/2010/04/carolyn-m.html Carolyn M. Rodgers 1941 \u2014 2010] This \"cyber-[[tombeau]]\" at ''Silliman's Blog'' by poet [[Ron Silliman]] includes comments, tributes, and links. Appears to have listed the birth year incorrectly as 1941\n*[http://jstheater.blogspot.com/2010/04/rip-poem-carolyn-rodgers.html RIP+Poem], April 2010; this tribute piece includes Rodgers' poem \"Poem for Some Black Women\".\n*[http://www.thatblackgirlsite.com/thatblackgirlblogs/why-the-words-and-works-of-carolyn-m-rodgers-matter/ Why the Words and Works of Carolyn M. Rodgers Matter]\n*[http://www.bvblackspin.com/2010/04/14/carolyn-m-rodgers-dead-at-69/ Black Arts Movement Star Carolyn M. Rodgers Dead at 69]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100418194447/http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article CAROLYN M. RODGERS: 'Great poet' born of '60s] reads the [[byline]]: \"Her work 'affirmed the voice of black women -- of everyday black women'.\"\n*[http://www.blackamericaweb.com/?q=articles/news/moving_america_news/18087 Little Known Black History Fact: Carolyn Rodgers]\n\n;Poems and other writings\n*[http://somemeofbeauty.blogspot.com/2005/11/some-me-of-beauty.html \"Some Me of Beauty\"], Rodgers' poem from her 1975 collection ''How I Got Ovah''.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodgers, Carolyn}}\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Roosevelt University alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American women writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:African-American publishers (people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = Carolyn Rodgers\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = Carolyn Marie Rodgers\n| birth_date       =  {{Birth date|1940|12|14}} \n| birth_place      = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n| death_date       =  {{Death date and age|2010|04|02|1940|12|14}}\n| death_place      = Chicago, Illinois\n| resting_place    = \n| occupation       = Writer\n| language         = \n| nationality      = American\n| education        = [[Roosevelt University]]\n| alma_mater       = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = ''Paper Soul'' (1968); ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969)\n| spouse           = <!-- or: | spouses = -->\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = \n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n\n}}\n{{African American topics sidebar}}\n'''Carolyn Marie Rodgers''' (December 14, 1940<ref>According to [http://authorities.loc.gov/webvoy.htm Library of Congress Authority Files] her birth year was 1940, although their source seems to be ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref> &ndash; April 2, 2010) was a [[Chicago]]-based writer.<ref name=ny>Weber, Bruce (April 19, 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/19/books/19rodgers.html \"Carolyn Rodgers, Poet, Is Dead at 69\"], ''The New York Times''.</ref> The youngest of four, Rodgers had two sisters and a brother, born to Clarence and Bazella Rodgers. Rodgers was also a founder of one of America's oldest and largest black presses, [[Third World Press]]. She got her start in the literary circuit as a young woman studying under [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning poet [[Gwendolyn Brooks]] in the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]] of Chicago.\n\nLater, Rodgers began writing her own works, which grappled with black identity and culture in the late 1960s. Rodgers was a leading voice of the [[Black Arts Movement]] (BAM) and the author of nine books, including ''How I got Ovah'' (1975). She was also an essayist and critic, and her work has been described as delivered in a language rooted in a black female perspective<ref>Shadduck, Lani, [http://www.huliq.com/9502/92676/funeral-held-chicago-poet-founding-black-press \"Funeral Held For Chicago Poet Founding Black Press\"], ''Huliq'', April 14, 2010.</ref> that wove strands of [[feminism]], [[black power]], [[spirituality]], and self-consciousness into a sometimes raging, sometimes ruminative search for identity. She also wrote deeply on the subject of mother/daughter relationships, particularly focusing on feminist, matriarchal issues.\n\n==Life and work==\nBorn in the [[Douglas, Chicago#Bronzeville|Bronzeville]] neighborhood in the South Side of [[Chicago, Illinois]], Rodgers was encouraged from a young age to pursue music, and learned to play guitar and composed music for much of her life. She kept a journal throughout adolescence in which she explored poetry, but did not take writing seriously until she began college. Rodgers first attended college at the [[University of Illinois]] in 1960, but transferred in 1961 to Chicago's [[Roosevelt University]], where she earned her BA degree in 1965. She later earned a MA in English from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1980. Rodgers is most well known for her writing contributions to the [[Black Arts Movement]] (BAM). Rodgers first became involved in writing during that period while attending Writers Workshops by the [[Organization of Black American Culture]] (OBAC), of which she was an active member from 1967 to 1971.<ref>[[Margaret Busby|Busby, Margaret]], \"Carolyn Rodgers\", ''[[Daughters of Africa]]'', 1992, pp. 544\u201346.</ref> The organization sought to promote city involvement and inclusion of the arts in the city of Chicago, which Rodgers was eager to participate in.\n\nShe became distinctive as a new black woman poet in the 1960s with the publication of her first two books, ''Paper Soul'' and ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (Chicago: Third World Press, 1969). Following the national success of ''Paper Soul'', Rodgers was awarded the first Conrad Kent Rivers Memorial Fund Award. Rodgers also won the Poet Laureate Award from the Society of Midland Authors in 1970. She then went on to receive an award from the [[National Endowment of the Arts]], following the publication of ''Songs of a Blackbird''. In 1980, Rodgers won the Carnegie Writer's Grant. She won the Television Gospel Tribute in 1982 and the PEN Grant in 1987.\n\nIn 2009, Rodgers was inducted into the International Literary Hall of Fame for Writers of African Descent at the Gwendolyn Brooks Center for Black Literature and Creative Writing.  In 2012, Rodgers was inducted into the Chicago Literary Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://chicagoliteraryhof.org/inductees/profile/carolyn-rodgers |title=Carolyn Rodgers |date=2012 |website=Chicago Literary Hall of Fame |language=en |access-date=October 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Poetry and poetics==\n;Early work\nRodgers's poetry is recognizable for its themes, which included identity, religion, and revolution, and her own use of [[free verse]] street slang and concern with feminine issues. In her early days, black revolutionary themes and \"cuss words\" wove through some poems.\n\nShe used slang and heartfelt language to write about love, lust, body image, family, religion, and the grace of human kindness. In her earliest writings such as ''Paper Soul'' (1968) and ''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969), her revolutionary ideas about women's roles conflicted with the more traditional ideas of the African-American culture. She was criticized for her use of profanity, which male leaders of BAM found inappropriate for a woman.\n\n[[Haki R. Madhubuti]], chair, publisher and fellow founder of Third World Press, told the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' that: \"She would take no quarter from insults, or downgrading her writing as a woman ... Her writing could stand by itself.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article |title=\"CAROLYN M. RODGERS: 'Great poet' born of '60s\". |access-date=2010-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418194447/http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article |archive-date=2010-04-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSo while Rodgers's ''Songs of a Blackbird'' includes themes about survival, mother-daughter conflicts, and street life, it also criticizes those who dishonor her use of profanity. In her poem \"The Last M.F.\" she fights back:\n\n<blockquote>\nthey say,<br />\nthat I should not use the word<br />\nmothafucka anymo<br />\nin my poetry or in any speech I give.<br />\nthey say,<br />\nthat I must and can only say it to myself<br />\nas the new Black Womanhood suggests<br />\na softer self<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nIn \"The Last M.F.\" Rodgers says she will stop using profanity but continues using the \"menacing word\" at least 11 times throughout the poem, blatantly making jabs at men and their ideas of how a woman should speak and behave. Here too, Rodgers mocks the new Black Womanhood which she believes, paradoxically, promotes women to be silent.\n\n;Later work\n\nRodgers was a revolutionary influence during the Civil Rights Movement for the black community and oppressed women. She was not afraid to stand up and fight for herself and her people, and she welcomed controversy:\n\n<blockquote>\nlet uh revolution come<br />\nstate of peace is not known to me<br />\nanyway\n</blockquote>\n\nHer poetry centered on declaring what black people needed to do to overcome their low status in society. She also elocuted that women not stand for the poor treatment they received from men, black or white.\n\nOther volumes of work such as ''The Heart as Ever Green'' (1978) and ''How I Got Ovah'' (1975) also reflect on feminine issues such as female identity, women's roles in society, and the relationships between mothers and daughters. However, ''How I Got Ovah'' exhibits a more crafted tendency than previous books, along with being more autobiographical and transformative. Personal voice pervades the poems of ''How I Got Ovah''.<ref name=McElroy>{{cite web|last=McElroy|first=Hilda|title=About Carolyn Rodgers|url=//www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/about.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rodgers develops the individual tone so well that the reader experiences a kinship with the poet and her subject matter (McElroy). The poem \"how i got ovah\" (from which the book receives its title) serves as an example of this deep personal voice. Rodgers begins an intimate revealing of personal survival with the opening lines:\n\n<blockquote>\ni can tell you<br />\nabout them<br />\ni have shaken rivers<br />\nout of my eyes.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nRodgers carries the reader through experiences of crossing rivers while \"eyelash deep,\" picturing the engulfing of ideas and socially accepted expectations of her as a black woman. She encounters ancestors through nature with their \"rich dark root fingers,\" showing appreciation for her heritage. At the end of the poem, she has found secret strength through staying afloat:\n\n<blockquote>\nthough i shivered<br />\nwas wet with cold<br />\nand wanted to sink down<br />\nand float as water, yea--<br />\ni can tell you.<br />\ni have shaken rivers<br />\nout of my eyes.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nEstella M. Sales concludes that, in this poem, Rodgers \"comes to recognize ... her own inner voice, her ancestral rootedness, her Christian faith, and her parental support\".<ref name=Sales>{{cite web|last=Sales|first=Estella|title=About Carolyn Rodgers|url=//www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/about.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> She finds a way to \"bridg[e] the separating waters\" and \"reconcile ... contradictions\" in the \"seemingly dichotomous entities of black life.\"\n\nBy the 1970s, Rodgers was distilling her language and militant persona into poetry that was deeply concerned with religion, God, and the quest for inner beauty. The change from militant views to more religious views can be seen in her 1975 poem \"and when the revolution came.\" The repetition in the first four verses show a constancy in the black church communities:\n\n<blockquote>\nand they just kept on going to church<br />\ngittin on they knees and praying<br />\nand tithing and building and buying<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nThe implied criticism here is that while the militants were busy telling other black people how they should live to improve their lives, the black church communities were busy making black communities better. In stanzas 1\u20135, Rodgers notes that the militants try to change the hair styles, the dress, any association with whites, the food eaten by blacks, and what the militants termed \"white man's religion\", According to Friedrike Kaufel, these changes \"are petty ones\".<ref name=Kaufel>{{cite web|last=Kaufel|first=Friederike|title=On \"when the revolution came\"|url=http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/revolution.html|publisher=Modern American Poetry|accessdate= November 11, 2012}}</ref>  These changes were quietly and passively resisted by the church members, who continued \"going to church\" and \"tithing and building and praying\" Stanzas 6\u20138 show the militants wanting to build new institutions for black children, and realizing that while the militants were only using words, in the form of orders, to make changes, the churches were actually making needed changes in black neighborhoods. Rodgers shows further implicates the oppressive actions of the militants, and celebrates the communal sanctity of the black church in Stanza 8:\n\n<blockquote>\nand the church folks said, yeah.<br />\nwe been waiting fo you militants<br />\nto realize that the church is an eternal rock<br />\nnow why don't you militants jest come on in<br />\nwe been waitin for you<br />\nwe can show you how to build<br />\nanything that needs building<br />\nand while we're on our knees, at that.<br />\n</blockquote>\n\nIn these actions, the church members have long before reached the state of solidarity among themselves that the militants finally call for in Stanza 6.<ref name=Kaufel />\n\nAnother example of Rodgers's turn to more personal and religious matters is her poem \"mama's God\":<ref>\"mama's God\", in Cary Nelson (ed.), ''Anthology of Modern American Poetry''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2000.</ref>\n\n<blockquote>\n:mama's God never was no white man.\nher My Jesus, Sweet Jesus never was neither.<br />\n::the color they had was the color of\nher aches and trials, the tribulations of her heart<br />\n:mama never had no savior that would turn\n::his back on her because she was black\n:::when mama prayed, she knew who she\n::was praying to and who she was praying to\n:::didn't and ain't got\n::::no color.\n</blockquote>\n\t\t\nHere Rodgers points once again to the underlying foundation to which African Americans had been clinging even before the Black Arts Movement. By using her mother as the major reference point, the poet establishes these ideas as coming before the militants. Just as the church-goers had already been calling each other brother and sister according to a higher authority, Rodgers perceives an authority to which she can appeal who \"ain't got no color\". She renders powerless the restrictions placed on her by the color of her skin.\n\nIf this cannot be characterized as transformative, nonetheless her work seems to have shifted from a collective black perspective in her early work to an individual one<ref name=ny/> in her later writings. Consequently, by the time she publishes ''The Heart as Ever Green'' in 1978, Rodgers is incorporating earlier themes of feminism and human dignity in her poems, along with newer or more pronounced themes of love and Christianity. Some readers and cultural observers do not recognize a break or rupture from Rodgers's past in her later work. For them, Rodgers's spiritual progress in her poetry still brings a radical infusion. Even in her later poetry, we can still break open into a vision uniquely situated in a poetics that remains strident, militant and experimental.\n\n==Fiction and literary criticism==\nRodgers earned an appreciative and crucial audience through her fiction and literary criticism. Her short stories, which are often overlooked, ultimately suggest themes of survival and adaptability, and are directed to a predominately black audience. Rodgers was successful in providing contemporary black readers with solace and encouragement to persist through her use of well-crafted language. Marsha C. Vick points out some of the reasons why Rodger's fiction was so influential at the time of publication, particularly focusing on her aesthetic appeal:\n\n<blockquote>\nThe same insight and searching analysis that distinguish her poetry are integral to Rodgers's short fiction and her literary criticism. She portrays in her short fiction the ordinary and overlooked people in everyday African American life and emphasizes the theme of survival. Many consider her critical essay \"Black Poetry\u2014Where It's At\" (1969) to be the best essay on the work of the \"new black poets\". In it, she aesthetically evaluates contemporary African American poetry and sets up preliminary criteria of appraisal.<ref>[http://www.answers.com/topic/carolyn-m-rodgers Carolyn M. Rodgers: Information from Answers.com]</ref> </blockquote>\n\nAccording to poet [[Lorenzo Thomas (poet)|Lorenzo Thomas]], Carolyn Rodgers proposed new [[prosodic]] categories specific to black poetry. Thomas points out that this kind of essay (or [[manifesto]]) outlining a vision statement to spur militant and creative inquiry (but most particularly \"Black Poetry\u2014Where It's At\") was widely disseminated and discussed among poets of that time.<ref>Thomas, Lorenzo. ''Extraordinary Measures: Afrocentric Modernism and Twentieth-Century American Poetry.'' Tuscaloosa and London: The University of Alabama Press, 2000. p. 211.</ref> Thomas then goes on to point out that: \"Her [Rodgers's] ideas were based on what Jerry W. Ward, Jr., has called \"culturally anchored SPEECH ACTS and Reader/Hearer Response.\" Her position on not only African-Americans' rights, but women's rights, was clear in the content and language in her poems. \"She's demonstrably feminine because she's sexy,\"<ref name=Gender>From ''Gender and The Poetics of Excess: Moments of Brocade''. Copyright \u00a9 1997 by the University Press of Mississippi.</ref> and her lines in \"The Last M.F.\" show this:\n\n<blockquote>\ni say,<br />\nthat i am soft, and you can subpoena my man, put him<br /> \non trial, and he will testify that i am<br /> \nsoft in the right places at the right times<br />\nand often we are so reserved, i have nothing to say.<ref name=Gender />\n</blockquote>\n\nDespite recognition for her efforts in the Black Arts Movement, Rodgers' unconventional use of language, especially for a woman, was frowned upon by some of her readers, most notably men. Her consistent use of profanity wasn't seen as \"ladylike\". Also, she urged her fellow black women to be strong and state clearly what they wanted. She prompted them not to acquiesce to the demands and expectations of white people, but just as important, she made it clear that black women should not be submissive to men in general; \"she registers her scorn for black men who censor women.\"<ref name=Gender />\n\n==Sidelights==\n*In addition to writing poetry, Rodgers wrote numerous short stories. Her play ''Love'' was produced Off-Broadway by [[Woodie King Jr.]], a father of the Black Theatre movement.\n*Rodgers had a career as a teacher and educator, and taught at [[Columbia College Chicago]], [[University of Washington]], Malcolm X Community College, [[Albany State University|Albany State College]], and [[Indiana University]].\n*Rodgers was a member of the [[Organization of Black American Culture]] (OBAC), which promotes cultural activity of the arts.\n*Rodgers also owned her own publishing firm, Eden Press.\n*Rodgers was deeply influenced by [[Hoyt Fuller]], the founder of Chicago's OBAC, after meeting him while working as a social worker at the YMCA (1963\u201369).  \n*Rodgers worked as a book critic for the ''Chicago Daily News'' and as a columnist for the ''Milwaukee Courier'' \n*In December 1967, Carolyn Rodgers met with Haki R. Madhubuti and Johari Amini in the basement of a South Side apartment to found Third World Press, an outlet for [[African-American literature]]. By 2007, the company continues to thrive in a multimillion-dollar facility. Over the years, Rodgers would publish works for friend and Pulitzer Prize\u2013winning author Gwendolyn Brooks, as well as [[Sonia Sanchez]], [[Sterling Plumpp]] and [[Pearl Cleage]]. Rodgers' work has been quoted by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and performed by [[Ruby Dee]] and [[Ossie Davis]].<ref>[http://www.blackamericaweb.com/?q=articles/news/moving_america_news/18087 Little Known Black History Fact: Carolyn Rodgers]</ref>\n*Was at the forefront of the Civil Rights Movement and served as a great influence for Black Consciousness, sparking \"a new generation of African Americans [who questioned] the political relevance of Black Christian organizations, beliefs, and practices.\"<ref>Gilks, Cheryl T. \"Plenty Good Room: Adaption in a Changing Black Church.\" ''The Annals of the American Academy of Political and Social Science,'' vol. 558, no. 1, Americans and Religions in the Twenty-First Century, Summer 1998, pp. 101\u2013121.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n*''Morning Glory: Poems'' (1989)\n*''Finite Forms'' (1985)\n*''Eden and Other Poems'' (1983)\n*''The Heart as Ever Green'' (1978)\n*''How I Got Ovah: New and Selected Poems'' (1975)\n*''2 Love Raps'' (1969)\n*''Songs of a Blackbird'' (1969)\n*''A Statistic, Trying to Make it Home'' (1969)\n*''Paper Soul (1968)\n*''Blackbird in a Cage'' (1967)\n\n===Further reading===\n*Bettye J. Parker-Smith, \"Running Wild in Her Soul: The Poetry of Carolyn Rodgers\", in Mari Evans (ed.), ''Black Women Writers (1950\u20131980): A Critical Evaluation'', 1984, pp. 393\u2013410.\n*Jean Davis, \"Carolyn M. Rodgers\", in Trudier Harris and Thadious M. Davis (eds), ''Dictionary of Literary Biography'', vol. 41, ''Afro-American Poets since 1955'', 1985, pp. 287\u201395.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n;Additional references\n*Nelson, Carrie. ''Anthology of Modern American Poetry''. New York: Oxford University Press, 2000, pp. 1095\u20131097.\n*Thomas, Lorenzo. ''Extraordinary Measures: Afrocentric Modernism and Twentieth-Century American Poetry''. Tuscaloosa and London: The University of Alabama Press, 2000.\n\n==External links==\n\n;Sites, exhibits, and artist pages\n*[http://voices.cla.umn.edu/artistpages/rodgers_carolyn.php Carolyn M. Rodgers: Voices from the Gaps]\n*[http://www.english.illinois.edu/maps/poets/m_r/rodgers/rodgers.htm Modern American Poetry Site: Carolyn M. Rodgers]\n\n;Tributes and obituaries\n*[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/04/13/carolyn-m-rodgers-dead-at_n_536569.html \"Carolyn M. Rodgers Dead at 69, Chicago Poet and Writer Helped Found Black Press\"], ''[[Huffington Post]]'', April 13, 2010.\n*[http://ronsilliman.blogspot.com/2010/04/carolyn-m.html Carolyn M. Rodgers 1941 \u2014 2010] This \"cyber-[[tombeau]]\" at ''Silliman's Blog'' by poet [[Ron Silliman]] includes comments, tributes, and links. Appears to have listed the birth year incorrectly as 1941\n*[http://jstheater.blogspot.com/2010/04/rip-poem-carolyn-rodgers.html RIP+Poem], April 2010; this tribute piece includes Rodgers' poem \"Poem for Some Black Women\".\n*[http://www.thatblackgirlsite.com/thatblackgirlblogs/why-the-words-and-works-of-carolyn-m-rodgers-matter/ Why the Words and Works of Carolyn M. Rodgers Matter]\n*[http://www.bvblackspin.com/2010/04/14/carolyn-m-rodgers-dead-at-69/ Black Arts Movement Star Carolyn M. Rodgers Dead at 69]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100418194447/http://www.suntimes.com/news/obituaries/2155306,CST-NWS-xrodg13.article CAROLYN M. RODGERS: 'Great poet' born of '60s] reads the [[byline]]: \"Her work 'affirmed the voice of black women -- of everyday black women'.\"\n*[http://www.blackamericaweb.com/?q=articles/news/moving_america_news/18087 Little Known Black History Fact: Carolyn Rodgers]\n\n;Poems and other writings\n*[http://somemeofbeauty.blogspot.com/2005/11/some-me-of-beauty.html \"Some Me of Beauty\"], Rodgers' poem from her 1975 collection ''How I Got Ovah''.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodgers, Carolyn}}\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Illinois]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Roosevelt University alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American women writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:African-American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:African-American publishers (people)]]\n", "name_user": "Proscribe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and work:minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolyn_Rodgers"}
{"title_page": "Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie", "text_new": "{{short description|French TV detective series 2009\u2013present}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = {{lang|fr|Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie}}\n| image                    = Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie.png\n| genre                    = {{lang|fr|com\u00e9die polici\u00e8re}} (comedic [[police procedural|police crime drama]])\n| creator                  = Anne Giafferi <br/> [[Murielle Magellan]]\n| writer                   = \n| director                 = \n| starring                 = ''Series One'':<br/>\n[[Antoine Dul\u00e9ry]]<br/>\n[[Marius Colucci]]<br/>\n''Series Two'':<br/>\n[[Samuel Labarthe]]<br/>\n[[Blandine Bellavoir]]<br/>\n[[\u00c9lodie Frenck]]<br/>\n| composer                 = \n| country                  = France\n| location                 = France\n| language                 = French\n| num_series               = 2\n| num_episodes             = 11 {{!}} 27\n| list_episodes            = \n| executive_producer       = \n| company                  = Escazai Films\n| distributor              = FranceTv, RLJ-Acorn (DVD), MHZ (USTV) (DVD)\n| camera                   = \n| runtime                  = 100 minutes\n| network                  = [[France 2]]\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]), [[720p]] ([[High-definition television|HDTV]])\n| first_aired              = 9 January 2009\n| last_aired               = present<ref name=\"telestar\" />\n| website                  = http://www.france2.fr/emissions/les-petits-meurtres-d-agatha-christie\n| website_title            = france\u2022tv\n| show_name_2              = The Little Murders of Agatha Christie; Agatha Christie's Criminal Games\n| based_on                 = [[Agatha Christie]]'s detective fiction\n| preceded_by              = {{lang|fr|Petits Meurtres en Famille}} 2006 (4-part mini-series)\n}}\n'''{{lang|fr|Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie}}''' (English title: \"'''''The Little Murders of Agatha Christie'''''\") is a French-language, [[Police procedural|police procedural genre]] television program consisting of two series loosely based on [[Agatha Christie|Agatha Christie's]] works of detective fiction. First broadcast on [[France 2]] on 9 January [[2009 in television|2009]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agathachristie.com/film-and-tv/les-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie|title=Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie|last=|first=|date=2020|website=The Home of Agatha Christie|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> Series One takes place in 1930s France with {{lang|fr|Commissaire}} (approximately [[Chief inspector#United%20Kingdom|DCI]]) Larosi\u00e8re ([[Antoine Dul\u00e9ry]]) and {{Lang|fr|Inspecteur}} Lampion ([[Marius Colucci]]). Series Two is set in mid-1950s through 1960s France with Commissaire Laurence ([[Samuel Labarthe]]), his secretary Marl\u00e8ne Leroy ([[\u00c9lodie Frenck]]), and newspaper reporter Alice Avril ([[Blandine Bellavoir]]). In English-speaking countries, the second series is titled \"Agatha Christie's Criminal Games\" and has streamed on [[MHz Choice]] in the United States and [[Special Broadcasting Service|SBS]] in Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://watch.mhzchoice.com/agatha-christie-s-criminal-games|title=Agatha Christie's Criminal Games|website=MHz Choice|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><ref> {{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/program/agatha-christies-criminal-games|title=Agatha Christie's Criminal Games|last=|first=|date=|website=SBS On Demand|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> The thirty-eight episodes to the end of Series Two include adaptations of thirty-six of Christie's works.\n\nA third series, with a new cast and set in 1970s France, was announced in 2019.<ref name=\"telestar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telestar.fr/actu-tv/exclu-telestar-les-petits-meurtres-d-agatha-christie-ce-n-est-pas-fini-467484|title=EXCLU TELESTAR. Les Petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie ce n'est... - T\u00e9l\u00e9 Star|last=Telestar.fr|date=2019-10-28|website=www.telestar.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Series One: 1930s France (2009\u20132012)==\n\n=== Overview ===\nIn France in the 1930s, womanising Commissaire Jean Larosi\u00e8re and his hapless junior officer Inspecteur \u00c9mile Lampion unravel a series of complicated murder cases to reveal the killers.\n\n=== Cast and characters ===\n==== Main ====\n* [[Antoine Dul\u00e9ry]] as Commissaire Jean Larosi\u00e8re (11 episodes)\n* [[Marius Colucci]] as Inspecteur \u00c9mile Lampion (11 episodes)\n\n==== Support ====\n* [[Serge Dubois]] as police officer ({{Lang|fr|policier}}) M\u00e9nard (9 episodes)\n* [[Olivier Carr\u00e9 (acteur)|Olivier Carr\u00e9]] as medical examiner ({{Lang|fr|m\u00e9decin l\u00e9giste}}) Dr Verdure (5 episodes)\n\n=== Episodes ===\n<!-- For help with these templates see \nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Episode_table\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Episode_list -->\n\n{{Episode table|background=|total_width=75|series=|title=25|aux1=25|aux1T=Christie adaptation|DirectedBy=25|airdate=10|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 1\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Les meurtres ABC}}\n |Aux1            = [[The A.B.C. Murders]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Eric Woreth]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2009\n |ShortSummary    = As a serial killer taunts Larosi\u00e8re, the great detective's career could be the next casualty.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 2\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Am stram gram}}\n |Aux1            = [[Ordeal by Innocence]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[St\u00e9phane Kappes]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2009\n |ShortSummary    = After the death of a beloved philanthropist, suspicion falls on her brood of adopted children.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 3\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|La plume empoisonn\u00e9e}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Moving Finger]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2009\n |ShortSummary    = Lampion gets badly wounded during a case and has to rest. Larosi\u00e8re rents a room for him in a small village which looks the perfect place to recover, except someone is sending ugly poison-pen letters.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 4\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|La maison du p\u00e9ril}}\n |Aux1            = [[Peril at End House]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2009\n |ShortSummary    = When a beautiful heiress is targeted for murder, Larosi\u00e8re loses his heart and nearly his life.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 5\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le chat et les souris}}\n |Aux1            = [[Cat Among the Pigeons]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2010\n |ShortSummary    = While investigating murders at a boarding school, Larosi\u00e8re is haunted by his past.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 6\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Je ne suis pas coupable}}\n |Aux1            = [[Sad Cypress]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2010\n |ShortSummary    = When death stalks a women's retreat, a reluctant Lampion goes undercover.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 7\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Cinq petits cochons}}\n |Aux1            = [[Five Little Pigs]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2011\n |ShortSummary    = Investigating a fifteen year old cold case, Larosi\u00e8re confronts five suspects with contradictory testimonies.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 8\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le flux et le reflux}}\n |Aux1            = [[Taken at the Flood]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2011\n |ShortSummary    = Larosi\u00e8re's former captain in World War I invites him to his family castle, where the host surprises his guests by announcing his marriage to the much younger Albertine, whom he met in Africa.<!-- revised plot summary --><br/>(Blandine Bellavoir, who plays Albertine, appears as a main character in the second series.)\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 9\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Un cadavre sur l'oreiller}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Body in the Library]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2011\n |ShortSummary    = With Larosi\u00e8re accused of strangling a prostitute, Lampion tries to clear his{{Whose|date=April 2020}} name.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 10\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Un meurtre en sommeil}}\n |Aux1            = [[Sleeping Murder]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2012\n |ShortSummary    = Sacha escapes from a psychiatric hospital and hides in an isolated house. On the first evening, she has a vision of a bloody woman. Is it related to a recently deceased woman in a house nearby?\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 11\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le couteau sur la nuque}}\n |Aux1            = [[Lord Edgware Dies]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Renaud Bertrand]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2012\n |ShortSummary    = The Larosi\u00e8re/Lampion duo investigate the murder of a woman last seen entering a theatre. Meanwhile, the commissaire's daughter, Juliette, storms into his life and might be in danger.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n}}\n\n== Series Two: mid-1950s to 1960s France (2013\u20132020) ==\n\n=== Overview ===\nThe action has moved to mid-1950s to 1960s [[Lille]], France. Suave, razor-sharp, arrogant, and intolerant \u2013 Commissaire Swan Laurence investigates murders with the often unappreciated assistance of reporter Alice Avril and police secretary Marl\u00e8ne Leroy. \u00a0\n\n=== Cast and characters ===\n==== Main ====\n* [[Samuel Labarthe]] as Commissaire Swan Laurence (27 episodes)<ref> {{Cite web|url=https://www.agathachristie.com/film-and-tv/les-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie/meet-the-characters/samuel-labarthe|title=Samuel Labarthe|last=|first=|date=|website=The Home of Agatha Christie|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}} </ref>\n* [[Blandine Bellavoir]] as {{Lang|fr|La Voix du Nord}} journalist and feminist Alice Avril (27 episodes)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agathachristie.com/film-and-tv/les-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie/meet-the-characters/blandine-bellavoir|title=Blandine Bellavoir|website=www.agathachristie.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n* [[\u00c9lodie Frenck]] as Laurence's [[Marilyn Monroe]]-esque police secretary Marl\u00e8ne Leroy (27 episodes)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.agathachristie.com/film-and-tv/les-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie/meet-the-characters/\u00e9lodie-frenck|title=\u00c9lodie Frenck|website=www.agathachristie.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==== Support ====\n* [[Dominique Thomas]] as {{Lang|fr|Commissaire Divisionnaire}} Ernest Tricard (27 episodes)\n* [[Christophe Piret]] / [[Fran\u00e7ois Godart]] as newspaper editor ({{Lang|fr|r\u00e9dacteur en chef}}) Robert Jourdeuil (2 / 15 episodes)\n*[[\u00c9ric Beauchamp]] as police \"cop\" ({{Lang|fr|flic}}) Martin (16 episodes)\n* [[Cyril Guei|Cyril Gue\u00ef]] as medical examiner ({{Lang|fr|m\u00e9decin l\u00e9giste}}) Dr Timoth\u00e9e Glissant (14 episodes)\n* [[Marie Berto]] as secretary then police officer Arlette Carmouille (5 episodes)\n*Bubulle as Marl\u00e8ne's goldfish Bubulle (5 episodes)\n* [[Natacha Lindinger]] as medical examiner Dr Euphrasie Maillol (4 episodes)\n\n=== Episodes ===\n<!-- For help with these templates see \nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Episode_table\nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Episode_list -->\n\n{{Episode table|background=|total_width=75|series=|title=25|aux1=25|aux1T=Christie adaptation|DirectedBy=25|airdate=10|episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 1\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Jeux de glaces}}\n |Aux1            = [[They Do It With Mirrors]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Eric Woreth]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2013\n |ShortSummary    = Laurence investigates gruesome murders in a rehabilitation centre.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 2\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Meurtre au champagne}}\n |Aux1            = [[Sparkling Cyanide]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2013\n |ShortSummary    = A famous movie star commits suicide during the shooting of her latest film. Alice replaces her on the set while Laurence investigates.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 3\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|T\u00e9moin Muet}}\n |Aux1            = [[Dumb Witness]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Marc Angelo]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2013\n |ShortSummary    = Laurence receives a letter dated months earlier from \u00c9milie Longuet fearing that she will be murdered. On learning that the wealthy old woman is already dead, he orders an exhumation and autopsy, which prove she had been poisoned. He and Avril both encounter ghosts who, despite his disbelief, help uncover secrets that are possible motives for all the resident family members, Mrs. Longuet's live-in personal assistant and, to Laurence's horror, his own mother, whom he arrests before discovering that the weapon used in a second murder was planted in her room.<!-- revised plot summary -->\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 4\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Pourquoi pas Martin?}}\n |Aux1            = [[Why Didn't They Ask Evans?]]\n |DirectedBy      = Marc Angelo\n |OriginalAirDate = 2013\n |ShortSummary    = Avril comes to a dying man's rescue on a cliff. While she hears his last words, she notices a woman's portrait next to him. She seeks help at the village, but when she returns, the photo is missing.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 5\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Meurtre \u00e0 la kermesse}}\n |Aux1            = [[Hallowe'en Party]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2014\n |ShortSummary    = After a gunfight, Laurence is left blind. Meanwhile a child is found drowned in a bucket of water. Laurence decides to hide his condition to investigate with Avril, who becomes his eyes.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 6\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Cartes sur table}}\n |Aux1            = [[Cards on the Table]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2014\n |ShortSummary    = A strange, wealthy man induces a dubious Laurence and Avril to attend a dinner party he is hosting with four other guests whom he suggests got away with murder, plus a self-proclaimed former member of France's secret service. When the host is murdered at the party, Laurence investigates.  Two guests are subsequently murdered and Laurence himself becomes a suspect before determining the culprit.<!-- revised plot summary -->\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 7\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le crime ne paie pas}}\n |Aux1            = [[Murder on the Links]]\n |DirectedBy      = Marc Angelo\n |OriginalAirDate = 2014\n |ShortSummary    = Avril goes undercover in a cabaret where a waitress was killed and the boss kidnapped. Laurence has to deal with an officer from the \"police of the police\" who wants him removed from the investigation.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 8\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Pension Vanilos}}\n |Aux1            = [[Hickory Dickory Dock]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2015\n |ShortSummary    = Marl\u00e8ne asks for Laurence's help on a case involving her sister Solange, who runs a boarding house  where a young woman dropped dead of poisoning.<br/>(\u00c9lodie Frenck appears in a dual role as Marl\u00e8ne's sister Solange.)\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 9\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Un meurtre est-il facile?}}\n |Aux1            = [[Murder is Easy]]\n |DirectedBy      = Marc Angelo\n |OriginalAirDate = 2015\n |ShortSummary    = Tired of living in poverty and being disrespected as a female journalist, Avril accepts a marriage proposal from a much older man, a very rich factory owner whom she barely knows. When a series of murders occurs at the factory, Avril, who has moved into her fianc\u00e9's mansion and also been given an executive position at his factory, helps Laurence solve the crimes, which include the attempted murders of herself and Marl\u00e8ne, from within. Avril and her fianc\u00e9 end their engagement amicably.<!-- revised plot summary -->\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 10\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Madame Mac Ginty est morte}}\n |Aux1            = [[Mrs McGinty's Dead]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Didier Bivel]], Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2015\n |ShortSummary    = Avril's ex-husband is accused of murder. She discovers him hiding in her apartment and does not turn him to the police.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 11\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Murder Party}}\n |Aux1            = [[A Murder is Announced]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2015\n |ShortSummary    = Marl\u00e8ne is puzzled by an advertisement in the paper for a \"murder party\". Laurence believes it is a joke, but at set time a man interrupts the party violently and drops dead.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 12\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|L'\u00e9trange enl\u00e8vement du petit Bruno}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Adventure of Johnnie Waverly]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2016\n |ShortSummary    = A famous author and her husband receive anonymous letters threatening that their son will be kidnapped for ransom from their home at a specific time. Despite deploying heavy security, Laurence fails to prevent the kidnapping and is shot in the aftermath. He feigns his death to pursue the case without the culprit's knowledge and, with major assistance from Avril, Marl\u00e8ne, and Dr. Maillol, is able to reveal all at his own fake funeral.<!-- revised plot summary -->\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 13\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le cheval p\u00e2le}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Pale Horse]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Olivier Panchot]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2016\n |ShortSummary    = Laurence investigates whether the death of Alice's young heiress friend is related to  occult powers.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 14\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|L'affaire Protheroe}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Murder at the Vicarage]]\n |DirectedBy      = Olivier Panchot\n |OriginalAirDate = 2016\n |ShortSummary    = After a young secretary hangs herself, Laurence suspects sinister forces led to her death.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 15\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|La myst\u00e9rieuse affaire de Styles}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Mysterious Affair at Styles]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2016\n |ShortSummary    = Laurence and Avril investigate a wealthy spa owner after a man drowns in her establishment.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 16\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Albert Major parlait trop}}\n |Aux1            = [[A Caribbean Mystery]]\n |DirectedBy      = Eric Woreth\n |OriginalAirDate = 2016\n |ShortSummary    = Avril investigates a murder in a hospital while she's admitted for her own injuries.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 17\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|L'Homme au complet marron}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Man in the Brown Suit]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Rodolphe Tissot]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2017\n |ShortSummary    = Laurence goes undercover for the French Secret Service as a female secretary.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 18\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Le miroir se brisa}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Mirror Crack'd from Side to Side]]\n |DirectedBy      = Rodolphe Tissot\n |OriginalAirDate = 2017\n |ShortSummary    = Investigating a murder becomes complicated for Laurence as he mourns his own loss.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 19\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Crimes haute couture}}\n |Aux1            = [[Third Girl]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2017\n |ShortSummary    = After a young fashionista accuses herself of murder, Laurence has to find the real killer.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 20\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Crime de No\u00ebl}}\n |Aux1            = not adapted\n |DirectedBy      = Rodolphe Tissot\n |OriginalAirDate = 2017\n |ShortSummary    = Two orphans witness the murder of a Santa Claus at an outdoor Christmas market; an original story.\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 21\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Drame en trois actes}}\n |Aux1            = [[Three Act Tragedy]]\n |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2018\n |ShortSummary    = Murder befalls Alice's acting class, which features a guest teacher who looks exactly like Laurence.<br/>(Samuel Labarthe appears in a dual role as acting teacher Herbert Michel.)\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 22\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Meurtres en solde}}\n |Aux1            = [[Hercule Poirot's Christmas]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Didier Bivel]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2018\n |ShortSummary    = Avril is attacked and struggles with amnesia while working on an article. The bodies of a man and a woman are found at a car crash and the deaths look suspicious.<br/>(This adaptation has no Christmas theme.)\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 23\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|M\u00e9lodie Mortelle}}\n |Aux1            = [[The Sittaford Mystery]]\n |DirectedBy      = [[Christophe Campos]]\n |OriginalAirDate = 2018\n |ShortSummary    = &nbsp;\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 24\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Ding Dingue Dong}}\n |Aux1            = [[Evil Under the Sun]]\n |DirectedBy      = Christophe Campos\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019\n |ShortSummary    = &nbsp;\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 25\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|L'Heure Zero}}\n |Aux1            = [[Towards Zero]]\n |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019\n |ShortSummary    = &nbsp;\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 26\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Rendez-vous avec la Mort}}\n |Aux1            = [[Appointment with Death]]\n |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019\n |ShortSummary    = &nbsp;\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 27\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Un Cadavre au Petit D\u00e9jeuner}}\n |Aux1            = not adapted\n |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019/2020\n |ShortSummary    = (Antoine Dul\u00e9ry appears as Larosi\u00e8re's nephew, who is also a commissaire. Original musical-comedy episode;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/1676468291833/agatha-christies-criminal-games-a-body-with-breakfast|title=Agatha Christie's Criminal Games: A Body with Breakfast|last=|first=|date=|website=SBS On Demand|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> first aired in Italy in 2019, Australia in 2020, and in France expected late 2020.)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mondofox.it/guida-tv/foxcrime/2019-10-31/|title=GUIDA TV di FoxCrime di gioved\u00ec 31 ottobre 2019|last=|first=|date=31 October 2019|website=MondoFox|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\"Les petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie\" Un cadavre au petit d\u00e9jeuner (TV Episode 2019) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10269126/releaseinfo|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\"telestar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telestar.fr/actu-tv/exclu-telestar-les-petits-meurtres-d-agatha-christie-ce-n-est-pas-fini-467484|title=EXCLU TELESTAR. Les Petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie ce n'est... - T\u00e9l\u00e9 Star|last=Telestar.fr|date=2019-10-28|website=www.telestar.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n}}\n\n== Series Three: 1970s France (announced 2019) ==\nA third series, with a new cast and set in France in the 1970s, was announced in 2019.<ref name=\"telestar\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.programme.tv/news/series/208867-emotion-dans-greys-anatomy-la-nouvelle-saison-des-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie-et-les-abdos-de-loup-denis-elion-les-tournages-de-la-semaine-photos/|title=Emotion dans Grey\u2019s Anatomy, la nouvelle saison des Petits Meurtres d\u2019Agatha Christie et les abdos de Loup-Denis Elion\u2026 Les tournages de la semaine (PHOTOS) - series - T\u00e9l\u00e9 2 semaines|website=www.programme.tv/news|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n\n* A distinct four-part mini-series, \"{{lang|fr|Petits Meurtres en Famille}}\", adapted from ''Hercule Poirot's Christmas'', was released in 2006. Although Larosi\u00e8re and Lampion are the main characters (played by the same actors), this mini-series is not a prequel or sequel to the later series.\n*[[Alexandre Labarthe]], who plays Laurence's son (S2 E22), is Samuel Labarthe's son.<ref> {{Cite web|url=https://www.telez.fr/actus-tv/petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie-alexandre-labarthe-fils-de-samuel-a-lecran-comme-a-la-vie/|title=\"Petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie\" : Alexandre Labarthe, fils de Samuel \u00e0 l'\u00e9cran comme \u00e0 la vie {{!}} News TV T\u00e9l\u00e9 Z|last=Charlet|first=Justine|date=2019-10-04|website=T\u00e9l\u00e9Z|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-20}} </ref>\n*[[Arnaud Perron]], Blandine Bellavoir's partner, plays Alice's ex-husband (S2 E10).<ref> {{Cite web|url=https://www.programme-tv.net/news/series-tv/225198-blandine-bellavoir-les-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie-poste-une-photo-trop-mignonne-de-son-bebe-sur-instagram/|title=Blandine Bellavoir (Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie) poste une photo trop mignonne de son b\u00e9b\u00e9 sur Instagram|last=Fuzeau|first=Stephanie|date=2019-02-06|website=www.programme-tv.net|language=fr|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}} </ref>\n*Laurence drives a [[Facel Vega]] Facellia FA red Bordeaux coupe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lesanciennes.com/annonce/A312537-ventes-auto-facel-vega-facellia-fa-coupe-2-2-1960.html?ftype=&fcat=&search=FACEL%20VEGA|title=V\u00e9hicule du film \"les petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie\"|last=|date=2020-03-08|year=|publisher=|pages=|language=|format=|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09|quote=|periodical=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.facel-vega.asso.fr/tv/tv.html|title=Facel Vega \u00e1 la T\u00e9l\u00e9vision|last=|date=2013-03-29|year=|publisher=|pages=|language=|format=|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09|quote=|periodical=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.rrforums.net/forum/messages/16947/22770.html?1479246125|title=RR Forums Australia|last=|date=2016-11-15|year=|publisher=|pages=|language=|format=|url-status=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09|quote=|periodical=}}</ref>\n\n== Complete cast ==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed center\" style=\"font-size: 86%; width:60%; left:0 auto; text-align:center;\"\n|+ align=\"center\" colspan=\"4\" |<big>{{nowrap|Cast of Series One and Series Two}}</big>\n|- style=\"background-color: #CCCCFF\" \n|'''Actor'''||'''Character'''||'''Epis