epsi NFL Rookie of the Week#2012 winners|Pepsi NFL Rookie of the Week]] (Week 3, 2012; Week 5, 2012; Week 8, 2012)\n\n===Records and achievements===\n<!---DON'T ADD UNSOURCED RECORDS --->\n[[File:Andrew Luck.JPG|thumb|225px|Luck in [[Empower Field at Mile High|Denver]] in 2014]]\n*Most passing yards in a single game by a rookie quarterback: 433 (vs [[Miami Dolphins]]) (11/4/12)<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/04/andrew-luck-record-colts-dolphins-23-20_n_2073511.html |title=Colts Beat Dolphins 23\u201320: Andrew Luck Breaks Single-Game Rookie Record With 433 Passing Yards |last=Marot |first=Michael |date=November 4, 2012 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |access-date=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105001511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/04/andrew-luck-record-colts-dolphins-23-20_n_2073511.html |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie in a single season (4,374)<ref name=\"McIntyre\"/>\n*Most game-winning drives by a rookie quarterback (7)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/vKI4i |title=Most game-winning drives by a rookie quarterback, single season, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 2 seasons (8,196)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20140110/NEWS/301109891/1009|title=Colts' Andrew Luck thinks he has learned from mistakes against Patriots|last=Garven|first=Rich|work=Telegram.com|date=January 10, 2014|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 3 seasons (12,688)<ref name=\"Most passing 3\"/>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 5 postseason games (1,703)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ESPNStatsInfo/status/554446056407437313|title=ESPN Stats & Info on Twitter|work=[[Twitter]]|date=January 11, 2015|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n*Most consecutive 350-yard passing games on the road (5)<ref name=\"Week 9 2014\"/>\n*Most pass attempts per game, career: (38.3)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_att_per_g_career.htm |title=NFL Pass Attempts per Game Career Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*Fifth highest passing yards total in a playoff game (443) (Wild-Card game against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] on January 4, 2014).<ref name=\"Wilson\"/>\n*First quarterback to throw for more than 350 yards in five consecutive road games<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasyfootball/update/24782826/andrew-luck-sets-career-high-in-td-passes-with-seven-games-left|title=Andrew Luck sets career high in TD passes with seven games left|last=Hartstein|first=Larry|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=November 3, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n*First quarterback to throw for 370 yards or more, 4 touchdowns, and have a completion percentage 70 percent or above in consecutive games<ref name=\"sports.yahoo.com\"/>\n*Third player to throw for 3,000 yards in the first nine games, alongside [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Drew Brees]] (twice)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nfldraftdiamonds.com/colts-andrew-luck-is-breaking-records-tonight/ |title=Colts Andrew Luck is breaking records tonight |last=Talbot |first=Desmond |work=NFL Draft Diamonds |access-date=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Colts franchise records====\n*Most passing yards in a single season (4,761, 2014)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2014/12/28/7457399/andrew-luck-breaks-peyton-mannings-colts-franchise-record-for-single |title=Andrew Luck Breaks Peyton Manning's Colts Franchise Record for Single-Season Passing Yards |last=Wilson |first=Josh |date=December 28, 2014 |website=Stampede Blue |access-date=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie quarterback in a single season (4,374)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">http://prod.static.colts.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/mediaguide/2014-mediaguide.pdf</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie quarterback in a single game (433)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass attempts by a rookie quarterback in a single season (627)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass completions by a rookie quarterback in a single season (339)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass completions by a rookie quarterback in a single game (31)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most passing touchdowns by a rookie quarterback in a single game (4)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Highest passer rating by a rookie quarterback with a minimum of 100 attempts (76.5)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Highest interception percentage by a rookie quarterback with a minimum of 100 attempts (2.87)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Endorsements==\nIn March 2012, [[Nike, Inc.]] signed Luck to its roster of athletes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nikeinc.com/news/nike-signs-quarterback-andrew-luck |title=Nike signs quarterback Andrew Luck |date=March 12, 2012 |website=Nike Inc. |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Luck became a partner and investor in BodyArmor SuperDrink.<ref name=\"Colts Quarterback Andrew Luck Dumps Gatorade for a Stake in Upstart BODYARMOR\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-09-17/colts-quarterback-andrew-luck-dumps-gatorade-for-a-stake-in-upstart-bodyarmor |title=Colts Quarterback Andrew Luck Dumps Gatorade for a Stake in Uptart BODYARMOR |last=Boudway |first=Ira |date=September 17, 2013 |website=Business Week |access-date=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 17, 2012, Luck graduated from Stanford with a bachelor's degree in architectural design and received the Al Masters Award, an honor given to an athlete each year, \"for the highest standards of athletic performance, leadership and academic achievement.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/story/2012-06-19/andrew-luck-graduates-stanford-degree-michelle-wie-indianapolis-colts |title=Andrew Luck graduates from Stanford with architectural degree |last=Brown |first=Clifton |date=June 19, 2012 |website=www.sportingnews.com |language=en |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>  He has stated that his favorite musician is [[Bruce Springsteen]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/colts/story/2012-06-25/luck-opens-up-on-the-beard-and-his-go-phone/55826972/1 |title=Luck opens up on the beard, his phone and thoughts on Indy |last=Kravitz |first=Bob |date=June 25, 2012 |website=USA Today |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> An avid reader, Luck has become known as \"the Colts' very own librarian\", giving and suggesting books for his teammates; in 2012, he said his favorite book was [[Henri Charri\u00e8re]]'s [[Papillon (book)|''Papillon'']], and he is a fan of [[Bernard Cornwell]]'s historical fiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-andrew-luck-book-club-1446675595|title=The Andrew Luck Book Club|last=Clark|first=Kevin|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref> On the field, Luck perplexes his opponents with comments that may or may not be trash talk: when he is knocked down, he is in the habit of congratulating his opponent on the hit. After a hit by linebacker [[Ryan Kerrigan]] that caused a fumble and sent Luck scrambling for the ball, he was not able to congratulate Kerrigan right away and had to wait until later in the game \"to tell Kerrigan how great he was doing\". Kerrigan's reaction was later captured, \"You want to say thank you but then you say 'wait a second\u2014I'm not supposed to like you!'\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/andrew-luck-the-nfls-most-perplexing-trash-talker-1418663249|title=Andrew Luck: The NFL's Most Perplexing Trash Talker. The Colts Quarterback Drives Defenders Crazy by Offering Compliments; Head Games or Genuine Kindness?|last=Clark|first=Kevin|date=December 16, 2014|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2019, Luck married longtime girlfriend Nicole Pechanec.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2019/03/31/andrew-luck-wedding-nicole-pechanec/3323937002/ |title=Andrew Luck wedding: Colts quarterback marries Nicole Pechanec |date=2019-03-31 |website=Indianapolis Star |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> He announced on June 14, 2019, that they are expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wthr.com/article/colts-quarterback-andrew-luck-wife-are-pregnant |title=Colts quarterback Andrew Luck, wife are pregnant |last=Calabro |first=Dave |date=June 14, 2019 |website=13 WTHR Indianapolis |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> The couple's first child was born in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horner |first1=Scott |title=Ex-Indianapolis Colts QB Andrew Luck's wife gives birth to couple's first child |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/11/22/andrew-luck-ex-colts-qbs-wife-gives-birth-daughter-lucy/4269024002/ |website=USAToday |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\n\nIn 2013 Luck appeared on the comedy series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' as himself alongside teammates [[Reggie Wayne]], [[Anthony Castonzo]], [[Robert Mathis]], and [[Adam Vinatieri]] during the show's [[Parks and Recreation (season 5)|fifth season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/movies/2013/11/19/andrew-luck-colts-nbc-amy-poehler/3644753/|title=Watch preview of Colts-themed \"Parks and Rec\" episode|last=Lindquist|first=David|work=indystar.com|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American football|College football}}\n*[[List of first overall National Football League draft picks]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Luck}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=2533031 |espn=14874 |pfr=L/LuckAn00}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120527030325/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html Indianapolis Colts bio]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527030325/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html |date=May 27, 2012 |title=Stanford Cardinal bio }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gostanford.com/andrew-luck/ |title=Stanford's Andrew Luck Heisman Trophy candidate site |accessdate=December 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125030431/http://www.gostanford.com/andrew-luck/ |archivedate=January 25, 2012 |df= }}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Andrew Luck\n| list1 =\n{{Stanford Cardinal quarterback navbox}}\n{{Pac-12 Player of the Year}}\n{{Football Academic All-America of the Year}}\n{{Johnny Unitas Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{2012 NFL Draft}}\n{{NFL Number One Draft Picks}}\n{{ColtsFirstPick}}\n{{Indianapolis Colts starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{AP NFL Comeback Player}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{NFL passing touchdown leaders}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luck, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:National Football League first overall draft picks]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Houston]]\n[[Category:Stanford Cardinal football players]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Andrew Luck\n|image=Andrew Luck.JPG\n|image_size=225px\n|alt=\n|caption=Luck in 2014\n|number=12\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1989|9|12|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=4\n|weight_lbs=240\n|high_school=[[Stratford High School (Houston)|Stratford]] ([[Houston, Texas]])\n|college=[[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]]\n|draftyear=2012\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=[[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|1]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] ({{NFL Year|2012}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n|highlights=\n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2013 Pro Bowl|2012]]\u2013[[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]], [[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]])\n* [[AP NFL Comeback Player of the Year|NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[List of National Football League annual passing touchdowns leaders|NFL passing touchdowns leader]] (2014)\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]] (2011)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2011)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2011)\n* {{nowrap|2\u00d7 [[Pac-12 Conference football individual awards|Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Year]] (2010, 2011)}}\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2010 College Football All-America Team|2010]], [[2011 College Football All-America Team|2011]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12]] ([[2010 All-Pacific-10 Conference football team|2010]], [[2011 All-Pac-12 Conference football team|2011]])\n|statlabel1=[[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue1=171\u201383\n|statlabel2=Completion percentage\n|statvalue2=60.8\n|statlabel3=Passing yards\n|statvalue3=23,671\n|statlabel4=[[Passer rating]]\n|statvalue4=89.5\n|statlabel5=Rushing yards\n|statvalue5=1,590\n|statlabel6=Rushing touchdowns\n|statvalue6=14\n|nflnew=andrewluck/2533031\n|pfr=LuckAn00\n}}\n'''Andrew Austen Luck''' (born September 12, 1989) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who played all seven years of his professional career with the [[Indianapolis Colts]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] for the  [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford Cardinal]], where he won the [[Maxwell Award]] and [[Walter Camp Award]] as college football's player of the year and was twice recognized as an [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]].<ref>He received first-team All-American honors from the [[American Football Coaches Association]], the [[Walter Camp Football Foundation]], [[ESPN.com]], and ''[[Pro Football Weekly]]''.</ref> He was the runner-up for the [[Heisman Trophy]] in both 2010 and 2011, and was named the Offensive Player of the Year in the [[Pac-12 Conference]] in both 2010 and 2011. [[CBS Sports]] draft analyst Rob Rang called Luck the best prospect he had ever scouted,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/14372683/rewind-lucks-stock-rises-even-higher-ingrams-sags |title=Luck stock rises even higher; Ingram's sags |work=CBSSports.com |date=November 29, 2010 |first=Rob |last=Rang |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120121134652/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/14372683/rewind-lucks-stock-rises-even-higher-ingrams-sags |archivedate=January 21, 2012 |df= }}</ref> while the ''[[Kansas City Star]]'' put him in line with [[LeBron James]] and [[Bryce Harper]] as \"the most hyped amateurs in recent sports memory.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kansascity.com/2011/10/22/3223747/it-will-take-luck-for-this-story.html |title=Luck may need luck to live up to hype |first=Sam |last=Mellinger |newspaper=Kansas City Star |date=October 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough widely projected as the first overall selection in the [[2011 NFL Draft]], Luck decided to return to Stanford for his [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] junior season.<ref name=\"Luck ESPN\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=5995754|first=Ted|last=Miller|title=Andrew Luck skipping NFL draft, will return to Stanford Cardinal |work=[[ESPN.com]] |date=January 6, 2011|accessdate=January 6, 2011}}</ref> A year later, he was selected [[List of first overall National Football League draft picks|first overall]] in the [[2012 NFL Draft]]. In his first three professional seasons, Luck led the Colts to three playoff appearances including two [[AFC South]] division titles in [[2013 Indianapolis Colts season|2013]] and [[2014 Indianapolis Colts season|2014]], also earning a [[Pro Bowl]] selection in each season. In the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs]], he led the Colts to the second largest playoff comeback in NFL history, over the [[Kansas City Chiefs]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2014/1/4/5274940/colts-chiefs-comeback-nfl-playoffs |title=Colts complete 2nd-largest playoff comeback |last=Dator |first=James |website=SB Nation|date=January 5, 2014 }}</ref> Primarily known for his passing, Luck also established himself as a [[Dual-threat quarterback|mobile threat]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmqb.si.com/2014/06/05/andrew-luck-russell-wilson-colin-kaepernick-robert-griffin-cam-newtown-running-quarterbacks-analysis/|title=NFL's Best Running Quarterback? The Answer May Surprise You|last=Benoit|first=Andy|work=mmqb.si.com|date=June 5, 2014|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Indianapolis Colts season|2016 season]], Luck suffered an injury to his throwing shoulder but continued to play. That offseason he had surgery on the shoulder, forcing him to miss the entire 2017 season. The next year he returned to playing, finishing second in the league in touchdown passes and setting career-highs in several categories, as well as leading the Colts to 10 wins and their first playoff appearance since 2014. For his play he was voted to the fourth [[2019 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] of his career and was named the [[National Football League Comeback Player of the Year Award|Comeback Player of the Year]]. Despite his success, Luck retired prior to the 2019 season, citing issues with injuries he sustained during his career. Due to retiring at the age of 29, Luck is considered by some to be among the best professional athletes to end their career during their prime.\n\n{{TOClimit|limit=3}}\n\n==Early life==\nLuck was born in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/andrew-luck-20954039|title=Andrew Luck Biography|work=Biography.com|accessdate=January 6, 2014}}</ref><ref name=sn>{{cite web|url=http://today.sportingnews.com/sportingnewstoday/20091103?pg=3#pg3\n|title=Andrew Luck|date=November 3, 2009|accessdate=November 23, 2009|work=[[The Sporting News]]}}</ref> to Kathy (n\u00e9e Wilson) Luck and [[Oliver Luck]], who is the current commissioner of the [[XFL (2020)|XFL]], former executive vice president for regulatory affairs at the NCAA, former quarterback (as well as athletic director) at [[West Virginia Mountaineers|West Virginia University]], and a former NFL quarterback for the [[Houston Oilers]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Dan Wolken and George Schroeder, USA TODAY Sports |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2014/12/17/oliver-luck-ncaa-west-virginia-college-football-playoff/20529783/ |title=Oliver Luck leaving West Virginia for high-ranking NCAA job |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=December 17, 2014 |accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOliver Luck was general manager of two [[World League of American Football]] teams before becoming president of the league, so Andrew spent his early childhood in London and [[Frankfurt]], Germany, where he attended [[Frankfurt International School]].<ref name=fitzgerald>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/08/19/SP3B19A8M2.DTL|title=Cardinal offense gets a little Luck this year|date=August 19, 2009|work=San Francisco Chronicle|last=FitzGerald|first=Tom|accessdate=November 23, 2009}}</ref> He is the oldest of four children, including sisters Mary Ellen and Emily and brother Addison. Mary Ellen is a Stanford graduate who played [[volleyball]] there, Emily is a current Stanford student, and Addison lived in [[Morgantown, West Virginia]] before their father's job took him to the [[Indianapolis]] area. In London, Andrew attended [[The American School in London]].<ref name=veness>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/sep/07/andrew-luck-peyton-manning-indianapolis-colts-denver-broncos|title=Andrew Luck keeps his head while all about lose theirs over Peyton Manning|date=September 7, 2014|newspaper=Guardian|last=Veness|first=Simon|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref> As a result of his childhood in London, he is a fan of soccer. Although supporters of London clubs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] have reached out to him believing he was a fellow fan, Luck said, \"I try to support as many of the American fellows playing [in the [[Premier League]]] as possible.\" Luck said the [[Houston Dynamo]] was the \"number one team in my heart\" because his father was the club's founding president and general manager.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/blog/_/name/relegationzone/id/1578?cc=5901|title=Andrew Luck's love for soccer runs deep|publisher=ESPN FC|work=Relegation Zone|date=December 19, 2013|first=Roger|last=Bennett}}</ref>\n\nThe Lucks returned to Texas when Oliver Luck was named [[chief executive officer|CEO]] of the Harris County-Houston Sports Authority. In Houston, Andrew attended [[Stratford High School (Houston)|Stratford High School]], where he threw for 7,139 yards and 53 touchdowns in his [[high school football|high school]] career, and rushed for another 2,085 yards.<ref name=mediaguide09/> Luck was also co-[[valedictorian]] of his graduating class in 2008.<ref name=mediaguide09>{{cite web|title=Bio: Andrew Luck |work=Stanford Football Media Guide |year=2009 |url=http://gostanford.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html |accessdate=September 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223233311/http://gostanford.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html |archivedate=December 23, 2008 |df= }}</ref> Regarded as a four-star recruit by ''[[Rivals.com]]'', Luck was listed as the No. 4 pro-style quarterback in the class of 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/recruiting/rankings/rank-1818|title=2008 Pro-style quarterbacks |work=Rivals.com |date=January 16, 2008 }}</ref> He played in the 2008 [[U.S. Army All-American Bowl]]. A highly rated high school recruiting target,<ref name=mediaguide09/> he chose Stanford over offers from [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]], [[Oklahoma State Cowboys football|Oklahoma State]], [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]], [[Rice Owls football|Rice]], and [[Virginia Cavaliers|Virginia]], after being recruited by Stanford head coach [[Jim Harbaugh]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/features/andrew-luck-the-natural-20150902|title=Andrew Luck: The Natural\n|last=Taibbi|first=Matt|date=September 2, 2015|accessdate=September 3, 2015|work=[[Rolling Stone]]\n}}</ref>\n\n{{College athlete recruit start|40=yes|collapse=no|year=2008}}\n{{College athlete recruit entry\n| recruit  = Andrew Luck\n| position = [[Quarterback|QB]]\n| hometown = Houston, Texas\n| highschool = [[Stratford High School (Houston)|Stratford HS]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 4\n| weight = 210\n| 40     = 4.7\n| commitdate = June 30, 2007\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 4\n| espn grade = 82\n}}\n{{College athlete recruit end\n| 40               = \n| year             = 2008\n| rivals ref title = Stanford Football Commitments\n| scout ref title  = 2008 Stanford Football Commits\n| espn ref title   = ESPN\n| rivals school    = stanford\n| scout s          = 18\n| espn schoolid    = 24\n| scout overall    = 4 (QB)\n| rivals overall   = 5 (QB)\n| espn overall     = 7 (QB)\n| accessdate       = December 14, 2011\n| bball            = \n}}\n\n==College career==\nAfter accepting an athletic scholarship to attend [[Stanford University]], Luck played for coach [[Jim Harbaugh]] and coach [[David Shaw (American football)|David Shaw]]'s [[Stanford Cardinal football|Cardinal]] teams from 2008 to 2011.\n\n===2009 season===\n[[File:Luckthrowingfotball.jpg|left|thumb|175px|Andrew Luck at the Big Game against Cal in 2009.]]\nAfter [[Redshirt (college sports)|redshirting]] during his freshman year in 2008, he earned the starting quarterback job in 2009 over the returning starter, [[Tavita Pritchard]], thereby becoming the first Stanford freshman to earn the starting quarterback job since [[Chad Hutchinson]] in 1996.<ref name=fitzgerald/> In his first season, Luck led the Cardinal to victories over top-10 [[2009 Oregon Ducks football team|Oregon]] and [[2009 USC Trojans football team|USC]] teams and a berth in the [[2009 Sun Bowl]].<ref>[http://espn.go.com/ncf/clubhouse?teamId=24 Cardinal Home] ESPN</ref> Playing in a run-oriented offense featuring Heisman Trophy runner-up [[Toby Gerhart]], Luck threw for 2,575 yards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/andrew-luck-1/gamelog/2009/ |title=Andrew Luck 2009 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Luck had 2,929 yards of total offense, the fifth-highest total in Stanford history. He led the Pac-10 in pass efficiency rating with a rating of 143.5, and finished second in the Pac-10 in total offense.<ref>Murphy, Austin, \"Man with a Plan\", ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 13, 2011, pp. 66\u201377.</ref>\n\nLuck injured a finger on his throwing hand in the Cardinal's final regular season game against [[2009 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]]. He had surgery prior to the [[Sun Bowl]] and did not play in the game.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/big12/post/_/id/8047/sooners-may-catch-break-in-sun-bowl-with-lucks-finger-surgery |title=Sooners may catch break in Sun Bowl with Luck's finger surgery |last=Griffin |first=Tim |date=December 7, 2009 |access-date=December 7, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211013220/http://espn.go.com/blog/big12/post/_/id/8047/sooners-may-catch-break-in-sun-bowl-with-lucks-finger-surgery |archive-date=December 11, 2009 |url-status=live |publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n===2010 season===\n[[File:Andrew Luck at the Big Game.jpg|right|thumb|225px|Luck after the Big Game between Stanford and Cal in 2010]]\nIn 2010, Luck emerged as one of the top players in the nation. Luck was named the Pac-10 Offensive Player of the Year and was unanimously selected to the All-Pac-10 First Team. Luck led Stanford to a 12\u20131 record, a #4 ranking in the final AP Poll, and a victory in the [[2011 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]]. Luck was named the Orange Bowl MVP after throwing four touchdown passes in Stanford's 40\u201312 win over [[2010 Virginia Tech Hokies football team|Virginia Tech]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2011-01-03-stanford.html |title=Orange Bowl \u2013 Virginia Tech vs Stanford Box Score, January 3, 2011 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Luck led the Pac-10 in pass efficiency for the second straight year with a [[quarterback rating]] of 170.2. He also led the conference in total offense with 3,791 yards, in passing yards with 3,338 yards, and in touchdown passes with 32. Luck rushed for 453 yards, a record for Stanford quarterbacks, with three runs of over 50 yards.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/andrew-luck-1/gamelog/2010/ |title=Andrew Luck 2010 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Luck's 32 touchdown passes are a new Stanford record, breaking the old record of 27 held by [[John Elway]] and [[Steve Stenstrom]]. Luck's 3,791 yards of total offense also are a school record, breaking the old record of 3,398 yards held by Stenstrom. Luck also set new Stanford single-season records for completion percentage (70.7%) and pass efficiency rating (170.2). He won the Pac-10 Offensive Player of the Week award for his performances against [[2010 Arizona Wildcats football team|Arizona]] and [[2010 California Golden Bears football team|California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2010/11/08/humble-luck-keeps-rolling-0 |title=Humble Luck Keeps On Rolling |last=Reiswig |first=Ryan |website=Pac-12 |language=en |access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pac-12.com/article/2010/11/08/luck-mcdonald-and-forbath-named-pac-10-football-players-week |title=Luck, McDonald and Forbath Named Pac-10 Football Players of the Week |website=Pac-12 |language=en |access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nLuck finished the 2010 season with two years of college eligibility remaining. He was eligible to declare for the [[2011 NFL Draft]], but announced on January 6, 2011 that he would remain at Stanford to complete his degree.<ref name=\"Luck ESPN\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010611aac.html |title=Andrew Luck to Return to Stanford for 2011 Season |location=[[Stanford, California]] |work=[[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford Cardinal]] |publisher=[[Stanford University]] |date=January 6, 2011 |accessdate=January 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230221502/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/010611aac.html |archivedate=December 30, 2011 |df= }}</ref> He was viewed by many TV sportscasters and ESPN writers as the top pro quarterback prospect in college football. In December 2010, ''[[Sporting News]]'' projected Luck as the No. 1 selection in the 2011 NFL Draft, had he entered.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/mock-draft-luck-would-re-energize-panthers-listless-offense |title=Mock Draft: Luck would re-energize Panthers' listless offense |work=Sporting News |first=Russ |last=Lande |date=December 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224015613/http://www.sportingnews.com/nfl/feed/2010-09/draft-dish/story/mock-draft-luck-would-re-energize-panthers-listless-offense |archivedate=December 24, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===2011 season===\nIn 2011, Luck led Stanford to a record of 11\u20132, a berth in a [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] bowl, the [[2012 Fiesta Bowl]] against [[2011 Oklahoma State Cowboys football team|Oklahoma State]], and a # 7 ranking in the final AP Poll. He won the [[Maxwell Award]] and the [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp Player of the Year Award]]. He was the runner-up for the [[Heisman Trophy]] for the second consecutive year, becoming the fourth player to finish second in the Heisman voting twice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/heisman-2011.html |title=2011 Heisman Trophy Voting |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> He was named a First Team All America ([[American Football Coaches Association|AFCA]], [[Walter Camp Football Foundation|Walter Camp]], [[ESPN.com]], [[Pro Football Weekly]]). He was the [[2011 Pac-12 Conference football season#Awards and honors|Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Year]], becoming only the fifth player to win that award twice (after John Elway, Charles White, Reggie Bush, and Rueben Mayes). He was named First Team All-Pac-12 for the second straight year. Luck set a new Stanford record for career touchdown passes with 82, breaking John Elway's record of 77. Luck also set a new school record for touchdown passes in a season with 37, breaking his own record of 32. Luck set another school record for career total offense with 10,387 yards, breaking [[Steve Stenstrom]]'s mark of 9,825 yards. Luck became Stanford's all-time leader in wins by a starting quarterback, with 31 wins through the end of the regular season. Luck also became Stanford's all-time leader in winning percentage by a starting quarterback, with a winning percentage of .816 (31\u20137). Luck broke the Pac-12 records for career passing efficiency rating (162.8) and career completion percentage (67.0%). He also broke his own Pac-12 record for highest completion percentage in a season (71.3%). Luck was named Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Week for his performance against [[2011 Washington State Cougars football team|Washington State]]. He earned the 2011 [[List of Football Academic All-America Team Members of the Year|Academic All-America of the Year]] award.<ref name=SqALht2COAAADIFT>{{cite web|url=http://cosida.com/news.aspx?id=3474|title=Stanford quarterback Andrew Luck headlines the 2011 Capital One Academic All-America\u00ae Division I Football Team|accessdate=December 8, 2011|date=December 8, 2010|publisher=[[College Sports Information Directors of America]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426040719/http://cosida.com/news.aspx?id=3474|archive-date=April 26, 2012|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season !! colspan=7|Passing !! rowspan=6| !! colspan=5|Rushing !! rowspan=6| !! colspan=3|Receiving !! rowspan=6| !!|Total Offense\n|-\n! Comp !! Att !! Yds !! Pct !! TD !! Int !! [[Passer rating|Rating]] !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Yards\n|-\n| [[2009 Stanford Cardinal football team|2009]]\n| 162 || 288 || 2,575 || 56.3% || 13 || 4 || 143.5\n| 61 ||  354 || 5.8 || 31 ||  2\n| 1 || 11 || 11.0\n| 2,929\n|-\n| [[2010 Stanford Cardinal football team|2010]]\n|  263 || 372 || 3,338 || 70.7% || 32 || 8 || 170.2\n|  55 ||  453 || 8.2 || 58 || 3\n| 0 || 0 || 0\n| 3,791\n|-\n| [[2011 Stanford Cardinal football team|2011]]\n|  288 || 404 || 3,517 || 71.3% || 37 || 10 || 169.7\n|  47 ||  150 || 3.2 || 17 || 2\n| 1 || 13 || 13.0\n| 3,667\n|-\n! Total\n! 713 !! 1,064 !! 9,430 !! 67.0% !! 82 !! 22 !! 162.8\n! 163 !!  957 !! 5.9 !! 58 !! 7 !! 2 !! 24 !! 12.0\n! 10,387\n|}\nReference: [https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/andrew-luck-1.html Andrew Luck profile at Sports-Reference.com]\n\n===Awards and honors===\n<!---DON'T ADD UNSOURCED AWARDS OR HONORS--->\n'''2011 season'''\n* First-team [[2011 College Football All-America Team|All American]] ([[American Football Coaches Association|AFCA]], [[Walter Camp Football Foundation|Walter Camp]], [[ESPN.com]], [[Pro Football Weekly|PFW]])\n* [[Maxwell Award]]\n* [[Walter Camp Award|Walter Camp Player of the Year Award]]\n* [[Johnny Unitas Golden Arm Award]]\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] runner-up\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] finalist\n* [[Manning Award]] finalist\n* [[List of Football Academic All-America Team Members of the Year|Academic All-America of the Year]] ([[College Sports Information Directors of America|CoSIDA]])\n* [[2011 Pac-12 Conference football season#Awards and honors|Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Year]]\n* First-team [[2011 Pac-12 Conference football season#Awards and honors|All-Pac-12]]\n* [[2011 Pac-12 Conference football season#Players of the week|Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Week]], October 17, 2011\n\n==== Legacy ====\n\nFor Stanford fans, though, Luck's individual honors were secondary to his transformative impact on the program:\n\n* Stanford had never won more than 10 games in a season (three times, twice before WWII) when Luck's 2010 team won 12. \n* Its best 2-year win total had been 18 wins (four times, last in 1991\u201392); Luck's teams won 23 in 2010\u20132011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://football.stassen.com/cgi-bin/records/fetch-team.pl?team=Stanford|title=All-Time Records for Stanford|last=|first=|date=|website=STASSEN.com|access-date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>  \n* When Luck arrived, Stanford had enjoyed a grand total of three weeks in the AP top ten since 1971.  It spent 24 weeks in the top ten in 2010 and 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegepollarchive.com/football/ap/app_streaks_weeks.cfm?teamid=46&streak=top10#.W6fboYopChA|title=College Poll Archive \u2013 AP Weekly Appearance Streaks: Stanford / Top 10|last=|first=|date=|website=collegepollarchive.com|access-date=}}</ref>\n*Stanford earned its first-ever BCS bowl berth in 2010, and a second in 2011.\n\nIn 2012, an appreciative but anonymous donor endowed a permanent chair for Stanford's offensive coordinator position, to be known as the \u201cAndrew Luck Director of Offense.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/si-wire/2012/05/22/stanford-football-coaching-position-renamed-for-andrew-luck|title=Stanford football coaching position renamed for Andrew Luck|last=Abnos|first=Alexander|date=May 22, 2012|website=SI.com|access-date=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nIn September 2010, before Luck's sophomore season, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''\u2032s Tony Pauline considered him \"the most NFL-ready of all the draft-eligible quarterback prospects.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1174040/index.htm |title=Underclassmen WRs among top 2011 NFL Draft offensive prospects |work=SI.com |date=September 3, 2010 |first=Tony |last=Pauline }}</ref> After a stellar sophomore year, Luck was widely projected to be the No. 1 pick in the [[2011 NFL Draft]], but decided to return for his junior year.<ref name=\"Luck ESPN\" /> In May 2011 he was unanimously projected as the top prospect for the [[2012 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/story/15014424/flash-forward-top-32-picks-for-the-2012-nfl-draft |title=Flash forward: Top 32 picks for the 2012 NFL Draft |date=May 1, 2011 |work=[[CBSSports.com]] |first=Pete |last=Prisco |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928011232/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/story/15014424/flash-forward-top-32-picks-for-the-2012-nfl-draft |archivedate=September 28, 2011 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/football/nfl/05/03/2012.prospects/ |title=Stanford's Luck headlines early look at top 2012 draft prospects |work=Sports Illustrated |date=May 3, 2011 |first=Tony |last=Pauline }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/15029593/mock-draft-first-look-with-luck-and-heels |title=2012 mock draft: First look with Luck and Heels |work=CBSSports.com |date=May 4, 2011 |first=Chad |last=Reuter |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522225342/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/draft/story/15029593/mock-draft-first-look-with-luck-and-heels |archivedate=May 22, 2012 |df= }}</ref> By midseason, Pauline described him as \"the best quarterback since [[Peyton Manning]]\" in [[1998 NFL Draft|1998]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/tony_pauline/10/24/top.50/ |title=Andrew Luck, Trent Richardson high in midseason NFL draft rankings |date=October 24, 2011 |work=SI.com |first=Tony |last=Pauline }}</ref> while ''[[ESPN]]''\u2032s [[Mel Kiper Jr.]] went even further, calling Luck the best quarterback prospect since [[John Elway]] in [[1983 NFL Draft|1983]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/feature/video/_/id/7303334/ultimate-scouting-report |work=ESPN |title=It's All About Luck: Ultimate Scouting Report |date=January 16, 2012 }}</ref> Despite [[Robert Griffin III]]\u2032s impressive [[Heisman Trophy]]-winning season, Luck's status as the No. 1 overall draft prospect was never questioned.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1193759/index.htm |title=2012 NFL Mock Draft: Post-BCS Championship Game version |date=January 12, 2012 |work=SI.com |first=Andrew |last=Perloff }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/don_banks/01/26/mock-draft/index.html |title=Pre-Super Bowl Mock Draft |work=SI.com |date=January 27, 2012 |first=Don |last=Banks }}</ref>\n\nThroughout the [[2011 NFL season]], some fans called for their teams to try to lose their remaining games (or \"[[Tanking (sports)#Encouragement by fans|Suck for Luck]]\") in order to improve their chances at the first pick in the draft.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/10/21/us/suck-for-luck-could-be-best-hope-for-nfls-worst/index.html |date=October 21, 2011 |title='Suck for Luck' could be best hope for NFL's worst |first=Steve |last=Politi |work=CNN }}</ref> By midseason the [[2011 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]] were believed to be the \"frontrunners\" for the No. 1 pick and drew criticism from their former franchise quarterback [[Dan Marino]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcmiami.com/news/sports/Marino-Says-Dolphins-Shouldnt-Suck-for-Luck-131463493.html |title=Marino Says Dolphins Shouldn't Suck for Luck |work=NBC Miami |date=October 13, 2011 |first=David |last=Hill }}</ref> The [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], who were without starting quarterback [[Peyton Manning]], won the \"Luck sweepstakes\" with a 2\u201314 record.<ref name=\"farmer20120128\">{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-super-bowl-quarterbacks-20120129,0,4590029,full.story | title=In the NFL, it's (almost) all about the quarterback | work=Los Angeles Times | date=January 28, 2012 | accessdate=January 28, 2012 | author=Farmer, Sam}}</ref>\n\nEnding speculations on April 24, Colts general manager [[Ryan Grigson]] announced the team would take Luck with their first overall draft pick.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Luck will be Indianapolis Colts' first pick in NFL draft|url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/story/09000d5d8288de6e/article/andrew-luck-will-be-indianapolis-colts-first-pick-in-nfl-draft?module=News_CP|work=NFL.com}}</ref> The decision became official on draft day, April 26, 2012. Luck was the fourth Stanford quarterback to be selected first overall, after [[Bobby Garrett]] in [[1954 NFL Draft|1954]], [[Jim Plunkett]] in [[1971 NFL Draft|1971]], and Elway in [[1983 NFL Draft|1983]]. Luck was the second Stanford quarterback to be taken first overall by the Colts, after Elway.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/schools/stanford/drafted.htm |title=Stanford Drafted Players/Alumni |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{NFL predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 4\n|       weight = 234\n|         dash = 4.67\n|    ten split = 1.62\n| twenty split = 2.63\n|      shuttle = 4.28\n|   cone drill = 6.80\n|     vertical = 36\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 4\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = 37<ref name=\"Wonderlic\"/>\n|     arm span = 32\u215d\n|    hand span = 10\n|         note = All values from [[NFL combine]]<ref name=\"Wonderlic\">{{cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1152058-nfl-draft-2012-did-andrew-luck-or-robert-griffin-iii-score-better-on-wonderlic |title=NFL Draft 2012: Did Andrew Luck or Robert Griffin III Score Better on Wonderlic? |last=Kruse |first=Zach |work=[[Bleacher Report]] |date=April 19, 2012 |accessdate= January 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.nfl.com/combine/profiles/andrew-luck?id=2533031 |title= Andrew Luck QB Stanford |work=[[NFL.com]] |accessdate= January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2012 season: Rookie year===\n[[File:Andrew Luck 2013.jpg|thumb|225px|Luck vs. the Ravens during a Wild Card playoff game on January 6, 2013.]]\nOn July 19, 2012, Luck signed a four-year contract with the [[Indianapolis Colts]] worth $22 million.<ref>{{cite news|title=Colts sign top draft pick Andrew Luck to four-year deal expected to be worth $22 million|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20120719/SPORTS03/120719025/Colts-sign-Andrew-Luck-four-year-deal|work=IndyStar.com|first=Mike|last=Chappell}}</ref> The deal made Luck the fourth starting quarterback for the Colts in the past two NFL seasons,<ref>{{cite web|title=With Andrew Luck Signed, Indianapolis Colts Officially Ready for \"New Era\"|url=http://www.colts101.com/2012/07/20/with-andrew-luck-signed-indianapolis-colts-officially-ready-for-new-era/|access-date=July 20, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220320/http://www.colts101.com/2012/07/20/with-andrew-luck-signed-indianapolis-colts-officially-ready-for-new-era/|archive-date=October 4, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> following [[Kerry Collins]], [[Curtis Painter]], and [[Dan Orlovsky]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/thehuddle/post/2011/11/colts-tab-qb-dan-orlovsky-as-third-starter-of-2011/1#.UBBuabTY8g0 |title=Colts tab QB Dan Orlovsky as third starter of 2011 |last=Davis |first=Nate |date=November 29, 2011 |work=USA Today}}</ref> In his debut, a preseason game against the [[2012 St. Louis Rams season|St. Louis Rams]], Luck's first pass was a 63-yard touchdown to running back [[Donald Brown (American football)|Donald Brown]]. He also threw a touchdown pass to receiver [[Austin Collie]]. In his second preseason game, a 26\u201324 loss to the [[2012 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], Luck played the first half and ran for one touchdown, with two interceptions.<ref>{{cite web |author= |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/48720603/ns/sports-nfl/ |title=Luck throws 2 INTs in loss to Steelers \u2013 NFL- NBC Sports |publisher=Nbcsports.msnbc.com |date=August 20, 2012 |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120822184344/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/48720603/ns/sports-nfl |archive-date=August 22, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn his regular-season debut, Luck threw his first career interception to [[2012 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] cornerback [[Tim Jennings]]<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-game-highlights/0ap2000000059664/WK-1-Can-t-Miss-Play-Andrew-Luck-s-first-interception |title=NFL Videos: WK 1 Can't Miss Play: Andrew Luck's first interception |publisher=Nfl.com |date= |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> and his first career touchdown pass to [[Donnie Avery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/playbyplay?gameId=320909003&period=4 |title=Indianapolis Colts vs. Chicago Bears \u2013 Play By Play \u2013 September 09, 2012 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref> Ultimately, Luck completed 23 of 45 passes for 309 yards, a touchdown, and three interceptions, as the Colts lost 41\u201321.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000060073/article/andrew-luck-up-and-down-in-indianapolis-colts-debut?module=HP11_content_stream |title=Andrew Luck up and down in Indianapolis Colts debut |last=Copeland |first=Kareem |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=September 10, 2012}}</ref> The next week against the [[2012 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Luck threw for 224 yards and two touchdowns with no interceptions. He got his first career win and did it by completing the first game-winning drive of his professional career.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209160clt.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 September 16th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Luck won his first career road and overtime game during a week 8 game against the division rival [[2012 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]]. A touchdown pass to running back [[Vick Ballard]] on the first drive of overtime gave the Colts a 19\u201313 victory. In a Week 9 win against the [[2012 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Luck threw for 433 yards, a new record for most yards in a game by a rookie quarterback (surpassing [[Cam Newton]]'s 432 against the [[Green Bay Packers]] in 2011). He later sent his jersey from the Dolphins game to the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000091836/article/andrew-lucks-colts-jersey-makes-nfl-hall-of-fame|title=Andrew Luck's Colts jersey makes Pro Football Hall of Fame|work=[[National Football League]]|date=November 7, 2012|accessdate=November 7, 2012}}</ref> Through Week 9, Luck had thrown for the same number of yards as his predecessor, Peyton Manning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000089564/article/andrew-luck-sets-nfls-singlegame-rookie-passing-record|title=Andrew Luck sets NFL's single-game rookie passing record|work=[[National Football League]]|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=November 4, 2012}}</ref> In Week 13 against the [[2012 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], Luck and the Colts were trailing 33\u201321 with 2:39 left. After throwing a touchdown to fellow rookie [[LaVon Brazill]], Luck and the Colts were able to get the ball back and get to the Lions' 14-yard line, facing a 4th down with four seconds left. Luck then threw a screen pass to Donnie Avery, who got free and ran in for the winning score, a big moment in Luck's early career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Dunleavy|first=Nate|title=Colts vs. Lions: Andrew Luck Leads Miracle Comeback Luck and the Colts finished with an 11\u20135 record and earned the 5 seed in the AFC Playoffs. The Colts fell to the Baltimore Ravens 9\u201324 in the AFC Wild Card round in Baltimore. (Again)|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1430010-colts-vs-lions-andrew-luck-leads-miracle-comback-again|accessdate=December 2, 2012}}</ref> The win gave Luck his eighth of the season\u2014the most wins by a rookie quarterback drafted first overall in NFL history\u2014as well as his fifth game-winning drive on the season, tying [[Vince Young]] and [[Ben Roethlisberger]] for the most by a rookie quarterback.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fifthdown.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/12/04/andrew-luck-beating-odds-with-colts/|title=It's Almost Unfair: Andrew Luck and the Colts|first=Chase|last=Stuart|website=The Fifth Down|date=December 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\nStarting every game, Luck led the Colts to 11 wins\u2014a record for rookie quarterbacks drafted first overall, where the previous record was 8\u2014and reached the playoffs with a team that had gone 2\u201314 the year before. Playing against the [[2012 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] on December 23, 2012, Luck broke the record for most passing yards in a season by a rookie, throwing 205 to bring his season total to 4,183. [[Cam Newton]] held the previous record with 4,051 yards.<ref name=\"McIntyre\">{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/andrew-luck-sets-rookie-passing-records-colts-clinch-214556362--nfl.html|title=Andrew Luck sets rookie passing records as Colts clinch spot in AFC playoffs|last=McIntyre|first=Brian|work=Yahoo.com|date=December 23, 2012|accessdate=December 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\n[[File:Andrew Luck signing autographs at 2014 Pro Bowl.jpg|thumb|left|Luck signing autographs for fans at the [[2014 Pro Bowl|2013 Pro Bowl]]]]\nIn 2013, Luck was reunited with offensive coordinator [[Pep Hamilton]], who was his offensive coordinator and quarterback coach at Stanford. In week 1 against the [[2013 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], Luck capped off another comeback win by scoring a 20-yard rushing touchdown in a 21\u201317 win.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2013/09/08/raiders-colts-week1/2782659/|title=Andrew Luck, Colts fend off Terrelle Pryor, Raiders|publisher=usatoday.com|agency=Associated Press|date=September 8, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref> After a Week 2 loss to the [[2013 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Luck defeated his former [[Stanford University|Stanford]] coach [[Jim Harbaugh]] in a 27\u20137 win against the [[2013 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] in Week 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/luck-outplays-kaepernick-as-colts-beat-49ers/|title=Luck outplays Kaepernick ad Colts beat 49ers|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|date=September 22, 2013|accessdate=September 23, 2013}}</ref> After falling behind early to the [[2013 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] in Week 4, Luck and the Colts scored 37 unanswered points to win 37\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Colts-Zoom-Past-Jacksonville-37-3/58324e05-ca49-472d-a34b-f6d2114b448e|title=Colts Zoom Past Jacksonville, 37\u20133|last=Kelley|first=Craig|publisher=colts.com|date=September 29, 2013|accessdate=September 29, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202185515/http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Colts-Zoom-Past-Jacksonville-37-3/58324e05-ca49-472d-a34b-f6d2114b448e|archive-date=February 2, 2015|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> The win gave Luck a 14\u20136 record through his first 20 games, tying him with [[John Elway]] for the best record through 20 games for a quarterback selected first overall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/photoessays/0ap2000000254639/mindblowing-stats-for-week-5-of-the-2013-nfl-season#photo=1|title=Mind-blowing stats for Week 5 of the NFL season|publisher=NFL.com|date=October 2, 2013|accessdate=October 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, Luck led the Colts to a 34\u201328 win over the then-undefeated [[2013 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] in his first game against fellow sophomore quarterback [[Russell Wilson]]. Luck also recorded his ninth career fourth-quarter comeback in the win, handing Seattle their first regular-season loss since November 25, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2013100603/2013/REG5/seahawks@colts#menu=highlights&tab=recap|title=Luck leads Colts in late rally to topple Seahawks|publisher=NFL.com|date=October 6, 2013|accessdate=October 6, 2013}}</ref> The Colts traveled to San Diego to face the [[2013 San Diego Chargers season|Chargers]] for a Week 6 ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' match, the first of Luck's career. Indianapolis was dominated in time of possession and lost 19\u20139.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201310140sdg.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at San Diego Chargers \u2013 October 14th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 17, 2017}}</ref> In week 7, Peyton Manning made his return to [[Lucas Oil Stadium]] to play Luck on ''NBC Sunday Night Football''. The Colts lead at halftime 26\u201314 and survived a near comeback by the previously undefeated [[2013 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] to win 39\u201333, going into a [[bye week]]. The win also snapped Denver's 17-game regular-season winning streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nfl/story/?id=434637|title=Luck, Colts knock off Broncos in Manning's return|work=TSN.ca|date=October 21, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> Luck won his second AFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance against the Broncos, going 21\u201338 for 228 yards with 3 touchdown passes, 1 rushing touchdown, and no interceptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000268327/article/andrew-luck-matt-ryan-among-players-of-the-week|title=Andrew Luck, Matt Ryan among players of the week|last=Patra|first=Kevin|work=[[National Football League|NFL]]|date=October 23, 2013|accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> After a Week 8 bye, Luck engineered his tenth career fourth-quarter comeback, scoring 15 points in the quarter to defeat the [[2013 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]] by a score of 27\u201324. He threw three touchdowns, all to fellow sophomore Colt [[T. Y. Hilton]], and finished with 271 passing yards with no interceptions. During Week 14, the Colts won their first division championship under Luck and were the first team to clinch their division that season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2013/12/8/5190022/colts-win-afc-south-thanks-to-peyton-manning|title=Colts Win AFC South Thanks to Peyton Manning|last=Wilson|first=Josh|work=stampedeblue.com|date=December 8, 2013|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> The next week, Luck threw for 2 touchdowns in a 25\u20133 victory over the Houston Texans in their second divisional matchup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2013/12/17/5219502/2013-nfl-week-fifteen-inside-the-colts-numbers|title=2013 NFL Week Fifteen: Inside The Colts Numbers|last=Grecco|first=Matt|work=stampedeblue.com|date=December 17, 2013|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 16 23-7 victory over the [[2013 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]], Luck threw for 241 yards and a touchdown. In doing so, he passed Peyton Manning for second place for quarterback passing yards through 2 seasons with 7,914 (Manning had 7,874 in his first 2 seasons).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2013/12/26/5239428/andrew-luck-recap-game-fifteen-vs-chiefs|title=Andrew Luck Recap: Game Fifteen vs. Chiefs|last=Wilson|first=Josh|work=stampedeblue.com|date=December 26, 2013|accessdate=December 27, 2013}}</ref> In week 17, Luck broke [[Cam Newton]]'s record for yards passing in the first two seasons of a career, with 8,196 yards (Newton had 7,920 yards) in a win against the Jacksonville Jaguars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldbulletin.com/breakingnews/x1353074045/Luck-Colts-blow-out-Jaguars-30-10|title=Luck, Colts blow out Jaguars 30\u201310|work=heraldbulletin.com/|date=December 29, 2013|accessdate=January 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLuck played his first NFL home playoff game on January 4, 2014, against the fifth-seeded Kansas City Chiefs in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC: Indianapolis Colts 45, Kansas City Chiefs 44|Wild Card Round]]. After the Colts fell back by 28 points, he led a historic comeback, capping the game with a 64-yard touchdown pass to [[T. Y. Hilton]] to take the lead for the first time, 45\u201344. The Colts defense would then deny [[Alex Smith]] a chance to get Kansas City within field goal range to end the game. Luck completed 29 passes for 433 yards and 4 touchdowns, in addition to recovering a fumble for a key touchdown, to record the second-biggest comeback in NFL playoff history<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2014/01/04/colts-chiefs-wild-card-playoffs-andrew-luck/4321311/|title=Andrew Luck leads Colts back from 28-point hole to beat Chiefs|last=Corbett|first=Jim|work=usatoday.com|date=January 4, 2014|accessdate=January 4, 2014}}</ref> and the largest comeback to end in regulation. This game was ranked #1 on NFL.com's Top Games of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/labs/rr/top20games/game/01/copy|title=Top 20 NFL Games of 2013 \u2013 Game 1 Chiefs at Colts AFC Wild Card Game|publisher=}}</ref> The Colts lost to the [[2013 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] 43\u201322 in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 43, Indianapolis Colts 22|Divisional Round]] of the playoffs the following week. Luck threw for 331 yards, two touchdowns, and four interceptions.<ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2014/1/8/5285192/andrew-luck-recap-wild-card-game-vs-chiefs|title=Andrew Luck Recap: Wild Card Game vs. Chiefs|last=Wilson|first=Josh|work=stampedeblue.com|date=January 8, 2014|accessdate=January 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLuck was named to his second Pro Bowl on January 19, 2014, replacing [[Russell Wilson]] due to Wilson's participation in [[Super Bowl XLVIII]]. He went on to be taken first overall by [[Deion Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2014/1/19/5326114/andrew-luck-is-heading-to-the-pro-bowl|title=Andrew Luck is Heading to the Pro Bowl|last=Wilson|first=Andrew|work=stampedeblue.com|date=January 19, 2014|accessdate=January 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/01/19/andrew-luck-added-to-pro-bowl-roster/|title=Andrew Luck added to Pro Bowl roster|last=Wilkening|first=Mike|work=nbcsports.com|date=January 19, 2014|accessdate=January 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014 season===\nOpening the season with his second game against his predecessor, [[Peyton Manning]], Luck passed for 370 yards and 2 touchdowns with 2 interceptions. After rallying from a 24\u20130 deficit following halftime, the Colts fell short of the comeback and lost to the [[2014 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] 31\u201324.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070den.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at Denver Broncos \u2013 September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 2 loss against the [[2014 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Luck threw for 3 touchdowns, passing [[Jim Harbaugh]] for fourth on the Colts' all-time list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kspr.com/sports/recap-eagles-30-colts-27/21051914_28078318 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140916070310/http://www.kspr.com/sports/recap-eagles-30-colts-27/21051914_28078318 |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 16, 2014 |title=Recap: Eagles 30, Colts 27 |publisher=[[KGHZ|KSPR]] |date=September 15, 2014 |accessdate=September 24, 2014 }}</ref> Looking to avoid losing three consecutive games for the first time in his career, Luck completed 31 of 39 passes for 370 yards and 4 touchdowns against the [[2014 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]] to win 44\u201317 in Week 3. He was named the AFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance, the third time he has won the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Andrew-Luck-Named-AFC-Offensive-Player-Of-The-Week/210a95ca-3f9a-4734-b7dc-0986d0b4cec1|title=Andrew Luck Named AFC Player Of The Week|last=Bowen|first=Kevin|work=colts.com|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=September 24, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923205517/http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Andrew-Luck-Named-AFC-Offensive-Player-Of-The-Week/210a95ca-3f9a-4734-b7dc-0986d0b4cec1|archive-date=September 23, 2015|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn a Week 4 win against the [[2014 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Luck became the first quarterback in NFL history to throw for 370 yards or more, 4 touchdowns, and have a completion percentage 70 percent or above in consecutive games.<ref name=\"sports.yahoo.com\">{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/colts-qb-andrew-luck-playing-004454480.html|title=Colts QB Andrew Luck is Playing Phenomenal Football this Season|last=Wilson|first=Josh|work=sports.yahoo.com|date=September 28, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> He would continue his winning ways in Week 5 against the [[2014 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], throwing 312 yards with a touchdown pass, as well as 1 rushing touchdown, to win 20\u201313.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2014100503/2014/REG5/ravens@colts#menu=gameinfo&tab=analyze|title=Colts defense leads win over Ravens|work=NFL.com|date=October 5, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Luck would record his fourth-consecutive 300 yard game on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' against the [[2014 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]]. Indianapolis jumped out to a 24\u20130 lead after 1 quarter, and would hold on to beat the Texans 33\u201328.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2014100900/2014/REG6/colts@texans#menu=gameinfo%7CcontentId%3A0ap3000000408386&tab=recap&recap=fullstory|title=Andrew Luck, T.Y. Hilton key Colts' victory over Texans|work=NFL.com|date=October 9, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref> Through Week 6, Luck had thrown for 1,987 yards and 17 touchdowns, leading the league in both, and establishing career-highs through 6 games.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/football/2014/10/10/lucks_throws_three_touchdowns_as_colts_beat_texans.html|title=Luck throws three TDs as Colts hang on to beat Texans|last=Rieken|first=Kristie|work=[[Toronto Star]]|date=October 10, 2014|accessdate=October 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Luck2014.jpg|thumb|left|Luck vs. the Bengals in 2014]]\nLuck continued his excellent play in Week 7 against the [[2014 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], passing for over 300 yards for the 5th consecutive game, tying the Colts record set by Peyton Manning. He would finish the day with 344 passing yards and 2 touchdowns, as Indianapolis defeated the Bengals, 27\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2014/10/19/colts-d-dominant-victory-cincinnati/17576265/|title=Colts' D is dominant in shutout win over Bengals|last=Keefer|first=Zack|work=[[The Indianapolis Star|Indy Star]]|date=October 19, 2014|accessdate=October 19, 2014}}</ref> The shutout victory was the first for Indianapolis since a 23\u20130 win over the Tennessee Titans in December 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theindychannel.com/sports/colts/four-down-territory-colts-shutout-bengals|title=Four-Down Territory: Colts shutout Bengals|last=Chappell|first=Mike|website=theindychannel.com|date=October 19, 2014|accessdate=October 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021122734/http://www.theindychannel.com/sports/colts/four-down-territory-colts-shutout-bengals|archive-date=October 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Luck broke his single-season touchdown mark in the Colts Week 9 game against the [[2014 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], throwing four to bring his total to 26. He also became the first quarterback in 2014 to reach 3,000 passing yards.<ref name=\"Week 9 2014\">{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/american-football/news/12040/9548998/nfl-andrew-luck-throws-four-touchdowns-as-indianapolis-colts-beat-new-york-giants |title=NFL: Andrew Luck throws four touchdowns as Indianapolis Colts beat New York Giants |last=Higham |first=Paul |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |date=November 4, 2014 |accessdate=November 4, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141104234935/http://www1.skysports.com/american-football/news/12040/9548998/nfl-andrew-luck-throws-four-touchdowns-as-indianapolis-colts-beat-new-york-giants |archivedate=November 4, 2014 |df= }}</ref> In Week 13, Luck threw a career-high 5 touchdown passes in a 49\u201327 win over the [[2014 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411300clt.htm |title=Washington Redskins at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 November 30th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> In addition, he also became the first quarterback to reach 4,000 passing yards in 2014. On December 4, Luck was named the AFC Offensive Player of the Month for November. In the month, Luck passed for 1,280 yards, 12 touchdowns, and had a quarterback rating of 112.0.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.colts.com/2014/12/04/indianapolis-colts-qb-andrew-luck-named-afc-offensive-player-of-the-month/?adbid=10153479524735110&adbpl=fb&adbpr=133691530109&campaign=fb_vid__20141204_36697717|title=Indianapolis Colts QB-Andrew Luck Named AFC Offensive Player of the Month|work=Colts.com|date=December 4, 2014|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref> Entering a Week 14 matchup with the [[2014 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Luck needed only 81 yards to surpass Peyton Manning for the most passing yards by a quarterback in their first 3 seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400554422|title=Andrew Luck rallies Colts past Browns with game-winning drive|work=scores.espn.go.com|date=December 7, 2014|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Luck passed for 294 yards to take the record, and engineered a fourth-quarter comeback by throwing a 1-yard touchdown pass to T. Y. Hilton to win the game 25\u201324.<ref name=\"Most passing 3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/football/andrew-luck-rebounds-colts-edge-browns-25-24-article-1.2037047|title=Andrew Luck rebounds, Colts edge Browns, 25\u201324|work=nydailynews.com|date=December 7, 2014|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Andrew Luck vs Browns 2014.jpg|thumb|Luck vs. the Browns in 2014]]\n\nAfter a Week 15 win against the Texans, Luck successfully led the Colts to the playoffs for the third straight year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/153955/andrew-luck-is-3-for-3-in-making-the-playoffs|title=Colts' Andrew Luck is 3-for-3 in making the playoffs|last=Wells|first=Mike|website=[[ESPN.com]]|date=December 14, 2014|accessdate=December 19, 2014}}</ref> Along with the division title, Luck also earned his third straight Pro Bowl berth.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/nflnation/post/_/id/155666/2015-pro-bowl-andrew-luck-leads-group-of-five-indianapolis-colts|title=2015 Pro Bowl: Andrew Luck leads group of five Indianapolis Colts|last=Wells|first=Mike|website=ESPN.com|date=December 23, 2014|accessdate=December 26, 2014}}</ref> In Week 17, Luck broke Peyton Manning's franchise record for passing yards in a single-season. In addition, he became the 8th quarterback in NFL history to throw for 40 or more touchdowns in a single season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SiriusXMNFL/status/549285435638177792|title=SiriusXM NFL Radio on Twitter|work=[[Twitter]]|date=December 28, 2014|accessdate=December 28, 2014}}</ref> In the Colts' [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: Indianapolis Colts 26, Cincinnati Bengals 10|Wild Card Round]] game against the Cincinnati Bengals, Luck completed 31 of 44 passes for 376 yards and 1 touchdown, leading the team to a 26\u201310 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/colts-beat-bengals-to-set-up-rematch-at-denver/|title=Colts beat Bengals to set up showdown in Denver|publisher=[[Sportsnet]]|date=January 4, 2015|accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref> He then went on to complete 27 of 43 passes and throw for 265 yards, 2 touchdowns, and 2 interceptions in a 24\u201313 Indianapolis victory over the Denver Broncos in the AFC [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC: Indianapolis Colts 24, Denver Broncos 13|Divisional Round]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501110den.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at Denver Broncos \u2013 January 11th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> In the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 45, Indianapolis Colts 7|AFC Championship]], Luck and the Colts fell to the [[2014 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], 45\u20137.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201501180nwe.htm |title=AFC Championship \u2013 Indianapolis Colts at New England Patriots \u2013 January 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 20, 2017}}</ref> Luck was also the league's [[List of National Football League season passing touchdowns leaders|leader in passing touchdowns]] for the first time in his career.\n\nIn the Pro Bowl, Luck was Team Carter's starting quarterback. In the game, he completed 9 out of 10 passes, with 119 yards, and 2 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/nfl/boxscore?id=7347 |title=Team Irvin All-Pros vs. Team Carter All-Pros \u2013 Box Score \u2013 January 25, 2015 |website=www.foxsports.com |language=en-US |access-date=November 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2015 season===\nOn April 9, the Colts announced they had picked up the fifth-year option on Luck's contract, which will pay him a guaranteed $16.55 million in 2016. In Weeks 4 and 5, Luck missed the first two games of his career with an injured shoulder. Backup [[Matt Hasselbeck]] played in his place and led the team to a 16\u201313 overtime win over the [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], followed by a 27\u201320 ''Thursday Night Football'' victory over the [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000484524/article/colts-pick-up-fifthyear-option-on-andrew-luck|title=Colts pick up fifth-year option on Andrew Luck|last=Orr|first=Conor|work=NFL.com|date=April 9, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2015}}</ref> Luck returned to the lineup on October 18 in a 34\u201327 loss to the [[2015 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510180clt.htm |title=New England Patriots at Indianapolis Colts \u2013 October 18th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> On November 2, Luck led the Colts back from a 17-point deficit in the fourth quarter to force overtime against the [[2015 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], but his third interception of the game helped lead to the Panthers' 29\u201326 win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/indianapolis-colts-carolina-panthers-20151102029/|title=Indianapolis 26 \u2013 29 Carolina: Final OT \u2013 2015-11-02 \u2013 National Football League \u2013 Yahoo! Sports|website=Yahoo Sports}}</ref> On November 10, it was announced that Luck would miss 2\u20136 weeks with a lacerated kidney and a partially torn abdominal muscle, suffered during the fourth quarter of the Colts 27\u201324 win over the previously undefeated [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]] two days prior.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/football/nfl/colts-qb-luck-out-2-6-weeks-with-lacerated-kidney/|title=Colts QB Luck out 2\u20136 weeks with lacerated kidney|last=Simmons|first=Jeff|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 10, 2015|accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref> However, the recovery process took much longer than expected and Luck did not return for the rest of the season. The Colts failed to make the playoffs for the first time with Luck, ending the season 8\u20138.<ref>{{cite web|title = Colts QB Luck not cleared to play against Titans|url = http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14467635/indianapolis-colts-rule-andrew-luck-tennessee-titans|website = ESPN.com|accessdate = December 30, 2015}}</ref> He was ranked 92nd by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000660061/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-92-Andrew-Luck|title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 92 Andrew Luck|website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n===2016 season===\nOn June 29, the Colts announced Luck had signed a six-year extension worth $140 million, with $87 million guaranteed, making him the highest paid player in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/16621472/andrew-luck-indianapolis-colts-87-million-guaranteed-contract-letdown-future-quarterbacks |title=Andrew Luck got paid, but he should have held out for more |publisher=ESPN.com|first=Dan|last=Graziano|date=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000672131/article/andrew-luck-signs-sixyear-140-million-colts-contract |title=Andrew Luck signs six-year, $140 million Colts contract |first=Gregg|last=Rosenthal|publisher=NFL.com|date=June 29, 2016|accessdate=June 29, 2016}}</ref> In a 41\u201310 win over the [[2016 New York Jets season|New York Jets]] in Week 13, Luck passed for 278 yards and four touchdowns, which earned him the AFC Offensive Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Andrew-Luck-Named-AFC-Offensive-Player-Of-The-Week/6ba2ae62-60dc-4ef4-bab5-fac9bb7c97f5?sf45296272=1|title=Andrew Luck Named AFC Offensive Player Of The Week|last=Bowen|first=Kevin|work=colts.com|date=December 7, 2016|accessdate=December 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170902190525/http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Andrew-Luck-Named-AFC-Offensive-Player-Of-The-Week/6ba2ae62-60dc-4ef4-bab5-fac9bb7c97f5?sf45296272=1|archive-date=September 2, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000752902/article/andrew-luck-headlines-nfl-players-of-the-week?campaign=Twitter_atn |title=Andrew Luck headlines NFL Players of the Week |last=Lewis |first=Edward |date=December 7, 2016 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> In the 2016 season, Luck threw for 4,240 yards and 31 touchdowns, and a career-high  63.5 completion percentage, despite missing one game due to a concussion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/L/LuckAn00/gamelog/2016 |title=Andrew Luck 2016 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> He was also ranked 51st by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000810436/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-51-Andrew-Luck|title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 51 Andrew Luck|website=NFL.com}}</ref> Shortly following the 2016 season, Luck underwent surgery to repair an issue with his right (throwing) shoulder that had been lingering since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Luck has surgery to fix right shoulder|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/18508604/andrew-luck-indianapolis-colts-undergoes-shoulder-surgery|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2017 season: Lost season with shoulder injury===\nFollowing surgery on his shoulder during the off-season, Luck was held out of training camp and the preseason, and it was announced he was to miss regular season games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000838891/article/colts-gm-andrew-luck-will-not-play-week-1-vs-rams |title=Colts GM: Andrew Luck will not play Week 1 vs. Rams |last=Sessler |first=Marc |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=September 4, 2017}}</ref> [[Scott Tolzien]] started for the season opener against the [[2017 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], and the newly acquired [[Jacoby Brissett]] took over as the starter in Week 2 against the [[2017 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]]. Following the Colts' Week 4 loss to the [[2017 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], Colts' general manager [[Chris Ballard (American football)|Chris Ballard]] stated that Luck would begin practicing but was not ready to fully return to games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000855781/article/colts-gm-andrew-luck-will-return-to-practice-this-week|title=Colts GM: Andrew Luck will return to practice this week|work=[[NFL]]|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=October 3, 2017}}</ref> On November 2, the Colts placed Luck on [[injured reserve]], meaning that he was ruled out for the 2017 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Colts-To-Place-Andrew-Luck-On-Injured-Reserve/91f39778-f534-4ca4-8604-aac9767db261 |title=Colts To Place Andrew Luck On Injured Reserve |last=Walker |first=Andrew |date=November 2, 2017 |website=Colts.com |access-date=November 2, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231043653/http://www.colts.com/news/article-1/Colts-To-Place-Andrew-Luck-On-Injured-Reserve/91f39778-f534-4ca4-8604-aac9767db261 |archive-date=December 31, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rapoport|first1=Ian|title=Andrew Luck advised not to throw for months to focus on rehab|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000871706/article/andrew-luck-advised-not-to-throw-for-months-to-focus-on-rehab|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> On November 11, it was revealed that Luck was traveling to Europe to seek additional treatment for his previously injured shoulder.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lewis|first1=Edward|title=Andrew Luck to go to Europe for additional treatment|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000875137/article/andrew-luck-to-go-to-europe-for-additional-treatment|publisher=NFL|accessdate=November 11, 2017}}</ref> After returning to the U.S., Luck was put through a throwing program. This led him to travel to Los Angeles to go through rehab with a throwing coach. Ballard stated on February 7, 2018, that Luck would not need an additional surgery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Colts GM: Andrew Luck doesn't need another surgery|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000915239/article/colts-gm-andrew-luck-doesnt-need-another-surgery|website=NFL.com|accessdate=February 9, 2018|date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018 season: Final season===\n[[File:Andrew Luck (44010386874).jpg|thumb|Luck passing against the Redskins in 2018]]\nLuck started Week 1 on September 9, 2018 against the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], his first game in 616 days. He had 319 passing yards, two touchdowns and an interception, and set a career-high in completions with 39, but the Colts lost 34\u201323.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/09/10/andrew-luck-return-to-lineup-was-overwhelming |title=Andrew Luck: Return to lineup was \"overwhelming\" |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=September 10, 2018 |work=ProFootballTalk |access-date=October 2, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], with the Colts down 20\u201316 with seconds left in the game, Luck, who had thrown for just 164 yards in the game, was replaced by backup [[Jacoby Brissett]] to attempt a [[Hail Mary pass]] from his own 46-yard line. Brissett overthrew several players in the back of the end zone and the Colts lost the game. The move was questioned by some journalists and fans, and led to some speculation about the health of Luck's shoulder, although head coach [[Frank Reich]] and Luck both said it was purely because Brissett had a stronger throwing arm.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/still-not-100-percent-colts-pull-andrew-luck-off-field-hail-mary-play-203455728.html |title=Still not 100 percent? Colts pull Andrew Luck off field for Hail Mary |last=Young |first=Shalise |work=Yahoo! Sports |access-date=October 2, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> The following week against the [[2018 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Luck threw for four touchdowns and career-highs in completions (40), attempts (62) and yards (464). He led the Colts back from down 28\u201310 in the third quarter, including a game-tying two point conversion with :51 left. However the team lost in overtime, 37\u201334, after Indianapolis failed to convert a 4th and 4 on their own 43 and the Texans kicked the game-winning field goal.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2018/09/30/indianapolis-colts-vs-houston-texans-frank-reichs-questionable-decisions-led-37-34-overtime-loss/1434940002/ |title=Frank Reich's questionable decisions lead to Colts' 37\u201334 overtime loss vs. Texans |last=Ayello |first=Jim |work=Indianapolis Star |access-date=October 2, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In Week 5, on ''Thursday Night Football'' against the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]], he was 38-of-59 for 365 passing yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions as the Colts fell 38\u201324.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/columnists/gregg-doyel/2018/10/05/andrew-luck-cant-beat-new-england-patriots-himself-38-24-indianapolis-colts-loss/1501326002/ |title=Colts' Andrew Luck can't beat Patriots by himself |last=Doyel |first=Gregg |work=Indianapolis Star |access-date=October 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Luck's 121 passing attempts in Weeks 4\u20135 were the most over a two-game span in NFL history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.heraldbulletin.com/sports/colts-seek-balance-to-the-air-force/article_038b37fe-c99b-11e8-a053-1b0fec4c7dd0.html |title=Colts seek balance to the (air) force |last=Bremer |first=George |work=Herald Bulletin |access-date=October 10, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In Week 6, against the New York Jets, he had 301 passing yards, four touchdowns, and three interceptions in the 42\u201334 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/football/news/colts-andrew-luck-comes-up-short-in-comeback/ |title=Colts' Andrew Luck: Comes up short in comeback |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 1\u20135 start to the season, Luck and the Colts went on a five-game winning streak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/clt/2018.htm |title=2018 Indianapolis Colts Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In Week 7, he passed for 156 yards and four touchdowns in a 37\u20135 victory over the [[2018 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/colts-luck-use-efficient-air-show-to-blow-out-bills-37-5/ |title=Colts, Luck use efficient air show to blow out Bills 37\u20135 |website=CBSSports.com|agency=Associated Press |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In the next two games, victories over the [[2018 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]] and [[2018 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]], he passed for three touchdowns in both games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/nfl/index.ssf/2018/10/oakland_raiders_vs_indianapoli_1.html |title=Andrew Luck's three TD passes leads the Indianapolis Colts past the hapless Oakland Raiders: Game recap, score, stats |last=Arnold |first=Geoffrey |website=OregonLive.com |language=en-US |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/ed08fb882ba64aceab98daffb5ca5482 |title=Luck, Ebron lead Colts past struggling Jaguars 29\u201326 |last=Marot |first=Michael |date=November 12, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In Week 11, Luck completed 23 of 29 passes for 297 yards and three touchdowns, posting a 143.8 passer rating, in a 38\u201310 win over the Titans, earning him AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000990812/article/samson-ebukam-barkley-among-players-of-the-week |title=Samson Ebukam, Saquon Barkley among Players of the Week |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=November 21, 2018 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> In a Week 12 27\u201324 victory over the [[2018 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], Luck had his eight consecutive game with at least three passing touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/boston/patriots/resurgent-colts-qb-andrew-luck-closing-tom-brady-nfl-record |title=Luck closing in on Tom Brady NFL record |last=Goss |first=Nick |date=November 26, 2018 |website=NBC Sports Boston |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In Week 16, Luck led a double-digit comeback against the [[2018 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], the 21st fourth quarter comeback of his career, throwing a go-ahead score to [[Chester Rogers]] with 55 seconds left, and winning 28\u201327. The win put the Colts in position for a chance to earn a Wild Card playoff berth the following week in their matchup with the Titans.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/cac61b74ad3a425c8ca349a73ad988a3 |title=Luck keeps Colts in playoff hunt with 28\u201327 win over Giants |last=Marot |first=Michael |date=December 24, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> Luck also set a new in single-season completions in the game, passing his previous mark of 380 in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://coltswire.usatoday.com/2018/12/23/indianapolis-colts-new-york-giants-5-takeaways-week-16/ |title=5 takeaways from Colts' 28-27 comeback win vs. Giants |date=2018-12-24 |website=Colts Wire |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> The Colts defeated the Titans, earning a Wild Card berth and end the season winning nine of ten games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/clt/2018.htm |title=2018 Indianapolis Colts Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> Luck finished his first season back from injury with 4,593 passing yards, 39 touchdowns, and 15 interceptions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sentinel-echo.com/cnhi_network/luck-s-comeback-season-earns-national-praise/article_bed0e52a-1db2-11e9-807c-6b59bd410aa5.html |title=Luck's comeback season earns national praise |last=Bremer |first=George |website=The Sentinel-Echo |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> Luck and the Colts upset the AFC South division champion Houston Texans in the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: Indianapolis Colts 21, Houston Texans 7|Wild Card Round]] by a score of 21\u20137. In the victory, Luck passed for 222 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/01/05/luck-has-2-tds-to-lead-colts-over-texans-21-7-in-wild-card/38850097/ |title=Luck has 2 TDs to lead Colts over Texans 21\u20137 in wild card |website=USA TODAY|agency=Associated Press |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#AFC: Kansas City Chiefs 31, Indianapolis Colts 13|Divisional Round]], the Colts faced off against the [[AFC West]] champion [[2018 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]]. In what ended up being his final game, Luck passed for 203 yards and one touchdown, but the Colts fell to the Chiefs by a score of 31\u201313.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/4fe6101f388348119a19ae0a69ee7770 |title=Chiefs roll past Colts 31\u201313 to reach AFC title game |last=Skretta |first=Dave |date=January 13, 2019 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the completion of the season, Luck was named to the fourth [[Pro Bowl]] of his career, as well as being given the [[National Football League Comeback Player of the Year Award]] by the [[Pro Football Writers Association]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.colts.com/news/andrew-luck-voted-pfwa-s-2018-nfl-comeback-player-of-the-year |title=Andrew Luck Voted PFWA's 2018 NFL Comeback Player Of The Year |last=Walker |first=Andrew  |date=January 18, 2019 |website=Colts.com |access-date=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nOn August 24, 2019, after seven seasons and at the age of 29, Luck announced his retirement. At a press conference, he cited his recurrent cycle of injuries and rehabilitation as the primary reason,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2019/8/26/20832198/why-andrew-luck-retired-rehab-injuries |title=I understand why Andrew Luck retired, because I\u2019ve been in his shoes: Retired NFL lineman Geoff Schwartz describes just how awful it feels to go through the rigors of constant rehab |last=Schwartz |first=Geoff |date=August 26, 2019 |website=SB Nation |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> saying:<blockquote>\"I've been stuck in this process.  I haven't been able to live the life I want to live.  It's taken the joy out of this game.  The only way forward for me is to remove myself from football.  This is not an easy decision.  It's the hardest decision of my life.  But it is the right decision for me.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27456682/luck-retires-calls-decision-hardest-my-life |title=Luck retires, calls decision 'hardest of my life' |last=Wells |first=Mike |date=24 August 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=24 August 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nDue to retiring at the age of 29, Luck is considered by some to be among the best professional athletes to end their career during their prime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/nfl-stars-who-retired-early-andrew-luck-joins-list-of-10-other-great-players-who-stepped-away-in-their-prime/ |title=NFL stars who retired early: Andrew Luck joins list of 10 other great players who stepped away in their prime |last=DeArdo |first=Bryan  |date=August 26, 2019 |website=[[CBS Sports]] |access-date=August 28, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2019/8/26/20832885/andrew-luck-indianapolis-colts-early-athlete-retirements|title=Andrew Luck and the Afterburn of Early Retirement |author=Katie Baker|work=[[The Ringer (website)|The Ringer]] |date=August 26, 2019|accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|<center>Legend</center>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec;\"|\n| Led the league\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n====Regular season====\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=2|Season !! rowspan=2|Team !! colspan=3|Games !! colspan=10|Passing !! colspan=4|Rushing || colspan=2|Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Record !! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! Int !! Sck !! SckY !! Rate !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! TD !! FUM !! Lost\n|-\n! [[2012 NFL season|2012]] !! {{Colts season|2012}}\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || '''11\u20135''' || 339 || 627 || 54.1 || 4,374 || 7.0 || 23 || '''18''' || '''41''' || 246 || 76.5 || 62 || 255 || 4.1 || '''5''' || 10 || 5\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! {{Colts sea