 Beat Dolphins 23\u201320: Andrew Luck Breaks Single-Game Rookie Record With 433 Passing Yards |last=Marot |first=Michael |date=November 4, 2012 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |access-date=November 4, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105001511/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/04/andrew-luck-record-colts-dolphins-23-20_n_2073511.html |archive-date=November 5, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie in a single season (4,374)<ref name=\"McIntyre\"/>\n*Most game-winning drives by a rookie quarterback (7)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/vKI4i |title=Most game-winning drives by a rookie quarterback, single season, NFL history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 2 seasons (8,196)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20140110/NEWS/301109891/1009|title=Colts' Andrew Luck thinks he has learned from mistakes against Patriots|last=Garven|first=Rich|work=Telegram.com|date=January 10, 2014|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 3 seasons (12,688)<ref name=\"Most passing 3\"/>\n*Most passing yards for a quarterback through his first 5 postseason games (1,703)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ESPNStatsInfo/status/554446056407437313|title=ESPN Stats & Info on Twitter|work=[[Twitter]]|date=January 11, 2015|accessdate=January 11, 2015}}</ref>\n*Most consecutive 350-yard passing games on the road (5)<ref name=\"Week 9 2014\"/>\n*Most pass attempts per game, career: (38.3)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_att_per_g_career.htm |title=NFL Pass Attempts per Game Career Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n*Fifth highest passing yards total in a playoff game (443) (Wild-Card game against the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] on January 4, 2014).<ref name=\"Wilson\"/>\n*First quarterback to throw for more than 350 yards in five consecutive road games<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasyfootball/update/24782826/andrew-luck-sets-career-high-in-td-passes-with-seven-games-left|title=Andrew Luck sets career high in TD passes with seven games left|last=Hartstein|first=Larry|website=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=November 3, 2014|accessdate=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n*First quarterback to throw for 370 yards or more, 4 touchdowns, and have a completion percentage 70 percent or above in consecutive games<ref name=\"sports.yahoo.com\"/>\n*Third player to throw for 3,000 yards in the first nine games, alongside [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Drew Brees]] (twice)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://nfldraftdiamonds.com/colts-andrew-luck-is-breaking-records-tonight/ |title=Colts Andrew Luck is breaking records tonight |last=Talbot |first=Desmond |work=NFL Draft Diamonds |access-date=November 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Colts franchise records====\n*Most passing yards in a single season (4,761, 2014)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stampedeblue.com/2014/12/28/7457399/andrew-luck-breaks-peyton-mannings-colts-franchise-record-for-single |title=Andrew Luck Breaks Peyton Manning's Colts Franchise Record for Single-Season Passing Yards |last=Wilson |first=Josh |date=December 28, 2014 |website=Stampede Blue |access-date=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie quarterback in a single season (4,374)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">http://prod.static.colts.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/mediaguide/2014-mediaguide.pdf</ref>\n*Most passing yards by a rookie quarterback in a single game (433)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass attempts by a rookie quarterback in a single season (627)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass completions by a rookie quarterback in a single season (339)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most pass completions by a rookie quarterback in a single game (31)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Most passing touchdowns by a rookie quarterback in a single game (4)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Highest passer rating by a rookie quarterback with a minimum of 100 attempts (76.5)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n*Highest interception percentage by a rookie quarterback with a minimum of 100 attempts (2.87)<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Endorsements==\nIn March 2012, [[Nike, Inc.]] signed Luck to its roster of athletes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nikeinc.com/news/nike-signs-quarterback-andrew-luck |title=Nike signs quarterback Andrew Luck |date=March 12, 2012 |website=Nike Inc. |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Luck became a partner and investor in BodyArmor SuperDrink.<ref name=\"Colts Quarterback Andrew Luck Dumps Gatorade for a Stake in Upstart BODYARMOR\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2013-09-17/colts-quarterback-andrew-luck-dumps-gatorade-for-a-stake-in-upstart-bodyarmor |title=Colts Quarterback Andrew Luck Dumps Gatorade for a Stake in Uptart BODYARMOR |last=Boudway |first=Ira |date=September 17, 2013 |website=Business Week |access-date=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 17, 2012, Luck graduated from Stanford with a bachelor's degree in architectural design and received the Al Masters Award, an honor given to an athlete each year, \"for the highest standards of athletic performance, leadership and academic achievement.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/nfl/story/2012-06-19/andrew-luck-graduates-stanford-degree-michelle-wie-indianapolis-colts |title=Andrew Luck graduates from Stanford with architectural degree |last=Brown |first=Clifton |date=June 19, 2012 |website=www.sportingnews.com |language=en |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>  He has stated that his favorite musician is [[Bruce Springsteen]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/colts/story/2012-06-25/luck-opens-up-on-the-beard-and-his-go-phone/55826972/1 |title=Luck opens up on the beard, his phone and thoughts on Indy |last=Kravitz |first=Bob |date=June 25, 2012 |website=USA Today |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> An avid reader, Luck has become known as \"the Colts' very own librarian\", giving and suggesting books for his teammates; in 2012, he said his favorite book was [[Henri Charri\u00e8re]]'s [[Papillon (book)|''Papillon'']], and he is a fan of [[Bernard Cornwell]]'s historical fiction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-andrew-luck-book-club-1446675595|title=The Andrew Luck Book Club|last=Clark|first=Kevin|date=November 4, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref> On the field, Luck perplexes his opponents with comments that may or may not be trash talk: when he is knocked down, he is in the habit of congratulating his opponent on the hit. After a hit by linebacker [[Ryan Kerrigan]] that caused a fumble and sent Luck scrambling for the ball, he was not able to congratulate Kerrigan right away and had to wait until later in the game \"to tell Kerrigan how great he was doing\". Kerrigan's reaction was later captured, \"You want to say thank you but then you say 'wait a second\u2014I'm not supposed to like you!'\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/andrew-luck-the-nfls-most-perplexing-trash-talker-1418663249|title=Andrew Luck: The NFL's Most Perplexing Trash Talker. The Colts Quarterback Drives Defenders Crazy by Offering Compliments; Head Games or Genuine Kindness?|last=Clark|first=Kevin|date=December 16, 2014|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2019, Luck married longtime girlfriend Nicole Pechanec.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/nfl/colts/2019/03/31/andrew-luck-wedding-nicole-pechanec/3323937002/ |title=Andrew Luck wedding: Colts quarterback marries Nicole Pechanec |date=2019-03-31 |website=Indianapolis Star |access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> He announced on June 14, 2019, that they are expecting their first child.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wthr.com/article/colts-quarterback-andrew-luck-wife-are-pregnant |title=Colts quarterback Andrew Luck, wife are pregnant |last=Calabro |first=Dave |date=June 14, 2019 |website=13 WTHR Indianapolis |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref> The couple's first child was born in November 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Horner |first1=Scott |title=Ex-Indianapolis Colts QB Andrew Luck's wife gives birth to couple's first child |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/11/22/andrew-luck-ex-colts-qbs-wife-gives-birth-daughter-lucy/4269024002/ |website=USAToday |accessdate=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\n\nIn 2013 Luck appeared on the comedy series ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' as himself alongside teammates [[Reggie Wayne]], [[Anthony Castonzo]], [[Robert Mathis]], and [[Adam Vinatieri]] during the show's [[Parks and Recreation (season 5)|fifth season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indystar.com/story/entertainment/movies/2013/11/19/andrew-luck-colts-nbc-amy-poehler/3644753/|title=Watch preview of Colts-themed \"Parks and Rec\" episode|last=Lindquist|first=David|work=indystar.com|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\nSince 2015, Luck has been the subject of a parody [[Twitter]] account under the name Capt. Andrew Luck. The tweets report on Luck's career using the language of an [[American Civil War]] soldier writing back home to his family.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/01/04/squirrel-oil-raccoon-thighs-tobacco-spit-capt-andrew-luck-is-back-nfl-playoffs/ |title=Squirrel oil, raccoon thighs and tobacco spit: Capt. Andrew Luck is back in the NFL playoffs |last=Strauss |first=Ben  |website=[[Washington Post]] |language=en |access-date=2020-01-30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|American football|College football}}\n*[[List of first overall National Football League draft picks]]\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Andrew Luck}}\n* {{Footballstats |nfl=2533031 |espn=14874 |pfr=L/LuckAn00}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120527030325/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html Indianapolis Colts bio]\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120527030325/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/luck_andrew00.html |date=May 27, 2012 |title=Stanford Cardinal bio }}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.gostanford.com/andrew-luck/ |title=Stanford's Andrew Luck Heisman Trophy candidate site |accessdate=December 6, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125030431/http://www.gostanford.com/andrew-luck/ |archivedate=January 25, 2012 |df= }}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Andrew Luck\n| list1 =\n{{Stanford Cardinal quarterback navbox}}\n{{Pac-12 Player of the Year}}\n{{Football Academic All-America of the Year}}\n{{Johnny Unitas Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{2012 NFL Draft}}\n{{NFL Number One Draft Picks}}\n{{ColtsFirstPick}}\n{{Indianapolis Colts starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{AP NFL Comeback Player}}\n{{NFL Comeback Players of the Year}}\n{{NFL passing touchdown leaders}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luck, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:National Football League first overall draft picks]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Houston]]\n[[Category:Stanford Cardinal football players]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "name_user": "98.111.225.189", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn media:Not relevant.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Luck"}
{"title_page": "Prison abolition movement", "text_new": "{{Criminology and penology|penology}}\n\nThe '''prison abolition movement''' is a loose network of groups and activists that seek to reduce or eliminate [[prisons]] and the prison system, and replace them with systems of rehabilitation that do not place a focus on punishment and government institutionalization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Robin F|date=2009|title=Angela Y. Davis and the Prison Abolition Movement, Part II|journal=Contemporary Justice Review|volume=12|pages=101\u2013104|doi=10.1080/10282580802685452}}</ref> The prison abolitionist movement is distinct from conventional [[prison reform]], which is the attempt to improve conditions inside prisons.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of basic principles and promising practices on Alternatives to Imprisonment|publisher=United Nations|date=April 2007|url=http://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/Handbook_of_Basic_Principles_and_Promising_Practices_on_Alternatives_to_Imprisonment.pdf|isbn=978-92-1-148220-1}}</ref>{{rp|3}}\n\nSupporters of prison abolition also work to end solitary confinement, the death penalty, and the construction of new prisons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ordinary-gentlemen.com/shawngude/2013/02/non-reformist-reforms-defined/|title=Non-reformist reforms defined|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:45v7WbHjnlgJ:https://www.jacobinmag.com/2017/08/prison-abolition-reform-mass-incarceration+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ca&client=firefox-b-ab|title=What Abolitionsts Do|last=Berger|first=Dan|last2=Kaba|first2=Mariame|date=August 24, 2017|website=Jacobin|access-date=March 23, 2018|last3=Stein|first3=David}}{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Others support book-to-prisoner projects and defend the rights of prisoners to have access to information and library services. Some organizations such as the [[Anarchist Black Cross]] seek total abolishment of the prison system, without any intention to replace it with other government-controlled systems. Many anarchist organizations believe that the best form of justice arises naturally out of [[social contracts]] or [[restorative justice]].\n\n== 1973 Walpole Prison Uprising ==\nIn 1973, two years after the [[Attica Prison uprising]], the inmates of [[Walpole (prison)|Walpole prison]] formed a prisoners' union to protect themselves from guards, end behavioral modification programs, advocate for the prisoner's right for education and healthcare, gain more visitation rights, work assignments, and to be able to send money to their families.\n\nThe union also created a general truce within the prison and race-related violence sharply declined.  During the [[Kwanzaa]] celebration, black prisoners were placed under lockdown, angering the whole facility and leading to a general strike. Prisoners refused to work or leave their cells for three months, leading to the guards beating prisoners, putting prisoners in solitary confinement, denying prisoners medical care and food.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gelderloos|first=Peter|title=Anarchy Works|publisher=|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe strike ended in the prisoners' favour as the superintendent of the prison resigned. The prisoners were granted more visitation rights and work programs. Angered by this, the prison guards went on strike and abandoned the prison, hoping that this would create chaos and violence throughout the prison. But the prisoners were able to create an [[Anarchism|anarchist]] [[List of anarchist communities|community]] where [[recidivism]] dropped dramatically and murders and rapes fell to zero. Prisoners volunteered to cook meals. Vietnam veterans who had been trained as medics took charge of the pharmacy and distribution of meds. Decisions were made in community assemblies.\n\nGuards retook the prison after two months, leading to many prison administrators and bureaucrats quitting their jobs and embracing the prison abolition movement.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bisonnette|first=Jamie|title=When the prisoners ran Walpole: a true story in the movement for prison abolition|publisher=South End Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Advocates of prison abolition ==\nProminent social activist [[Angela Davis]], outspoken critic of the [[Prison\u2013industrial complex|prison-industrial complex]] (PIC), openly supports prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=Angela Y.|last2=Rodriguez|first2=Dylan|date=2000-01-01|title=The Challenge of Prison Abolition: A Conversation|journal=Social Justice|volume=27|issue=3 (81)|pages=212\u2013218|jstor=29767244}}</ref> In her work, she writes: \"Mass incarceration is not a solution to unemployment, nor is it a solution to the vast array of social problems that are hidden away in a rapidly growing network of prisons and jails. However, the great majority of people have been tricked into believing in the efficacy of imprisonment, even though the historical record clearly demonstrates that prisons do not work.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=cl_admin|url=http://www.colorlines.com/articles/masked-racism-reflections-prison-industrial-complex|title=Masked Racism: Reflections on the Prison Industrial Complex|date=1998-09-10|newspaper=Colorlines|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\nAngela Davis and [[Ruth Wilson Gilmore]] co-founded [[Critical Resistance]], which is an organization working to \"build an international movement to end the Prison Industrial Complex by challenging the belief that caging and controlling people makes us safe.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://criticalresistance.org/about/|title=About|website=Critical Resistance|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Kushner|first=Rachel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/17/magazine/prison-abolition-ruth-wilson-gilmore.html|title=Is Prison Necessary? Ruth Wilson Gilmore Might Change Your Mind|date=2019-04-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Other similarly motivated groups such as the Prison Activist Resource Center (PARC), a group \"committed to exposing and challenging all forms of institutionalized racism, sexism, able-ism, heterosexism, and classism, specifically within the Prison Industrial Complex,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prisonactivist.org/about|title=About PARC {{!}} Prison Activist Resource Center|website=www.prisonactivist.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> and [[Black & Pink]], an abolitionist organization that focuses around LGBTQ rights, all broadly advocate for prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackandpink.org/purpose-analysis/#family|title=Purpose and Analysis {{!}} black and pink|website=www.blackandpink.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> Furthermore, the Human Rights Coalition, a 2001 group that aims to abolish prisons,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrcoalition.org/about-hrc/purpose/|title=HR Coalition's Vision for Prisoners {{!}} Human Rights Coalition|website=hrcoalition.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://decarceratepa.info/content/organizational-spotlight-human-rights-coalition|title=Organizational Spotlight: the Human Rights Coalition {{!}} Decarcerate PA|website=decarceratepa.info|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> and the California Coalition for Women Prisoners, a grassroots organization dedicated to dismantling the PIC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenprisoners.org/|title=California Coalition for Women Prisoners|website=womenprisoners.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> can all be added to the long list of organizations that desire a different form of justice system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realcostofprisons.org/links.html|title=The Real Cost of Prisons Project|website=www.realcostofprisons.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\nSince 1983,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Levinson|first=David|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofcr0004unse|title=Encyclopedia of crime and punishment. Volume 1, Volume 1|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Sage Publications|isbn=978-0761922582|location=Thousand Oaks, Ca.|language=English|oclc=51883999|url-access=registration}}</ref> the International Conference on Penal Abolition (ICOPA) gathers activists, academics, journalists, and \"others from across the world who are working towards the abolition of imprisonment, the penal system, carceral controls and the prison industrial complex (PIC),\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.actionicopa.org/|title=actionICOPA :: The International Conference on Penal Abolition|website=www.actionicopa.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> to discuss three important questions surrounding the reality of prison abolition ICOPA was one of the first penal abolitionist conference movements, similar to Critical Resistance in America, but \"with an explicitly international scope and agenda-setting ambition.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?sid=ba78d840-bf7d-4fce-babe-fbd928d6ba5f@sessionmgr4007&vid=2&hid=4205|title=The moving targets of penal abolitionism: ICOPA, past, present and future.|last=|first=|date=|website=eds.a.ebscohost.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-28}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nAnarchists wish to eliminate all forms of [[State (polity)|state]] control, of which [[imprisonment]] is seen as one of the more obvious examples. Anarchists also oppose prisons given that statistics show incarceration rates affect mainly poor people and [[ethnic minorities]], and do not generally rehabilitate criminals, in many cases making them worse.<ref>National Advisory Commission on Criminal Justice Standards and Goals (US). A National Strategy to Reduce Crime. [https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/Digitization/54466NCJRS.pdf National Advisory Commission on Criminal Justice Standards and Goals], 1973. p. 358</ref> As a result, the prison abolition movement often is associated with humanistic socialism, [[anarchism]] and [[anti-authoritarian]]ism.\n\nIn October 2015, members at a plenary session of the [[National Lawyers Guild]] (NLG) released and adopted a resolution in favor of prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nlg.org/nlg-adopts-resolution-supporting-prison-abolition/|title=NLG Adopts Resolution Supporting Prison Abolition|date=2015-12-17|newspaper=National Lawyers Guild|access-date=2016-11-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commons.commondreams.org/t/national-lawyers-guild-adopts-resolution-supporting-prison-abolition/16567|title=National Lawyers Guild Adopts Resolution Supporting Prison Abolition|date=2015-12-17|website=The Commons {{!}} Common Dreams|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\n== Mental illness and prison ==\nPrison abolitionists such as Amanda Pustilnik take issue with the fact that prisons are used as a \"default asylum\" for many individuals with mental illness.<ref name=\"def\">Pustilnik, Amanda. 2005. \"Prisons of the Mind: Social Value and Economic Inefficiency in the Criminal Justice Response to Mental Illness.\"The Journal of Criminal Law and Criminology.96(1): 217\u2013265.</ref> \n<blockquote>\n\"Why do governmental units choose to spend billions of dollars a year to concentrate people with serious illnesses in a system designed to punish intentional lawbreaking, when doing so matches neither the putative purposes of that system nor most effectively addresses the issues posed by that population?\"<ref name=\"def\" />\n</blockquote> To rephrase, if the whole point of the penal system is to rehabilitate and reform individuals who have willingly transgressed, then those who transgress the law for reasons outside their cognitive control don't belong in prison since prisoners were never designed nor intended to rehabilitate this population.\n\nIn the United States, there are more [[Mentally ill prisoners in the United States|people with mental illness in prisons]] than in psychiatric hospitals.<ref name=\"def\" />   This statistic is one of the major pieces of evidence that prison abolitionists claim highlights the depravity of the penal system.\n\nPrison abolitionists contend that prisons violate the Constitutional rights (5th and 6th Amendment rights) of mentally ill prisoners on the grounds that these individuals will not be receiving the same potential for rehabilitation as the non-mentally ill prison population.  This injustice is sufficient grounds to argue for the abolishment of prisons.<ref name=\"def\" /><ref name=\"def\" /><ref name=\"ment\">Rollin, Henry. 2006. \"The Mentally Ill Should Be in Hospital, not in Jail.\" ''The Journal of Forensic Psychiatry and Psychology''. 17(2): 326\u2013329.</ref><ref name=\"harvard\">Harvard Law Review. February 2008. \"Developments in the Law: The Law of Mental Illness.\" ''Harvard Law Review''. 121(4):1114\u20131191.</ref> Prisons were not designed to be used to house the mentally ill, and prison practices like solitary confinement are awful for mental health. Additionally, individuals with mental illnesses have a much higher chance of committing suicide while in prison.<ref name=\"sui\">Ahmed, Mukhtar. Bowen, Andy. and Graham, Tanya. et al. 2007. /ref> \"The Identifications and Management of Suicide Risk in Local Prisons.\" ''Journal of Forensic Psychiatry and Psychology''. 18(3): 368\u2013380.</ref>\n\n== Arguments made for prison abolition ==\n\n* Lack of proper legal representation\n:\"Eighty percent of people accused of crimes [in the [[United States]]] are unable to afford a lawyer to defend them.\"<ref name=\"Wright 2003. p.6\">Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 6.</ref> The [[US Supreme Court]] held in 1963 that a poor person facing felony charges \"cannot be assured a fair trial unless counsel is provided for him.\"\n:\"Long Term Neglect and underfunding of indigent defense have created a crisis of extra ordinary proportions in many states throughout the country.\"<ref name=\"Wright 2003. p.6\" />\n* War on drugs conceals racial tension\n:(2005) \"The United States leads the world in the number of people incarcerated in federal and state correctional facilities. There are currently more than 2 million people in American prisons or jails. Approximately one-quarter of those people held in U.S. prisons or jails have been convicted of a drug offense. The United States incarcerates more people for drug offenses than any other country. With an estimated 6.8 million Americans struggling with drug abuse or dependence, the growth of the prison population continues to be driven largely by incarceration for drug offenses.\"<ref>Justice Policy Institute, \"Substance Abuse Treatment and Public Safety,\" (Washington, DC: January 2008), p. 1.\nhttp://www.justicepolicy.org/images/upload/08_01_REP_DrugTx_AC-PS.pdf</ref>\n:\"The so-called drug war was started in the 1980s and it was aimed directly at the black population. None of this has anything to do with drugs. It has to do with controlling and criminalizing dangerous populations.\"<ref>Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 56.</ref>\n:\"Blacks are 12.3 percent of the U.S. population (2001) but they comprise fully half of the roughly 2 million Americans currently behind Bars. On any given day, 30 percent of African-American males aged 20\u201329 are \"under correctional supervision\".<ref>Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 31.</ref>\n:Blacks constitute 13 percent of all drug users, but 35 percent of those arrested for drug possession, 55 percent of persons convicted, and 74 percent of people sent to prison.<ref>http://www.fff.org/comment/com0303e.as{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* Incarceration is socially and economically crippling to the convicted and the community.\n:\"Each Prisoner represents an economic asset that has been removed from that community and placed elsewhere. As an economic being, the person would spend money at or near his or her area of residence\u2014typically, an inner city. Imprisonment displaces that economic activity: Instead of buying snacks in a local deli, the prisoner makes those purchases in a prison commissary. The removal may represent a loss of economic value to the home community, but it is a boon to the prison [host] community. Each prisoner represents as much as $25,000 in income for the community in which the prison is located, not to mention the value of constructing the prison facility in the first place. This can be a massive transfer of value: a young male worth a few thousand dollars of support to children and local purchases is transformed into a $25,000 financial asset to a rural prison community. The economy of the rural community is artificially amplified, the local city economy is artificially deflated.\"<ref>Clear, Todd. \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.497.3373&rep=rep1&type=pdf Backfire: When Incarceration Increases Crime]\". in The Unintended consequences of Incarceration. New York: Vera Institute of Justice, January 1996</ref>\n\n:Unfortunately, there are no definitive national statistics on the employment status of felons. But both anecdotal evidence and fragmentary data confirm what common sense would predict: individuals who have been incarcerated have great difficulty securing employment when they return to society. Except for a short period in the late 1990s, when the labor market was so tight that the Wall Street Journal reported on employer efforts to reach out to felons, those leaving prison have faced formidable obstacles to employment. Some of these difficulties are related to company policies or procedures and others are the result of employer perceptions of felons' job skills or trustworthiness. Felons are also barred from public employment in a number of states, including three with a high proportion of African American residents (Alabama, Mississippi, and South Carolina). Occupations that are licensed by states also have restrictions on allowing felons to work in them.<ref>Margaret C. Simms, \"JOINT CENTER FOR POLITICAL AND ECONOMIC STUDIES\" MAY/JUNE 2004 p. 7\"</ref>\n* It is argued by the Massachusetts Statewide Harm Reduction Coalition that the prison system is in violation of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/universal-declaration-human-rights/index.html|title=Universal Declaration of Human Rights {{!}} United Nations|date=2015-10-06|website=www.un.org|access-date=2016-11-26}}</ref> which was adopted by the [[United Nations General Assembly]] in 1948, and which is prescribing life, liberty, equality and justice to all people without discrimination of any sort as an inalienable right.<ref>http://www.massdecarcerate.org/download/HumanRights.doc</ref> The Universal Declaration of Human Rights has also abolished all forms of slavery and genocide, including torture, repression and oppression that prisons thrive upon.\n* Imprisonment is seen by some as a form of violent behavior which legitimizes violence and cruelty, producing a \"boomerang effect of dehumanization\"<ref>http://peaceconsortium.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Jakopovich.pdf Daniel Jakopovich, The Humanist Defense and Critique of the South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission, ''Peace Studies Journal'', Vol.4, Issue1, 2011</ref> on the society which dehumanizes itself and limits its potential for a peaceful future by resorting to the use of such repressive and cruel institutions.\n* Prisons may be less effective at discouraging crimes and/or compensating victims than other forms of punishment.<ref>Andrews and Bonta, 2003{{Title missing|date=September 2010}}{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}</ref>\n* Degree and quality of access to justice depends on the financial resources of the accused.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tyler|first=Tracey|url=https://www.thestar.com/article/245548|title=Access to justice a 'basic right'|date=August 12, 2007|work=The Star|accessdate=May 22, 2010|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>[http://www.pili.org/en/content/view/126/26/ Public Interest Law Institute \u2013 Indigent Defense Systems in the United States<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=August 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n* Prisons [[Social alienation|alienate]] people from their [[Community|communities]].\n* In the U.S., [[people of color]] and from the [[American lower class|lower class]] are much more likely to be imprisoned than people of European descent or people who are wealthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/prisons.htm|title=Prison population statistics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002081754/http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/prisons.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=2007-10-02|accessdate=2007-10-04}}</ref>\n* People who are put in prison for what are arguably crimes motivated by need, such as some minor theft (food, etc.) or prostitution, find it much harder to obtain legal employment once convicted of a crime. Arguably, this difficulty makes it more likely they will find themselves back in the prison system, having had few other options or resources available to support themselves and/or their families.{{citation needed|date=February 2008}} Many prison abolitionists argue that we should \"legalize survival\" and provide help to those who need it instead of making it even harder to find work and perpetuating the non-violent crimes.\n* Prisons are not proven to make people less violent. In fact, there is evidence that they may instead promote violence in individuals by surrounding them with other violent criminals, which can lead to predictable negative/violent results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/news/special_reports/prisons/violence.html|title=Mother Jones|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229105512/http://www.motherjones.com/news/special_reports/prisons/violence.html|archive-date=2008-12-29|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n* Drug-related offenders are being ushered in and out of the prison system like a revolving door. Rather than educate, and rehabilitate the offender to a clean path of sobriety and increased stature, the state ignores them.\n\n== Arguments made against prison abolition ==\nOpponents of the abolition argue that none of the arguments above address the protection of non-criminal population from the effects of crime, and from particularly violent criminals.\n* Prisons provide protection for broader society from those within who are judged likely to reoffend.\n* Individuals who have committed crimes, especially crimes violent in nature, must repay society. Retributive philosophy argues that punishment is necessary in order for an individual who has done wrong to pay for their crime<ref>Cottingham, John. \u201cVarieties of Retribution.\u201d The Philosophical Quarterly, vol. 29, no. 116, 1979, pp. 238\u2013246. JSTOR, JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/2218820.</ref>\n* [[Utilitarianism|Utilitarian ethics]] with happiness as its utility argues that the unhappiness of few is good or right if it leads to the happiness of the majority. The ethical argument in this case is that keeping 1% of the population incarcerated is worth it for the happiness of the majority, depending on the amount of unhappiness the 1% suffers by being incarcerated and inflicts on society by being free.\n* Deterrence theory makes the case that prison discourages citizens from committing a crime, because they would not want to end up in prison<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Incarceration|first1=Committee on Causes Consequences of High Rates of|url=https://www.nap.edu/read/18613/chapter/7#131|title=The Growth of Incarceration in the United States|last2=Justice|first2=Committee on Law and|last3=Education|first3=Division of Behavioral Social Sciences and|last4=Council|first4=National Research|year=2014|isbn=978-0-309-29801-8|doi=10.17226/18613}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed reforms and alternatives ==\nProposals for prison reform and alternatives to prisons differ significantly depending on the political beliefs behind them. Proposals and tactics often include{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}:\n\n* Penal system reforms:\n** Substituting, for incarceration, supervised release, [[probation]], [[restitution]] to victims, and/or community work.\n** Decreasing terms of imprisonment by abolishing [[Mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentencing]]\n** Decreasing ethnic disparity in prison populations\n* Prison condition reforms\n* Crime prevention rather than punishment\n* Abolition of specific programs which increase prison population, such as the [[prohibition of drugs]] (e.g., the American [[War on Drugs]]), [[gun control]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}, prohibition of [[sex work]], and [[prohibition|alcohol restrictions]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}.\n* Education programs to inform people who have never been in prison about the problems\n* Fighting individual cases of [[wrongful conviction]]\n\nThe [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] published a series of handbooks on criminal justice. Among them is [http://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/Handbook_of_Basic_Principles_and_Promising_Practices_on_Alternatives_to_Imprisonment.pdf Alternatives to Imprisonment] which identifies how the overuse of imprisonment impacts fundamental human rights, especially those convicted for lesser crimes.\n\nSocial justice and advocacy organizations such as Students Against Mass Incarceration (SAMI) at the [[University of California, San Diego]] often look to Scandinavian countries Sweden and Norway for guidance in regard to successful prison reform because both countries have an emphasis on rehabilitation rather than punishment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucsdguardian.org/2013/12/02/the-breakthrough-of-students-against-mass-incarceration/|title=The Breakthrough of Students Against Mass Incarceration {{!}} UCSD Guardian|last=Staff|first=Guardian|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> According to Sweden's Prison and Probation Service Director-General, Nils \u00d6berg, this emphasis is popular among the Swedish because the act of imprisonment is considered punishment enough.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/nov/26/prison-sweden-not-punishment-nils-oberg|title=Prison is not for punishment in Sweden. We get people into better shape|newspaper=The Guardian|last1=James|first1=Erwin|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=2014-11-26}}</ref> This focus on rehabilitation includes an emphasis on promoting normalcy for inmates, a charge lead by experienced criminologists and psychologists.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/09/why-scandinavian-prisons-are-superior/279949/|title=Why Scandinavian Prisons Are Superior|website=The Atlantic|last1=Larson|first1=Doran|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=2013-09-24}}</ref> In Norway a focus on preparation for societal re-entry has yielded \"one of the lowest recidivism rates in the world at 20%, [while] the US has one of the highest: 76.6% of [Americans] prisoners are re-arrested within five years\".<ref name=\"Business Insider\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/why-norways-prison-system-is-so-successful-2014-12|title=Why Norway's prison system is so successful|website=Business Insider|last1=Sterbenz|first1=Christina|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> The Scandinavian method of incarceration seems to be successful: the Swedish incarceration rate decreased by 6% between 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/dec/01/why-sweden-closing-prisons|title=Why is Sweden closing its prisons?|newspaper=The Guardian|last1=James|first1=Erwin|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Abolitionist views ===\nMany prison reform organizations and abolitionists in the United States advocate community accountability practices, such as community-controlled courts, councils, or assemblies as an alternative to the criminal justice system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackandpink.org/purpose-analysis/|title=Purpose and Analysis \u2013 black and pink|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOrganizations such as [[Incite!|INCITE!]] and Sista II Sista that support women of color who are survivors of interpersonal violence argue that the criminal justice system does not protect marginalized people who are victims in violent relationships. Instead, victims, especially those who are poor, minorities, transgender or gender non-conforming can experience additional violence at the hands of the state.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Arrested Justice: Black Women, Violence, and America's Prison Nation|last=Richie|first=Beth E.|publisher=New York University Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=17}}</ref> Instead of relying on the criminal justice system, these organizations work to implement community accountability practices, which often involve collectively-run processes of intervention initiated by a survivor of violence to try to hold the person who committed violence accountable by working to meet a set of demands.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rojas Durazo|first=Ana Clarissa|date=2011\u20132012|title=Community Accountability: Emerging Movements to Transform into Violence|url=|journal=Social Justice: A Journal of Crime, Conflict & World Order|volume=37|issue=4|pages=|via=}}</ref>\nFor organizations outside the United States see, e.g. [http://www.justiceaction.org.au Justice Action, Australia].\n\nSome anarchists and socialists contend that a large part of the problem is the way the judicial system deals with prisoners, people, and capital.  According to Marxists, in capitalist economies incentives are in place to expand the prison system and increase the prison population. This is evidenced by the creation of private prisons in America and corporations like CoreCivic, formerly known as Correction Corporation of America (CCA). http://www.cca.com/ \n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/mar/03/prison-population-titan-jails|title=George Monbiot: This revolting trade in human lives is an incentive to lock people up|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=2009-03-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\nIts shareholders benefit from the expansion of prisons and tougher laws on crime. More prisoners is seen as beneficial for business. Some anarchists contend that with the destruction of capitalism, and the development of social structures that would allow for the self-management of communities, property crimes would largely vanish. There would be fewer prisoners, they assert, if society treated people more fairly, regardless of gender, color, ethnic background, sexual orientation, education, etc.\n\nThe demand for prison abolition is a feature of [[anarchist criminology]], which argues that prisons encourage recidivism and should be replaced by efforts to rehabilitate offenders and reintegrate them into communities.<ref>{{cite encyclopaedia|first=Jeff|last=Ferrell|title=Anarchist Criminology|encyclopaedia=Encyclopedia of Criminological Theory|editor-first1=Francis T.|editor-link1=Francis T. Cullen|editor-last1=Cullen|editor-first2=Pamela|editor-last2=Wilcox|doi=10.4135/9781412959193.n11|publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]]|year=2010|page=45}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Angela Davis]]\n* [[Convict lease]] system, abolished by Presidential order in 1942\n* [[Emma Goldman]]\n* [[Fay Honey Knopp]]\n* [[Exile]]\n* [[Frankie Boyle]]\n* [[Louk Hulsman]]\n* [[Mentally ill people in United States jails and prisons]]\n* [[Nils Christie]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Penal labor]]\n* [[Restorative justice]]\n* [[Thomas Mathiesen]]\n* [[Prison-industrial complex]]\n* [[Transformative justice]]\n* [[Pacifism]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n* Livio Ferrari/Massimo Pavarini (eds.) NO Prison. European Group Press. London 2018.\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n\n[[Category:Criminal justice reform]]\n[[Category:Penal imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Prison abolition movement| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Criminology and penology|penology}}\n\nThe '''prison abolition movement''' is a loose network of groups and activists that seek to reduce or eliminate [[prisons]] and the prison system, and replace them with systems of rehabilitation that do not place a focus on punishment and government institutionalization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shaw|first=Robin F|date=2009|title=Angela Y. Davis and the Prison Abolition Movement, Part II|journal=Contemporary Justice Review|volume=12|pages=101\u2013104|doi=10.1080/10282580802685452}}</ref> The prison abolitionist movement is distinct from conventional [[prison reform]], which is the attempt to improve conditions inside prisons.<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of basic principles and promising practices on Alternatives to Imprisonment|publisher=United Nations|date=April 2007|url=http://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/Handbook_of_Basic_Principles_and_Promising_Practices_on_Alternatives_to_Imprisonment.pdf|isbn=978-92-1-148220-1}}</ref>{{rp|3}}\n\nSupporters of prison abolition also work to end solitary confinement, the death penalty, and the construction of new prisons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ordinary-gentlemen.com/shawngude/2013/02/non-reformist-reforms-defined/|title=Non-reformist reforms defined|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:45v7WbHjnlgJ:https://www.jacobinmag.com/2017/08/prison-abolition-reform-mass-incarceration+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=ca&client=firefox-b-ab|title=What Abolitionsts Do|last=Berger|first=Dan|last2=Kaba|first2=Mariame|date=August 24, 2017|website=Jacobin|access-date=March 23, 2018|last3=Stein|first3=David}}{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Others support book-to-prisoner projects and defend the rights of prisoners to have access to information and library services. Some organizations such as the [[Anarchist Black Cross]] seek total abolishment of the prison system, without any intention to replace it with other government-controlled systems. Many anarchist organizations believe that the best form of justice arises naturally out of [[social contracts]] or [[restorative justice]].\n\n== 1973 Walpole Prison Uprising ==\nIn 1973, two years after the [[Attica Prison uprising]], the inmates of [[Walpole (prison)|Walpole prison]] formed a prisoners' union to protect themselves from guards, end behavioral modification programs, advocate for the prisoner's right for education and healthcare, gain more visitation rights, work assignments, and to be able to send money to their families.\n\nThe union also created a general truce within the prison and race-related violence sharply declined.  During the [[Kwanzaa]] celebration, black prisoners were placed under lockdown, angering the whole facility and leading to a general strike. Prisoners refused to work or leave their cells for three months, leading to the guards beating prisoners, putting prisoners in solitary confinement, denying prisoners medical care and food.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Gelderloos|first=Peter|title=Anarchy Works|publisher=|year=2010|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nThe strike ended in the prisoners' favour as the superintendent of the prison resigned. The prisoners were granted more visitation rights and work programs. Angered by this, the prison guards went on strike and abandoned the prison, hoping that this would create chaos and violence throughout the prison. But the prisoners were able to create an [[Anarchism|anarchist]] [[List of anarchist communities|community]] where [[recidivism]] dropped dramatically and murders and rapes fell to zero. Prisoners volunteered to cook meals. Vietnam veterans who had been trained as medics took charge of the pharmacy and distribution of meds. Decisions were made in community assemblies.\n\nGuards retook the prison after two months, leading to many prison administrators and bureaucrats quitting their jobs and embracing the prison abolition movement.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bisonnette|first=Jamie|title=When the prisoners ran Walpole: a true story in the movement for prison abolition|publisher=South End Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=Cambridge|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Advocates of prison abolition ==\nProminent social activist [[Angela Davis]], outspoken critic of the [[Prison\u2013industrial complex|prison-industrial complex]] (PIC), openly supports prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Davis|first=Angela Y.|last2=Rodriguez|first2=Dylan|date=2000-01-01|title=The Challenge of Prison Abolition: A Conversation|journal=Social Justice|volume=27|issue=3 (81)|pages=212\u2013218|jstor=29767244}}</ref> In her work, she writes: \"Mass incarceration is not a solution to unemployment, nor is it a solution to the vast array of social problems that are hidden away in a rapidly growing network of prisons and jails. However, the great majority of people have been tricked into believing in the efficacy of imprisonment, even though the historical record clearly demonstrates that prisons do not work.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=cl_admin|url=http://www.colorlines.com/articles/masked-racism-reflections-prison-industrial-complex|title=Masked Racism: Reflections on the Prison Industrial Complex|date=1998-09-10|newspaper=Colorlines|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\nAngela Davis and [[Ruth Wilson Gilmore]] co-founded [[Critical Resistance]], which is an organization working to \"build an international movement to end the Prison Industrial Complex by challenging the belief that caging and controlling people makes us safe.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://criticalresistance.org/about/|title=About|website=Critical Resistance|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> Other similarly motivated groups such as the Prison Activist Resource Center (PARC), a group \"committed to exposing and challenging all forms of institutionalized racism, sexism, able-ism, heterosexism, and classism, specifically within the Prison Industrial Complex,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prisonactivist.org/about|title=About PARC {{!}} Prison Activist Resource Center|website=www.prisonactivist.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> and [[Black & Pink]], an abolitionist organization that focuses around LGBTQ rights, all broadly advocate for prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.blackandpink.org/purpose-analysis/#family|title=Purpose and Analysis {{!}} black and pink|website=www.blackandpink.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> Furthermore, the Human Rights Coalition, a 2001 group that aims to abolish prisons,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrcoalition.org/about-hrc/purpose/|title=HR Coalition's Vision for Prisoners {{!}} Human Rights Coalition|website=hrcoalition.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://decarceratepa.info/content/organizational-spotlight-human-rights-coalition|title=Organizational Spotlight: the Human Rights Coalition {{!}} Decarcerate PA|website=decarceratepa.info|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> and the California Coalition for Women Prisoners, a grassroots organization dedicated to dismantling the PIC,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://womenprisoners.org/|title=California Coalition for Women Prisoners|website=womenprisoners.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> can all be added to the long list of organizations that desire a different form of justice system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realcostofprisons.org/links.html|title=The Real Cost of Prisons Project|website=www.realcostofprisons.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\nSince 1983,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Levinson|first=David|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofcr0004unse|title=Encyclopedia of crime and punishment. Volume 1, Volume 1|date=2002-01-01|publisher=Sage Publications|isbn=978-0761922582|location=Thousand Oaks, Ca.|language=English|oclc=51883999|url-access=registration}}</ref> the International Conference on Penal Abolition (ICOPA) gathers activists, academics, journalists, and \"others from across the world who are working towards the abolition of imprisonment, the penal system, carceral controls and the prison industrial complex (PIC),\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.actionicopa.org/|title=actionICOPA :: The International Conference on Penal Abolition|website=www.actionicopa.org|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> to discuss three important questions surrounding the reality of prison abolition ICOPA was one of the first penal abolitionist conference movements, similar to Critical Resistance in America, but \"with an explicitly international scope and agenda-setting ambition.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/pdfviewer/pdfviewer?sid=ba78d840-bf7d-4fce-babe-fbd928d6ba5f@sessionmgr4007&vid=2&hid=4205|title=The moving targets of penal abolitionism: ICOPA, past, present and future.|last=|first=|date=|website=eds.a.ebscohost.com|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-28}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nAnarchists wish to eliminate all forms of [[State (polity)|state]] control, of which [[imprisonment]] is seen as one of the more obvious examples. Anarchists also oppose prisons given that statistics show incarceration rates affect mainly poor people and [[ethnic minorities]], and do not generally rehabilitate criminals, in many cases making them worse.<ref>National Advisory Commission on Criminal Justice Standards and Goals (US). A National Strategy to Reduce Crime. [https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/Digitization/54466NCJRS.pdf National Advisory Commission on Criminal Justice Standards and Goals], 1973. p. 358</ref> As a result, the prison abolition movement often is associated with humanistic socialism, [[anarchism]] and [[anti-authoritarian]]ism.\n\nIn October 2015, members at a plenary session of the [[National Lawyers Guild]] (NLG) released and adopted a resolution in favor of prison abolition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nlg.org/nlg-adopts-resolution-supporting-prison-abolition/|title=NLG Adopts Resolution Supporting Prison Abolition|date=2015-12-17|newspaper=National Lawyers Guild|access-date=2016-11-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://commons.commondreams.org/t/national-lawyers-guild-adopts-resolution-supporting-prison-abolition/16567|title=National Lawyers Guild Adopts Resolution Supporting Prison Abolition|date=2015-12-17|website=The Commons {{!}} Common Dreams|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref>\n\n== Mental illness and prison ==\nPrison abolitionists such as Amanda Pustilnik take issue with the fact that prisons are used as a \"default asylum\" for many individuals with mental illness.<ref name=\"def\">Pustilnik, Amanda. 2005. \"Prisons of the Mind: Social Value and Economic Inefficiency in the Criminal Justice Response to Mental Illness.\"The Journal of Criminal Law and Criminology.96(1): 217\u2013265.</ref> \n<blockquote>\n\"Why do governmental units choose to spend billions of dollars a year to concentrate people with serious illnesses in a system designed to punish intentional lawbreaking, when doing so matches neither the putative purposes of that system nor most effectively addresses the issues posed by that population?\"<ref name=\"def\" />\n</blockquote> To rephrase, if the whole point of the penal system is to rehabilitate and reform individuals who have willingly transgressed, then those who transgress the law for reasons outside their cognitive control don't belong in prison since prisoners were never designed nor intended to rehabilitate this population.\n\nIn the United States, there are more [[Mentally ill prisoners in the United States|people with mental illness in prisons]] than in psychiatric hospitals.<ref name=\"def\" />   This statistic is one of the major pieces of evidence that prison abolitionists claim highlights the depravity of the penal system.\n\nPrison abolitionists contend that prisons violate the Constitutional rights (5th and 6th Amendment rights) of mentally ill prisoners on the grounds that these individuals will not be receiving the same potential for rehabilitation as the non-mentally ill prison population.  This injustice is sufficient grounds to argue for the abolishment of prisons.<ref name=\"def\" /><ref name=\"def\" /><ref name=\"ment\">Rollin, Henry. 2006. \"The Mentally Ill Should Be in Hospital, not in Jail.\" ''The Journal of Forensic Psychiatry and Psychology''. 17(2): 326\u2013329.</ref><ref name=\"harvard\">Harvard Law Review. February 2008. \"Developments in the Law: The Law of Mental Illness.\" ''Harvard Law Review''. 121(4):1114\u20131191.</ref> Prisons were not designed to be used to house the mentally ill, and prison practices like solitary confinement are awful for mental health. Additionally, individuals with mental illnesses have a much higher chance of committing suicide while in prison.<ref name=\"sui\">Ahmed, Mukhtar. Bowen, Andy. and Graham, Tanya. et al. 2007. /ref> \"The Identifications and Management of Suicide Risk in Local Prisons.\" ''Journal of Forensic Psychiatry and Psychology''. 18(3): 368\u2013380.</ref>\n\n== Arguments made for prison abolition ==\n\n* Lack of proper legal representation\n:\"Eighty percent of people accused of crimes [in the [[United States]]] are unable to afford a lawyer to defend them.\"<ref name=\"Wright 2003. p.6\">Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 6.</ref> The [[US Supreme Court]] held in 1963 that a poor person facing felony charges \"cannot be assured a fair trial unless counsel is provided for him.\"\n:\"Long Term Neglect and underfunding of indigent defense have created a crisis of extra ordinary proportions in many states throughout the country.\"<ref name=\"Wright 2003. p.6\" />\n* War on drugs conceals racial tension\n:(2005) \"The United States leads the world in the number of people incarcerated in federal and state correctional facilities. There are currently more than 2 million people in American prisons or jails. Approximately one-quarter of those people held in U.S. prisons or jails have been convicted of a drug offense. The United States incarcerates more people for drug offenses than any other country. With an estimated 6.8 million Americans struggling with drug abuse or dependence, the growth of the prison population continues to be driven largely by incarceration for drug offenses.\"<ref>Justice Policy Institute, \"Substance Abuse Treatment and Public Safety,\" (Washington, DC: January 2008), p. 1.\nhttp://www.justicepolicy.org/images/upload/08_01_REP_DrugTx_AC-PS.pdf</ref>\n:\"The so-called drug war was started in the 1980s and it was aimed directly at the black population. None of this has anything to do with drugs. It has to do with controlling and criminalizing dangerous populations.\"<ref>Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 56.</ref>\n:\"Blacks are 12.3 percent of the U.S. population (2001) but they comprise fully half of the roughly 2 million Americans currently behind Bars. On any given day, 30 percent of African-American males aged 20\u201329 are \"under correctional supervision\".<ref>Herivel and Wright, ''Prison Nation''. Routledge, 2003. p. 31.</ref>\n:Blacks constitute 13 percent of all drug users, but 35 percent of those arrested for drug possession, 55 percent of persons convicted, and 74 percent of people sent to prison.<ref>http://www.fff.org/comment/com0303e.as{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* Incarceration is socially and economically crippling to the convicted and the community.\n:\"Each Prisoner represents an economic asset that has been removed from that community and placed elsewhere. As an economic being, the person would spend money at or near his or her area of residence\u2014typically, an inner city. Imprisonment displaces that economic activity: Instead of buying snacks in a local deli, the prisoner makes those purchases in a prison commissary. The removal may represent a loss of economic value to the home community, but it is a boon to the prison [host] community. Each prisoner represents as much as $25,000 in income for the community in which the prison is located, not to mention the value of constructing the prison facility in the first place. This can be a massive transfer of value: a young male worth a few thousand dollars of support to children and local purchases is transformed into a $25,000 financial asset to a rural prison community. The economy of the rural community is artificially amplified, the local city economy is artificially deflated.\"<ref>Clear, Todd. \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.497.3373&rep=rep1&type=pdf Backfire: When Incarceration Increases Crime]\". in The Unintended consequences of Incarceration. New York: Vera Institute of Justice, January 1996</ref>\n\n:Unfortunately, there are no definitive national statistics on the employment status of felons. But both anecdotal evidence and fragmentary data confirm what common sense would predict: individuals who have been incarcerated have great difficulty securing employment when they return to society. Except for a short period in the late 1990s, when the labor market was so tight that the Wall Street Journal reported on employer efforts to reach out to felons, those leaving prison have faced formidable obstacles to employment. Some of these difficulties are related to company policies or procedures and others are the result of employer perceptions of felons' job skills or trustworthiness. Felons are also barred from public employment in a number of states, including three with a high proportion of African American residents (Alabama, Mississippi, and South Carolina). Occupations that are licensed by states also have restrictions on allowing felons to work in them.<ref>Margaret C. Simms, \"JOINT CENTER FOR POLITICAL AND ECONOMIC STUDIES\" MAY/JUNE 2004 p. 7\"</ref>\n* It is argued by the Massachusetts Statewide Harm Reduction Coalition that the prison system is in violation of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/universal-declaration-human-rights/index.html|title=Universal Declaration of Human Rights {{!}} United Nations|date=2015-10-06|website=www.un.org|access-date=2016-11-26}}</ref> which was adopted by the [[United Nations General Assembly]] in 1948, and which is prescribing life, liberty, equality and justice to all people without discrimination of any sort as an inalienable right.<ref>http://www.massdecarcerate.org/download/HumanRights.doc</ref> The Universal Declaration of Human Rights has also abolished all forms of slavery and genocide, including torture, repression and oppression that prisons thrive upon.\n* Imprisonment is seen by some as a form of violent behavior which legitimizes violence and cruelty, producing a \"boomerang effect of dehumanization\"<ref>http://peaceconsortium.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/01/Jakopovich.pdf Daniel Jakopovich, The Humanist Defense and Critique of the South African Truth and Reconciliation Commission, ''Peace Studies Journal'', Vol.4, Issue1, 2011</ref> on the society which dehumanizes itself and limits its potential for a peaceful future by resorting to the use of such repressive and cruel institutions.\n* Prisons may be less effective at discouraging crimes and/or compensating victims than other forms of punishment.<ref>Andrews and Bonta, 2003{{Title missing|date=September 2010}}{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}</ref>\n* Degree and quality of access to justice depends on the financial resources of the accused.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tyler|first=Tracey|url=https://www.thestar.com/article/245548|title=Access to justice a 'basic right'|date=August 12, 2007|work=The Star|accessdate=May 22, 2010|location=Toronto}}</ref><ref>[http://www.pili.org/en/content/view/126/26/ Public Interest Law Institute \u2013 Indigent Defense Systems in the United States<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{Dead link|date=August 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n* Prisons [[Social alienation|alienate]] people from their [[Community|communities]].\n* In the U.S., [[people of color]] and from the [[American lower class|lower class]] are much more likely to be imprisoned than people of European descent or people who are wealthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/prisons.htm|title=Prison population statistics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002081754/http://www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs/prisons.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive -->|archivedate=2007-10-02|accessdate=2007-10-04}}</ref>\n* People who are put in prison for what are arguably crimes motivated by need, such as some minor theft (food, etc.) or prostitution, find it much harder to obtain legal employment once convicted of a crime. Arguably, this difficulty makes it more likely they will find themselves back in the prison system, having had few other options or resources available to support themselves and/or their families.{{citation needed|date=February 2008}} Many prison abolitionists argue that we should \"legalize survival\" and provide help to those who need it instead of making it even harder to find work and perpetuating the non-violent crimes.\n* Prisons are not proven to make people less violent. In fact, there is evidence that they may instead promote violence in individuals by surrounding them with other violent criminals, which can lead to predictable negative/violent results.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/news/special_reports/prisons/violence.html|title=Mother Jones|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229105512/http://www.motherjones.com/news/special_reports/prisons/violence.html|archive-date=2008-12-29|access-date=2018-07-09}}</ref>\n* Drug-related offenders are being ushered in and out of the prison system like a revolving door. Rather than educate, and rehabilitate the offender to a clean path of sobriety and increased stature, the state ignores them.\n\n== Arguments made against prison abolition ==\nOpponents of the abolition argue that none of the arguments above address the protection of non-criminal population from the effects of crime, and from particularly violent criminals.\n* Prisons provide protection for broader society from those within who are judged likely to reoffend.\n* Individuals who have committed crimes, especially crimes violent in nature, must repay society. Retributive philosophy argues that punishment is necessary in order for an individual who has done wrong to pay for their crime<ref>Cottingham, John. \u201cVarieties of Retribution.\u201d The Philosophical Quarterly, vol. 29, no. 116, 1979, pp. 238\u2013246. JSTOR, JSTOR, www.jstor.org/stable/2218820.</ref>\n* [[Utilitarianism|Utilitarian ethics]] with happiness as its utility argues that the unhappiness of few is good or right if it leads to the happiness of the majority. The ethical argument in this case is that keeping 1% of the population incarcerated is worth it for the happiness of the majority, depending on the amount of unhappiness the 1% suffers by being incarcerated and inflicts on society by being free.\n* Deterrence theory makes the case that prison discourages citizens from committing a crime, because they would not want to end up in prison<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Incarceration|first1=Committee on Causes Consequences of High Rates of|url=https://www.nap.edu/read/18613/chapter/7#131|title=The Growth of Incarceration in the United States|last2=Justice|first2=Committee on Law and|last3=Education|first3=Division of Behavioral Social Sciences and|last4=Council|first4=National Research|year=2014|isbn=978-0-309-29801-8|doi=10.17226/18613}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed reforms and alternatives ==\nProposals for prison reform and alternatives to prisons differ significantly depending on the political beliefs behind them. Proposals and tactics often include{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}:\n\n* Penal system reforms:\n** Substituting, for incarceration, supervised release, [[probation]], [[restitution]] to victims, and/or community work.\n** Decreasing terms of imprisonment by abolishing [[Mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentencing]]\n** Decreasing ethnic disparity in prison populations\n* Prison condition reforms\n* Crime prevention rather than punishment\n* Abolition of specific programs which increase prison population, such as the [[prohibition of drugs]] (e.g., the American [[War on Drugs]]), [[gun control]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}, prohibition of [[sex work]], and [[prohibition|alcohol restrictions]]{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}.\n* Education programs to inform people who have never been in prison about the problems\n* Fighting individual cases of [[wrongful conviction]]\n\nThe [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] published a series of handbooks on criminal justice. Among them is [http://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/Handbook_of_Basic_Principles_and_Promising_Practices_on_Alternatives_to_Imprisonment.pdf Alternatives to Imprisonment] which identifies how the overuse of imprisonment impacts fundamental human rights, especially those convicted for lesser crimes.\n\nSocial justice and advocacy organizations such as Students Against Mass Incarceration (SAMI) at the [[University of California, San Diego]] often look to Scandinavian countries Sweden and Norway for guidance in regard to successful prison reform because both countries have an emphasis on rehabilitation rather than punishment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ucsdguardian.org/2013/12/02/the-breakthrough-of-students-against-mass-incarceration/|title=The Breakthrough of Students Against Mass Incarceration {{!}} UCSD Guardian|last=Staff|first=Guardian|access-date=2016-11-28}}</ref> According to Sweden's Prison and Probation Service Director-General, Nils \u00d6berg, this emphasis is popular among the Swedish because the act of imprisonment is considered punishment enough.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/nov/26/prison-sweden-not-punishment-nils-oberg|title=Prison is not for punishment in Sweden. We get people into better shape|newspaper=The Guardian|last1=James|first1=Erwin|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=2014-11-26}}</ref> This focus on rehabilitation includes an emphasis on promoting normalcy for inmates, a charge lead by experienced criminologists and psychologists.<ref name=\"The Atlantic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2013/09/why-scandinavian-prisons-are-superior/279949/|title=Why Scandinavian Prisons Are Superior|website=The Atlantic|last1=Larson|first1=Doran|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=2013-09-24}}</ref> In Norway a focus on preparation for societal re-entry has yielded \"one of the lowest recidivism rates in the world at 20%, [while] the US has one of the highest: 76.6% of [Americans] prisoners are re-arrested within five years\".<ref name=\"Business Insider\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/why-norways-prison-system-is-so-successful-2014-12|title=Why Norway's prison system is so successful|website=Business Insider|last1=Sterbenz|first1=Christina|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> The Scandinavian method of incarceration seems to be successful: the Swedish incarceration rate decreased by 6% between 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/dec/01/why-sweden-closing-prisons|title=Why is Sweden closing its prisons?|newspaper=The Guardian|last1=James|first1=Erwin|accessdate=15 November 2016|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Abolitionist views ===\nMany prison reform organizations and abolitionists in the United States advocate community accountability practices, such as community-controlled courts, councils, or assemblies as an alternative to the criminal justice system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackandpink.org/purpose-analysis/|title=Purpose and Analysis \u2013 black and pink|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOrganizations such as [[Incite!|INCITE!]] and Sista II Sista that support women of color who are survivors of interpersonal violence argue that the criminal justice system does not protect marginalized people who are victims in violent relationships. Instead, victims, especially those who are poor, minorities, transgender or gender non-conforming can experience additional violence at the hands of the state.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Arrested Justice: Black Women, Violence, and America's Prison Nation|last=Richie|first=Beth E.|publisher=New York University Press|year=2012|isbn=|location=New York, NY|pages=17}}</ref> Instead of relying on the criminal justice system, these organizations work to implement community accountability practices, which often involve collectively-run processes of intervention initiated by a survivor of violence to try to hold the person who committed violence accountable by working to meet a set of demands.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rojas Durazo|first=Ana Clarissa|date=2011\u20132012|title=Community Accountability: Emerging Movements to Transform into Violence|url=|journal=Social Justice: A Journal of Crime, Conflict & World Order|volume=37|issue=4|pages=|via=}}</ref>\nFor organizations outside the United States see, e.g. [http://www.justiceaction.org.au Justice Action, Australia].\n\nSome anarchists and socialists contend that a large part of the problem is the way the judicial system deals with prisoners, people, and capital.  According to Marxists, in capitalist economies incentives are in place to expand the prison system and increase the prison population. This is evidenced by the creation of private prisons in America and corporations like CoreCivic, formerly known as Correction Corporation of America (CCA). http://www.cca.com/ \n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/mar/03/prison-population-titan-jails|title=George Monbiot: This revolting trade in human lives is an incentive to lock people up|last=Monbiot|first=George|date=2009-03-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-10-18|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\nIts shareholders benefit from the expansion of prisons and tougher laws on crime. More prisoners is seen as beneficial for business. Some anarchists contend that with the destruction of capitalism, and the development of social structures that would allow for the self-management of communities, property crimes would largely vanish. There would be fewer prisoners, they assert, if society treated people more fairly, regardless of gender, color, ethnic background, sexual orientation, education, etc.\n\nThe demand for prison abolition is a feature of [[anarchist criminology]], which argues that prisons encourage recidivism and should be replaced by efforts to rehabilitate offenders and reintegrate them into communities.<ref>{{cite encyclopaedia|first=Jeff|last=Ferrell|title=Anarchist Criminology|encyclopaedia=Encyclopedia of Criminological Theory|editor-first1=Francis T.|editor-link1=Francis T. Cullen|editor-last1=Cullen|editor-first2=Pamela|editor-last2=Wilcox|doi=10.4135/9781412959193.n11|publisher=[[SAGE Publishing]]|year=2010|page=45}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Angela Davis]]\n* [[Convict lease]] system, abolished by Presidential order in 1942\n* [[Emma Goldman]]\n* [[Fay Honey Knopp]]\n* [[Exile]]\n* [[Frankie Boyle]]\n* [[Louk Hulsman]]\n* [[Mentally ill people in United States jails and prisons]]\n* [[Nils Christie]]\n{{col-break}}\n* [[Penal labor]]\n* [[Restorative justice]]\n* [[Thomas Mathiesen]]\n* [[Prison-industrial complex]]\n* [[Transformative justice]]\n* [[Pacifism]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n== References ==\n* Livio Ferrari/Massimo Pavarini (eds.) NO Prison. European Group Press. London 2018.\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Incarceration}}\n\n[[Category:Criminal justice reform]]\n[[Category:Penal imprisonment]]\n[[Category:Prison abolition movement| ]]\n", "name_user": "Wikiedits5891", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAdvocates of prison abolition", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prison_abolition_movement"}
{"title_page": "Sword of Honour (2001 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2001 British television drama film}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sword of Honour\n| image          =Sword_of_Honour_(2001_TV_film).jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Bill Anderson\n| producer       = Gillian McNeill\n| writer         = [[Evelyn Waugh]] (novel)<br />[[William Boyd (writer)|William Boyd]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Daniel Craig]]<br>[[Megan Dodds]]<br>[[Katrin Cartlidge]]\n| music          = [[Nina Humphreys]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|2001}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Sword of Honour''''' is a 2001 British television film directed by Bill Anderson and starring [[Daniel Craig]]. Scripted by [[William Boyd (writer)| William Boyd]], it is based on the ''[[Sword of Honour]]'' trilogy of novels by [[Evelyn Waugh]],<ref name=\"Morris\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/jan/02/tvandradio.television1 |title=Declaration of Waugh |last=Morris |first=Mark |date=2 January 2001 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Keegan\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1312995/TV-adaption-of-Waughs-war-is-off-target.html|title=TV adaption of Waugh's war is off target |last=[[John Keegan| Keegan, John]] |date=3 January 2001 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref> which loosely parallel Waugh's own experiences in the [[Second World War]]. \n\n==Reception==\nCommenting in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', its Defence Editor, [[John Keegan]], said: \"To reduce Waugh's enormous text to a short television treatment presented William Boyd with a daunting challenge. He has met it magnificently... Boyd's compressions improve Waugh's plot. At the literary level, therefore, Boyd passes all the tests. The failure is at the directorial level. Bill Anderson has either simply not grasped or has flinched from depicting how utterly different the Britain of 1939-45 is from Tony Blair's. His lack of grasp or nerve has affected his actors&nbsp;\u2013 though some of them may also be guilty of not having immersed themselves in the books, inexcusably, since Waugh is the most readable of novelists. As a result, characters appear either as caricatures or as pale approximations of Waughian realities\".<ref name=\"Keegan\" />\n\n==Filming locations==\nEdinburgh was one of the locations for filming.<ref name=\"Film Edinburgh\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmedinburgh.org/Filmed-Here/Sword-of-Honour |title=Sword of Honour  |website=Film Edinburgh |access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title| tt0273021}}\n\n{{William Boyd}}\n{{Evelyn Waugh}}\n\n[[Category:2001 television films]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Evelyn Waugh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Screenplays by William Boyd]]\n\n\n{{UK-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2001 British television drama film}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Sword of Honour\n| image          =Sword_of_Honour_(2001_TV_film).jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        = \n| director       = Bill Anderson\n| producer       = Gillian McNeill\n| writer         = [[Evelyn Waugh]] (novel)<br />[[William Boyd (writer)|William Boyd]]\n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Daniel Craig]]<br>[[Megan Dodds]]<br>[[Katrin Cartlidge]]\n| music          = [[Nina Humphreys]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|2001}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n}}\n'''''Sword of Honour''''' is a 2001 British television film directed by Bill Anderson and starring [[Daniel Craig]]. Scripted by [[William Boyd (writer)| William Boyd]], it is based on the ''[[Sword of Honour]]'' trilogy of novels by [[Evelyn Waugh]],<ref name=\"Morris\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/jan/02/tvandradio.television1 |title=Declaration of Waugh |last=Morris |first=Mark |date=2 January 2001 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Keegan\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1312995/TV-adaption-of-Waughs-war-is-off-target.html|title=TV adaption of Waugh's war is off target |last=[[John Keegan| Keegan, John]] |date=3 January 2001 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref> which loosely parallel Waugh's own experiences in the [[Second World War]]. \n\n==Reception==\nCommenting in ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'', its Defence Editor, [[John Keegan]], said: \"To reduce Waugh's enormous text to a short television treatment presented William Boyd with a daunting challenge. He has met it magnificently... Boyd's compressions improve Waugh's plot. At the literary level, therefore, Boyd passes all the tests. The failure is at the directorial level. Bill Anderson has either simply not grasped or has flinched from depicting how utterly different the Britain of 1939-45 is from Tony Blair's. His lack of grasp or nerve has affected his actors&nbsp;\u2013 though some of them may also be guilty of not having immersed themselves in the books, inexcusably, since Waugh is the most readable of novelists. As a result, characters appear either as caricatures or as pale approximations of Waughian realities\".<ref name=\"Keegan\" />\n\n==Filming locations==\nEdinburgh was one of the locations for filming.<ref name=\"Film Edinburgh\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.filmedinburgh.org/Filmed-Here/Sword-of-Honour |title=Sword of Honour  |website=Film Edinburgh |access-date=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title| tt0273021}}\n\n{{William Boyd}}\n{{Evelyn Waugh}}\n\n[[Category:2001 television films]]\n[[Category:Films based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by Evelyn Waugh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Screenplays by William Boyd]]\n[[Category:British television films]]\n\n{{UK-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sword_of_Honour_(2001_film)"}
{"title_page": "List of Virtual Boy games", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Virtual-Boy-Set.jpg|thumb|right|A Virtual Boy console with its controller]]\nThe [[Virtual Boy]] is a [[History of video game consoles (fifth generation)|32-bit]] [[Tabletop game|tabletop]] [[video game console]] developed and designed by [[Nintendo]], first released in [[Japan]] on July 21, [[1995 in video gaming|1995]] and later in [[North America]] on August 14 of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/22/business/introduction-by-nintendo.html|title=Introduction by Nintendo|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707203354/https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/22/business/introduction-by-nintendo.html|archive-date=2018-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The following list contains all of the games released for the Virtual Boy.\n\nOriginally unveiled at Nintendo's [[Nintendo Space World|Shoshinkai Show]] in Japan on November 15, [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] and at [[Consumer Electronics Show|Winter CES]] in North America on January 6, 1995,<ref name=\"Boyer\">Boyer, Steven. \"A Virtual Failure: Evaluating the Success of Nintendos Virtual Boy.\" Velvet Light Trap.64 (2009): 23-33. ProQuest Research Library. Web. May 24, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetvb.com/modules/advertising/?r17|title=Nintendo introduces video game players to three-dimensional worlds with new virtual reality video game system \u00ab Press Releases \u00ab Planet Virtual Boy|publisher=planetvb.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628124825/https://www.planetvb.com/modules/advertising/?r17|archive-date=2018-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref> it was never intended to be released in its final form but Nintendo pushed the Virtual Boy in its unfinished state to market so that it could focus development resources on the then-upcoming [[Nintendo 64]] and arrived later than other 32-bit systems such as the [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[Sega Saturn]] but at a lower price,<ref>{{cite book|title=Game Over: How Nintendo Zapped an American Industry, Captured Your Dollars, and Enslaved Your Children|title-link=Game Over (book)|last1=Sheff|first1=David|last2=Eddy|first2=Andy|author-link=David Sheff|publisher=GamePress|year=1999|others=[https://books.google.com/books?id=b_N5FzzD3hsC&printsec=frontcover online]|isbn=978-0-9669617-0-6|oclc=26214063}}</ref><ref>KEVIN RAFFERTY, IN T. \"Super Mario Takes Leap into Three Dimensional Space.\" The Guardian (pre-1997 Fulltext): 0. November 16, 1994. ProQuest. Web. July 8, 2013.</ref> retailing at [[US$]]179.95 but in mid-[[1996 in video gaming|1996]], [[Blockbuster LLC|Blockbuster]] was selling Virtual Boy units at $50 each.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Q|first=The|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_086.pdf&page=34|title=Gaming Gossip|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=86|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=September 1996|page=34|access-date=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720194925/https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_086.pdf&page=34|archive-date=2018-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Benj|last=Edwards|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3050016/unraveling-the-enigma-of-nintendos-virtual-boy-20-years-later|title=Unraveling The Enigma Of Nintendo's Virtual Boy, 20 Years Later|date=August 21, 2015|work=Fast Company|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707231258/https://www.fastcompany.com/3050016/unraveling-the-enigma-of-nintendos-virtual-boy-20-years-later|archive-date=July 7, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Boyer\"/><ref>{{cite book|ref=CITEREFKent2002|last=Kent|first=Steven L.|authorlink=Steven L. Kent|title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: The Story Behind the Craze that Touched our Lives and Changed the World|date=2002|publisher=Random House International|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7615-3643-7|oclc=59416169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTrcTeAqeaEC&printsec=frontcover|pages=513\u2013515, 518, 519, 523, 524|access-date=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709060608/https://books.google.com/books?id=PTrcTeAqeaEC&printsec=frontcover|archive-date=2017-07-09|url-status=live}}</ref>{{rp|513}}\n\nThe system was overwhelmingly panned by critics and was deemed as a [[List of commercial failures in video gaming|commercial failure]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Lisa Foiles|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/2796-Top-5-Hardware-Super-Fails|title=Top 5 Hardware Super Fails &#124; Top 5 with Lisa Foiles Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist|publisher=Escapistmagazine.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707201630/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/2796-Top-5-Hardware-Super-Fails|archive-date=2018-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> selling only 770,000 units before being discontinued both in Japan and North America on {{dts|1995|12|22}} and March 2, 1996 respectively,<ref>{{cite web|last=Snow|first=Blake|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/111823/the-10-worst-selling-consoles-of-all-time-page-2-of-2/|title=The 10 Worst-Selling Consoles of All Time|accessdate=2018-07-20|publisher=[[GamePro]].com|date=May 4, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905175411/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/111823/the-10-worst-selling-consoles-of-all-time-page-2-of-2/|archivedate=September 5, 2008}}</ref> making it the second lowest-selling console by Nintendo after the [[64DD]] and its marketing campaign was commonly thought of as a failure.<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Geoff|last2=Krzywinska|first2=Tanya|year=2006|title=Tomb Raiders and Space Invaders : Videogame Forms and Contexts}}</ref> Several additional titles were announced to be released for the Virtual Boy at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3 1996]], but ultimately they were never released due to the system\u2019s discontinuation by Nintendo themselves, as were several localizations that were only released in one region.<ref name=\"Boyer\"/>{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} The system was never released in [[Europe]].\n\n== Games ==\nListed here are all '''{{table row counter|id=softwarelist|ignore=2}}'''{{efn|This number is always up to date by this [[Template:Table row counter|script]].}} officially released Virtual Boy games. Of these, eight titles were exclusive to Japan and three to North America. A number of games were either announced or already in development before ultimately being canceled including ''[[Bound High!]]'', ''[[Dragon Hopper]]'', and ''[[Zero Racers]]''.<ref name=\"Boyer\"/>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Regions released\n!scope=\"col\"|Region description\n!scope=\"col\"|Released\n|-\n![[North America]]\n|North America and other [[NTSC]] territories.\n|14\n|-\n![[Japan]]\n|Japan, Hong Kong and other [[NTSC-J]] territories.\n|19\n|}\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" id=\"softwarelist\" width=\"auto\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Title<ref name=\"lovbgN2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/doc/vb_games.pdf|title=Virtual Boy Games|format=PDF|publisher=Nintendo of America|accessdate=2008-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061202093110/http://www.nintendo.com/doc/vb_games.pdf|archivedate=2006-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"lovbgbig.N9\">{{cite magazine|last=Seidel|first=F.|url=https://www.planetvb.com/modules/articles/?s017110003|title=Feature: Der verlorene Sohn - Alle erschienenen Spiele auf einen Blick|magazine=[[:de:Wii Magazin|big.N]]|issue=9|publisher=LiveEmotion Verlag|date=July\u2013August 2000|page=20|lang=de}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Genre(s)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Developer(s)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Publisher(s)\n! 