\"/> No prototype has surfaced.\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: left;\"| '''''[[Worms (1995 video game)|Worms]]'''''\n| Artillery, Strategy\n| [[Team17]]\n| [[Ocean Software]]\n| {{date|2008}}\n| No actual development started on Virtual Boy version due to the commercial and critical failure of the platform.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=|url=https://archive.org/stream/MicromaniaTerceraEpocaSpanishIssue8#page/n57/mode/1up|title=Reportaje: Extra\u00f1a mezcla... de gusanos - Worms|magazine=[[Microman\u00eda]]|volume=3|issue=8|publisher=HobbyPress|date=September 1995|page=58|lang=es}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Radke|first=Christian|url=https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|title=Worms|website=planetvb.com|date=2019|access-date=2019-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529195248/https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|archive-date=2019-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! id=\"Z\" style=\"text-align: left;\"| '''''[[Zero Racers]]'''''\n| Racing\n| Nintendo\n| Nintendo\n| {{date|1998-10}}\n| Also known as ''G-Zero''. Artwork and screenshots exists.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_111.pdf&page=66|title=Nintendo 64 Previews: F-Zero X - G-Zero|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=111|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=October 1998|page=64}}</ref> No prototype has surfaced.\n|}\n{{Compact ToC|name=no|center=yes|top=yes|num=yes|seealso=no|nobreak=yes}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lists of video games]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.mobygames.com/browse/games/virtual-boy/list-games/ List of Virtual Boy games] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n{{Portal bar|1990s|Video games}}\n{{Virtual Boy}}\n{{Video game lists by platform}}\n\n[[Category:Nintendo-related lists]]\n[[Category:Video game lists by platform|Virtual Boy]]\n[[Category:Virtual Boy games|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Virtual-Boy-Set.jpg|thumb|right|A Virtual Boy console with its controller]]\nThe [[Virtual Boy]] is a [[History of video game consoles (fifth generation)|32-bit]] [[Tabletop game|tabletop]] [[video game console]] developed and designed by [[Nintendo]], first released in [[Japan]] on July 21, [[1995 in video gaming|1995]] and later in [[North America]] on August 14 of the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/22/business/introduction-by-nintendo.html|title=Introduction by Nintendo|website=Nytimes.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707203354/https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/22/business/introduction-by-nintendo.html|archive-date=2018-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> The following list contains all of the games released for the Virtual Boy.\n\nOriginally unveiled at Nintendo's [[Nintendo Space World|Shoshinkai Show]] in Japan on November 15, [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] and at [[Consumer Electronics Show|Winter CES]] in North America on January 6, 1995,<ref name=\"Boyer\">Boyer, Steven. \"A Virtual Failure: Evaluating the Success of Nintendos Virtual Boy.\" Velvet Light Trap.64 (2009): 23-33. ProQuest Research Library. Web. May 24, 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetvb.com/modules/advertising/?r17|title=Nintendo introduces video game players to three-dimensional worlds with new virtual reality video game system \u00ab Press Releases \u00ab Planet Virtual Boy|publisher=planetvb.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628124825/https://www.planetvb.com/modules/advertising/?r17|archive-date=2018-06-28|url-status=live}}</ref> it was never intended to be released in its final form but Nintendo pushed the Virtual Boy in its unfinished state to market so that it could focus development resources on the then-upcoming [[Nintendo 64]] and arrived later than other 32-bit systems such as the [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer]], [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] and [[Sega Saturn]] but at a lower price,<ref>{{cite book|title=Game Over: How Nintendo Zapped an American Industry, Captured Your Dollars, and Enslaved Your Children|title-link=Game Over (book)|last1=Sheff|first1=David|last2=Eddy|first2=Andy|author-link=David Sheff|publisher=GamePress|year=1999|others=[https://books.google.com/books?id=b_N5FzzD3hsC&printsec=frontcover online]|isbn=978-0-9669617-0-6|oclc=26214063}}</ref><ref>KEVIN RAFFERTY, IN T. \"Super Mario Takes Leap into Three Dimensional Space.\" The Guardian (pre-1997 Fulltext): 0. November 16, 1994. ProQuest. Web. July 8, 2013.</ref> retailing at [[US$]]179.95 but in mid-[[1996 in video gaming|1996]], [[Blockbuster LLC|Blockbuster]] was selling Virtual Boy units at $50 each.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Q|first=The|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_086.pdf&page=34|title=Gaming Gossip|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=86|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=September 1996|page=34|access-date=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720194925/https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_086.pdf&page=34|archive-date=2018-07-20|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Benj|last=Edwards|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3050016/unraveling-the-enigma-of-nintendos-virtual-boy-20-years-later|title=Unraveling The Enigma Of Nintendo's Virtual Boy, 20 Years Later|date=August 21, 2015|work=Fast Company|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707231258/https://www.fastcompany.com/3050016/unraveling-the-enigma-of-nintendos-virtual-boy-20-years-later|archive-date=July 7, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Boyer\"/><ref>{{cite book|ref=CITEREFKent2002|last=Kent|first=Steven L.|authorlink=Steven L. Kent|title=The Ultimate History of Video Games: The Story Behind the Craze that Touched our Lives and Changed the World|date=2002|publisher=Random House International|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7615-3643-7|oclc=59416169|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PTrcTeAqeaEC&printsec=frontcover|pages=513\u2013515, 518, 519, 523, 524|access-date=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170709060608/https://books.google.com/books?id=PTrcTeAqeaEC&printsec=frontcover|archive-date=2017-07-09|url-status=live}}</ref>{{rp|513}}\n\nThe system was overwhelmingly panned by critics and was deemed as a [[List of commercial failures in video gaming|commercial failure]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Lisa Foiles|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/2796-Top-5-Hardware-Super-Fails|title=Top 5 Hardware Super Fails &#124; Top 5 with Lisa Foiles Video Gallery &#124; The Escapist|publisher=Escapistmagazine.com|accessdate=2018-07-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180707201630/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/videos/view/top-5-with-lisa-foiles/2796-Top-5-Hardware-Super-Fails|archive-date=2018-07-07|url-status=live}}</ref> selling only 770,000 units before being discontinued both in Japan and North America on {{dts|1995|12|22}} and March 2, 1996 respectively,<ref>{{cite web|last=Snow|first=Blake|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/111823/the-10-worst-selling-consoles-of-all-time-page-2-of-2/|title=The 10 Worst-Selling Consoles of All Time|accessdate=2018-07-20|publisher=[[GamePro]].com|date=May 4, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905175411/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/111823/the-10-worst-selling-consoles-of-all-time-page-2-of-2/|archivedate=September 5, 2008}}</ref> making it the second lowest-selling console by Nintendo after the [[64DD]] and its marketing campaign was commonly thought of as a failure.<ref>{{cite book|last1=King|first1=Geoff|last2=Krzywinska|first2=Tanya|year=2006|title=Tomb Raiders and Space Invaders : Videogame Forms and Contexts}}</ref> Several additional titles were announced to be released for the Virtual Boy at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3 1996]], but ultimately they were never released due to the system\u2019s discontinuation by Nintendo themselves, as were several localizations that were only released in one region.<ref name=\"Boyer\"/>{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} The system was never released in [[Europe]].\n\n== Games ==\nListed here are all '''{{table row counter|id=softwarelist|ignore=2}}'''{{efn|This number is always up to date by this [[Template:Table row counter|script]].}} officially released Virtual Boy games. Of these, eight titles were exclusive to Japan and three to North America. A number of games were either announced or already in development before ultimately being canceled including ''[[Bound High!]]'', ''[[Dragon Hopper]]'', and ''[[Zero Racers]]''.<ref name=\"Boyer\"/>\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" width=\"auto\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Regions released\n!scope=\"col\"|Region description\n!scope=\"col\"|Released\n|-\n![[North America]]\n|North America and other [[NTSC]] territories.\n|14\n|-\n![[Japan]]\n|Japan, Hong Kong and other [[NTSC-J]] territories.\n|19\n|}\n</center>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" id=\"softwarelist\" width=\"auto\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Title<ref name=\"lovbgN2006\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/doc/vb_games.pdf|title=Virtual Boy Games|format=PDF|publisher=Nintendo of America|accessdate=2008-07-20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061202093110/http://www.nintendo.com/doc/vb_games.pdf|archivedate=2006-12-02|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"lovbgbig.N9\">{{cite magazine|last=Seidel|first=F.|url=https://www.planetvb.com/modules/articles/?s017110003|title=Feature: Der verlorene Sohn - Alle erschienenen Spiele auf einen Blick|magazine=[[:de:Wii Magazin|big.N]]|issue=9|publisher=LiveEmotion Verlag|date=July\u2013August 2000|page=20|lang=de}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Genre(s)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Developer(s)\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Publisher(s)\n! colspan=\"2\" | Release date\n|-\n! Japan\n! North America\n|-\n\n<!-- #, 0, 0-9, 1, 1-9 -->\n! id=\"0\u20139\" style=\"text-align: left;\"